<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Interest Rates Debated  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- It seemed so clear two weeks ago. The head of the
European Central Bank indicated an interest rate increase was just
around the corner, aimed at putting the brakes on inflation in the
11 countries that use the euro.
</P>
<P>
   But with the euro's nosedive against the dollar this week, those
at the ECB's meeting today are in a bit of a bind. Raising rates
now -- the same week the euro hit a new all-time low since its
launch last year -- could be interpreted as panicking. Not doing
anything at all could make them look like they don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are split on when the rate hike will come. Last week,
the feeling was that the bank would hold off until its next meeting
in early May. But with the euro's drop to below 93 cents for the
first time in a steep selloff Tuesday that saw it dip as low as
91.62 cents, more market watchers now feel the bank will move
sooner rather than later to bump up its benchmark lending rate,
currently at 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Petra Koehler, a senior economist at Dresdner Bank, said she
expects a quarter-point rate increase, which would come on the back
of a similar increase in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some time distance now from the last step,'' she said,
adding that inflation figures have also edged slightly over 2
percent -- the ECB's top limit under its own rules for keeping
prices stable.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Schubert, an economist at Commerzbank, said raising
rates now gives the impression that the ECB is trying to stop the
euro's plunge -- something it really can't control through interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reacting to this instantaneously would create the impression
in the markets that you react nervously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of the ECB buying euros to prop up the
currency, although that also isn't seen as a long-term solution for
the currency's woes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is almost imperative,'' said Neil Parker, chief economist
at the Royal Bank of Scotland. ''You need the ECB to step in and
stop the decline before it gets out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro has plunged almost 23 percent since January 1999, when
it was launched amid hopes that it would one day rival the dollar
as a global reserve currency.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about interest rates, experts still say the
real reason for the euro's decline remains Europe's sluggishness on
streamlining its economy and the unstoppable U.S. economic
juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason for the euro's fall is the very bad sentiment about
what is happening structurally in Euroland, compared with what is
happening in the United States,'' Commerzbank's Schubert said. ''If
that sentiment doesn't change, there will be no change in the
direction of the euro-dollar rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The weak currency has been particularly worrisome to British
companies that export to continental Europe or compete with imports
priced in euros.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederation of British Industry released a quarterly
survey Wednesday showing that exports among Britain's manufacturers
have fallen, with more companies recording a downturn in overseas
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Americans investing in shares of European companies also are
taking a beating. Swelling regional stock valuations look a lot
less impressive once those shares are converted from euros into
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Xetra Dax index of blue-chip shares listed on the
Frankfurt stock exchange has increased by 7.8 percent since the
start of the year. The Paris CAC 40 stock index has risen 4.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, after euro-denominated shares are converted into
dollars, the Xetra Dax index showed no increase for the year, while
the Paris CAC 40 actually lost 2.9 percent of its value in dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
