<HEADLINE> Sex Molest Suspect Jumps Off Bridge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAUSALITO, Calif. (AP) -- A man suspected of molesting a child
jumped off the Golden Gate Bridge Wednesday as police chased and
tried to arrest him, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers were waiting for Brian Alexander Ward, 39, near the
Sausalito home where he worked as a gardener. He was suspected of
molesting a 4-year-old boy who lived at the house and faced three
counts of lewd and lascivious acts with a child, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward spotted officers and fled in his truck, according to
Sausalito police. He was pursued by Marin County sheriff's deputies
and by Sausalito and Mill Valley officers.
</P>
<P>
   When he got onto the bridge, heading toward San Francisco, he
crossed into oncoming traffic, got out of the car and jumped into
the water.
</P>
<P>
   The tide was running out to the Pacific and Ward's body was not
found. Falls from the bridge are nearly always fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Ward was a high-risk sex offender with previous
convictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
