<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemala Marks Bishop's Murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- With a march and masses, human rights
groups and the Roman Catholic Church marked the second anniversary
of the still-unsolved killing of Bishop Juan Gerardi.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 people marched Wednesday from the crypt where
Gerardi is buried in Guatemala's Metropolitan Cathedral to a nearby
church where a bronze plaque bearing his image was unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Mission in Guatemala, which helped oversee peace
accords that put an end to the nation's 36-year civil war, issued a
statement calling Gerardi ''one of the most outstanding defenders
of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerardi, 75, was bludgeoned to death in his home April 26, 1998,
two days after he delivered a report blaming Guatemala's military
for the vast majority of the atrocities in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration has grown with the slow pace, and frequent
interruptions, in the investigation of his killing.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, a recently emerged witness implicated a former
presidential guard. Gilberto Gomez told a judge that former guard
Jose Obdulio Villanueva checked himself out of the prison where the
two men were held on the day of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva, a convicted murderer, had been a prime suspect but
was released after he claimed he was in jail in another city at the
time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Mission stressed ''the existence of new evidence about
the possible involvement in the crime of people linked to illegal
or underground security agencies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
