<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Storage Program Moving Slow  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MacDONALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- A program intended to help farmers find more
room for their grain may not be in place in time for many of them
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Stofferahn, North Dakota's director of the federal Farm
Service Agency, said officials do not expect the farm storage
facility loan program to be set up until at least early June. He
worries that may be too late for most North Dakota farmers to take
advantage of it this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody is pushing really hard to get it going, but
the process of moving such a program forward takes a lot of time,''
Stofferahn said. ''And that may end up being frustrating for some
farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agriculture Department is resurrecting the farm storage
facility loan program, which enables farmers to get low-interest
government loans to build new grain storage facilities on their
farms.
</P>
<P>
   The program was discontinued 18 years ago after studies found
enough storage available. But the USDA said that has changed and
the need for new storage facilities is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Without enough storage space, farmers must sometimes sell crops
when commodity prices are low rather than hanging on to the crops
until prices recover.
</P>
<P>
   ''Judging from the calls we've received in our offices and from
what I've heard elsewhere in the country, I think there is a really
sizable demand for the program out there right now,'' Stofferahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said earlier this
month that the department is working on rules for the program and
expected to issue them in time for this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   But the USDA has already come under fire from some lawmakers for
not moving quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Witnesses and members of a federal trade
panel disagreed among themselves over trade issues Wednesday, in a
hearing on whether wide-open markets or a more cautious approach
would be best for American agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Harry Cleberg, Farmland Industries chairman and chief
executive officer, told members of the U.S. Trade Deficit Review
Commission that American farmers need the help of a normal trade
relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to approve permanent normal trade relations, Cleberg
said during a hearing at the Federal Reserve Bank, would mean that
''we will have done nothing to redress our trade deficit with China
and, worse, we will damage our reputation as a reliable supplier of
goods and services to China and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan said development of export
markets was crucial because his state's farm economy was
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is backing a bill in the House that
would bring China into the World Trade Organization and make
China's normal trade status with the United States permanent.
Currently, China's trade status is reviewed each year.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill that the House is expected to take up next month
would ensure China the low-tariff access to U.S. markets that other
trading partners enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   But committee member C. Richard D'Amato, a Maryland state
legislator, praised what he called the ''radical'' idea that the
U.S. should enforce its existing trade pacts before entering any
new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is one of four to be held around the country. The
committee will report to the White House and Congress after the
hearings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
