<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Candidate Calls for Reforms  </HEADLINE>
By SUZAN FRASER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's main presidential candidate is
calling for democratic reforms and the right to free expression,
proposals that could anger the nation's powerful military.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmet Necdet Sezer is running against 10 candidates in the first
round of presidential elections in parliament today, but already
has received the backing of all the parties in parliament. Turkish
presidents are elected by parliament and no other candidate has any
party backing, leaving Sezer's election a near certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer, chief justice of the constitutional court, Turkey's
highest court, has called for reforms to the constitution drawn up
during the 1980-1983 military rule, saying it restricts basic
rights and freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   He also has questioned the military's annual purge of officers
suspected of links with Islamic groups or political parties. The
decisions are made behind closed doors and the sacked officers have
no right of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, which Turkey hopes to join, is likely to be
pleased with Sezer's nomination, which came about after intense
bargaining between Turkey's main parties. So is the far-right
Nationalist Action Party, a key member of the governing coalition,
which has strong support among the religious.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit appears relieved that his coalition
government found a compromise candidate and avoided a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Virtue Party, which faces being banned for
threatening Turkey's secular regime, has praised Sezer's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Sezer's candidacy was announced, Virtue experienced the
greatest happiness,'' wrote Emin Colasan, a commentator for
Hurriyet newspaper. ''Sezer is a democracy victory for Virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   That has raised fears that Sezer may not support the military's
relentless fight against what the generals call one of Turkey's
greatest threats, political Islam.
</P>
<P>
   None of Turkey's top generals attended a reception earlier this
week hosted by Sezer, sparking speculation that the powerful
military was not happy with his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''According to some, the new presidential candidate is not as
secular and republican as he is made out to be,'' said Bekir
Coskun, who also writes for Hurriyet.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit rushed to Sezer's defense Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chief of Staff and the Turkish Armed Forces are highly
sensitive to the issue of secularism,'' Ecevit said. ''There won't
be any problems on that aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports have claimed that Virtue is also supporting
Sezer in the hope that when he leaves the court his seat will be
filled by his deputy, who is reputed to be close to the Islamic
party.
</P>
<P>
   That also might anger the military, which regards itself as the
guarantor of the nation's secular system. The army has seized power
three times since 1960 and once forced an Islamic party from power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
