<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 03:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trader Rubdowns Rise in Popularity  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The Dow is falling and voices are rising on the
trading floor at Adams, Harkness, and Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Equity trading director Ben Marsh is shouting ''At 20~ I'm a
buyer!'' and ''Smith Barney's hitting it!'' across the trading room
floor. The daily wave of stress is about to crash.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Jim Kilcoyne is on duty. He's an onsite massage
therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ''Up higher, on the back of my neck,'' Marsh tells him during a
brief pause in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Practitioners of onsite chair-massage say the recent stock
market volatility has ratcheted up stress and been a boon for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, some of which subsidize the costs, get more relaxed
employees. And Kilcoyne and his fellow massage therapists get
access to their dream demographic: highly stressed people with
money to burn.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a 15-minute rubdown,'' said Marsh, who brought the idea
to Adams, Harkness and Hill's Boston office when he moved from New
York. ''It's like a boxer going back to his corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoyne -- oddly the only man in the trading room in a tie on
Wednesday -- unfolds a portable stand that props up Marsh at his
desk. A hole in the mask allows Marsh to breathe and see normally,
and he keeps right on trading through the rubdown. It's the closest
thing to a break he can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Once Kilcoyne finishes with Marsh, other traders get their
chance. The cost is $1 a minute.
</P>
<P>
   At the adjacent desk, trader Jeanne McCloskie said she hoped to
indulge later in the day, but only if she wasn't too busy to enjoy
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The uncertainty of the markets can make you crazed,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoyne is a laid-back, low-stress kind of guy. But after
realizing that a lot of other people aren't, he's making a pretty
good living off them. He hits several companies a week, sometimes
for as long as eight straight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Atkinson likewise says her Boston business, Backbeat, has
boomed amid the recent market volatility. She got into the onsite
massage business three years ago after several years of ''on the
table'' massage work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think with all the mergers, people are just being asked to
do an unreasonable amount of work under a lot of pressure,'' said
Atkinson, who has several employees and said she often works from 7
a.m. until 11 p.m. ''In many cases, they don't even know whether
they're going to have a job next month.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Kier, an onsite massage therapist in suburban Chicago,
has added several new brokerage clients over the last two months,
during which the Dow and the Nasdaq recorded their wildest point
swings in history on record volume.
</P>
<P>
   ''A massage helps them deal with it better, because it releases
endorphins, which are the body's natural painkillers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there's been only a little friendly competition in the
budding industry. The companies refer clients to each other when
their schedules don't fit.
</P>
<P>
   Intense competition, Atkinson said, ''isn't good karma.''
</P>
<P>
   More intense competition may be inevitable, though.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson said she regularly is called by curious strangers
looking to get into the business, and she's thinking of
franchising. There are few overhead expenses, so entrepreneurs face
few hurtles going into the business for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kilcoyne said there's no real reason to worry about the
client pool drying up.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's so much stress out there, there's no real reason to be
cutthroat,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 0340 </TRAILER>
