<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed lower Thursday following an
overnight retreat on Wall Street and ahead of a long holiday in
Japan. The dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 115.14 points,
or 0.63 percent, to close at 18,019.17 at the end of daily trading.
On Wednesday, the average closed down 138.02 points, or 0.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was trading at 106.30 yen on the Tokyo foreign
exchange market Thursday, up 0.42 yen from late Wednesday and above
its late New York level of 106.27 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, Tokyo investors remained cautious about
prospects for the U.S. stock market. The U.S. Commerce Department
was to release the nation's gross domestic product for the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors can't move before seeing U.S. data later Thursday,''
said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also reluctant to buy on concern that U.S. stocks
could drop sharply during Japan's ''Golden Week,'' a series of
upcoming holidays over that virtually shuts the country down,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 179.32 points
to 10,945.50 at Wednesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index
closed at 3,630.09 points, down 81.14.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section closed down 23.67 points, or 1.42 percent, to
1,644.22. The TOPIX closed up 2.61 points, or 0.16 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange
totaled an estimated 542.31 million shares, down from 551.86
million shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader market, the number of declining shares
overwhelmed advancers broadly. On the TSE First Section, 955 issues
fell, with 307 issues closing higher and 122 unchanged from
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, traders said some foreign investors bid up
the greenback against the yen in an attempt to cover losses in U.S.
stocks by selling Japanese shares.
</P>
<P>
   But trading was moderate ahead of the release of major economic
data in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar traded between 106.03 yen and 106.42 yen in Tokyo on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 97.98 yen, up from
97.60 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was
unchanged from Wednesday's finish at 1.7350 percent. Its price
remained at 100.55.
</P>
</TEXT>
