<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: Medical Privacy Laws Needed  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Health industry officials say congressional
action, and not regulations being proposed by the administration,
is the key to assuring confidentiality in the treatment of medical
records.
</P>
<P>
   At Senate health committee hearings Wednesday, witnesses argued
that rules drawn up by Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala were both not tough enough in protecting individual rights
and too tough in restricting the flow of information needed to
ensure that people get the best health care.
</P>
<P>
   ''The regulations are a good effort,'' said Charles Kahn III,
president of the Health Insurance Association of America. But
''their shortcomings point to why it's vitally important for
Congress to pass confidentiality legislation that protects both
consumers' medical records and their ability to receive
high-quality health care.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 health care law required Congress to approve medical
privacy legislation by August 1999 or, if that didn't happen,
compel the health secretary to draw up administrative rules.
</P>
<P>
   Led by health committee chairman Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., and
ranking Democrat Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, the Senate neared
a compromise last year but couldn't resolve differences over the
right to sue companies that violate privacy rights and privacy for
teen-agers getting abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala proposed the new regulations last November. After
receiving public comment, she is to announce the final rules later
this year. They would go into effect in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The rules limit disclosure of medical information to the
''minimum necessary,'' give patients the right to see their medical
records, require health care providers to write privacy contracts
with their business partners, and pre-empt weaker state privacy
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses before Jeffords' panel concurred with the aims of the
new rules but took issue with some of the details.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said the ''minimum necessary'' standard for divulging
information was too narrow and ''would have a chilling effect on
detecting and reporting (medical) errors.''
</P>
<P>
   From a different perspective, Janlori Goldman, director of the
Health Privacy Project at Georgetown University, said the rules
give too little weight to individual rights because people can't
control the use and disclosure of health information used for
treatment, payment and health care operations.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Farmer, representing the Washington Business Group on
Health, said the rule on pre-empting weaker state laws was too
confusing, and without a uniform federal code ''the functioning and
administration of employer health-related programs could be placed
in serious jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joanna Horobin, speaking for the Biotechnology Industry
Organization, said too many restrictions on access to important
data ''will severely hurt medical research.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Hospital Association's John Houston also warned
that the rules could drive up health care costs and said the
''minimum necessary'' standard was too stringent. ''This is
completely at odds with good medical practice and is potentially
very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Others noted that Shalala was limited in what she could impose
without congressional action. The rules cover only health care
providers, health plans and clearinghouses and apply only to
electronic data, not the paper records that make up most health
information.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congressional action would protect all health information,
however it is transmitted and wherever it exists,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Health Privacy Project: http://www.healthprivacy.org
</P>
<P>
   American Hospital Association testimony:
http://www.aha.org/ar/testimony4-26-00.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 0619 </TRAILER>
