<DOCNO> APW20000427.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 06:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minorities a Key Target for Census  </HEADLINE>
By DARA AKIKO WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Es Nuestro Futuro. Hagase Contar.
</P>
<P>
   That's Spanish for, ''nov yog peb lub caij nyoog yav tom ntej.
Tsis txhob tso nws tseg,'' which is Hmong for ''oja przysztosc. Nie
zawieszaj,'' which in Polish means ''This is our future. Don't
leave it blank.''
</P>
<P>
   These multilingual campaigns and the Census Bureau's first big
push to team with community groups are credited for a high response
rate in many California cities with ethnic minority populations
considered difficult to count.
</P>
<P>
   A tally showing exact response rates from different groups won't
be available until December, but mail-in numbers in several
California cities with large ethnic minority populations, such as
Modesto, Santa Ana, Compton and Anaheim, exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably one of the better and broader and most
consistent efforts I've seen,'' said Frank Berry, the Los
Angeles-based regional director for the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   A similar trend wasn't noticeable outside California. A check of
14 other cities nationwide with large or a majority of ethnic
minority population -- including Chicago, Atlanta and Tucson -- shows
that they fell short of their mail-in target rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think California got the message they lost billions of
dollars in federal aid targeted to these low-income communities
that were significantly undercounted in 1990. I think (legislators)
were determined to not let that happen again,'' said Phil Sparks, a
spokesman for Census 2000 Initiative, a nonpartisan group that
provides agencies with census data.
</P>
<P>
   California could lose $5 billion in federal money over the next
10 years if there is an inaccurate count in urban counties,
according to a federal study released in March.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, about 900,000 people in California weren't counted,
most of them ethnic minorities, census officials said. That cost
the state some $2.2 billion in federal funds over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the state dedicated $24.7 million to get a
more accurate count, including spending $8.7 million on
multilingual forums and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In previous tallies, many ethnic minorities didn't realize the
importance of the census, and were suspicious of how the data were
used and how private the information stays, census officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Hortencia Arias, 45, is among those who didn't fill out
the 1980 or 1990 census form. An undocumented immigrant in
south-central Los Angeles, she feared it would adversely affect her
residency application.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau is prohibited by law from sharing individual
information, even with other government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of my ignorance in the past I hurt myself and the
community,'' said Hortencia, who is now a legal U.S. resident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see the schools and how many children there are and not
enough teachers. And you'll go to the hospital and so many people
need attention and there's not enough doctors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Census Bureau took a much more active role in
reaching out to community groups. It stressed confidentiality, the
importance of minority representation in the redrawing of political
districts and the availability of federal funds for everything from
transportation to education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Besides posting fliers and billboards in multiple languages,
including Thai, Creole, Russian, Tagalog and Chinese, the bureau
and community groups held workshops and offered toll-free hot lines
to help answer questions about the census.
</P>
<P>
   Forms were also available in five languages other than English
and the bureau offered assistance guides in more than 40 languages.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, the Mexican-American Legal Defense and
Education Fund started a nationwide campaign -- going to schools,
union halls and community meetings to encourage people to fill out
the census. MALDEF also produced bilingual training booklets and
videos and commercials using prominent Latinos, including boxer
Oscar De La Hoya and talk show host Cristina Saralegui.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was also remarkable that this go around, a lot of elected
officials stressed the importance of the census,'' said Margaret
Leal-Sotelo, MALDEF's national census director. ''All those things
were very, very helpful. And that everyone had the same focus --
that this is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The mail-in deadline has passed and enumerators will begin today
visiting those who failed to return the forms.
</P>
<P>
   Loc Vu, the longtime director of the Indochinese Resettlement
and Cultural Center in San Jose, said more people have come to him
this year with questions about the census, a sign that they want to
be counted.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in Asian-language media has helped, too. Twenty years
ago, there were no radio or television stations broadcasting in
Vietnamese, while today there are several, including a 24-hour
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lot of ways to reach out to our community by our own
language. That's the big difference,'' Vu said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   Mexican-American Legal Defense and Education Fund:
http://www.maldef.org
</P>
</TEXT>
