<HEADLINE> Taxpayers' Electronic Filing Rises  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The returns are in: Americans by the millions
are embracing technology when they prepare and file income taxes.
There were impressive increases this year in electronic filing,
credit card payments and direct bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released Wednesday by the Internal Revenue Service
show that people are growing increasingly comfortable with doing
their own taxes on home computers. The number of self-prepared
electronic returns received as of last Friday doubled to more than
4.9 million compared with the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The total of 35 million electronic returns -- most of them filed
by professional preparers -- was 1.4 million more than the IRS had
expected and represented a 20 percent increase over last year.
Electronically filed returns now make up 27 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are more used to computers,'' IRS Commissioner Charles
Rossotti said. ''Secondly, the software is getting very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Working toward a goal of 80 percent electronic filing by 2007,
the IRS has been aggressively promoting the advantages, such as
fewer mistakes and much faster processing of refunds. Rossotti said
the agency will continue expanding the number of taxpayers who can
use identification numbers in place of the signature form that is
still required for most who file electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little thing but it is still a barrier,'' Rossotti
said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, about 7 million taxpayers used the electronic
signature option, including 1.4 million who did their own returns.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has asked Congress to approve a $10 tax credit
for people who file electronically, which would cover the cost of
most electronic filing services. The IRS is also working with
industry on ways to allow people to prepare and file their taxes on
the Internet at no cost, Rossotti said.
</P>
<P>
   About 186,000 taxpayers have charged $536 million in taxes on
their American Express, Mastercard and Discover cards so far this
year. Both are huge increases over 1999, when about $184 million
was charged on credit cards in the first year of the program.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 200 percent increase in the number of people who
paid taxes through direct debits from bank accounts and 25 percent
more people had their refunds deposited directly, the IRS reported.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this growth, an older piece of technology remained a
problem for the IRS. About 65 percent of all telephone calls have
gotten through so far this year, up from last year's dismal 50
percent level but far from adequate, despite 24-hour, 7-day
service, Rossotti said.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti wants Congress to approve a 9.5 percent budget increase
that will enable the IRS to hire about 2,000 more employees for
customer service and to reverse a steep slide in enforcement. In
both cases, he said, technology will never fully replace people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people who are trying to pay, we want them to get through
and get the help they need,'' Rossotti said. ''If they don't want
to pay, we don't want them to be able to shift the tax burden onto
their neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   IRS: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
