<HEADLINE> Clinton To Address Memorial Service  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The memory of civil rights leader Daisy
Bates stands tall in the eyes of President Clinton. He was just 11
when she counseled nine black students who strode into an all-white
high school here and inched America toward desegregated schools.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the president was addressing a memorial service for
Bates, who died Nov. 4 at the age of 84 after a lifetime of civil
rights work.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Bates died, Clinton said her death will ''leave a
vacuum in the civil rights community, the state of Arkansas and our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of her funeral, the president was in Washington
praising the courage of the black students, known as the Little
Rock Nine, as they accepted the Congressional Gold Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Whites rioted outside Central High School in 1957 when National
Guardsmen, on orders from Gov. Orval Faubus, turned the nine
students away. President Eisenhower sent in Army troops to escort
the students to class. It was a clear sign that Washington was
going to enforce the 1954 Supreme Court ruling in Brown v. Board of
Education that school segregation was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after their tense days at school, the nine black
students took solace at Bates' home. She was their mentor, advising
them how to stand up to intimidation and physical threats.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, Bates said: ''I'm 75 and a half. But I'm not
too tired to stand and do what I can for the cause I believe in. I
would like to see, before I die, that blacks and whites and
Christians can all get together.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wish is not yet reality.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visited Arkansas following a trip Wednesday to
Whiteville, N.C., where he stressed the need to enhance Internet
access across America, but especially in rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, he flew to Little Rock where he was
greeted at the airport by friends and local and state officials. He
briefly visited to the home of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's
mother and then dined on red snapper with cucumber salsa and
saffron rice with former U.S. Sens David Pryor and Dale Bumpers,
who met him at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also planned to speak today at a noon dedication of the
University of Arkansas at Little Rock Law School and later attend a
reception for the President's Committee on the Arts and Humanities
at the Arkansas Arts Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
