<DOCNO> APW20000427.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 06:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cartoons Go Three-Dimensional  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- From Superman to Batman, Popeye to Dick
Tracy, Hollywood has a long history of transforming comic-book and
cartoon characters into flesh and blood.
</P>
<P>
   The trend shows no sign of slowing, as studios prepare to bring
live-action versions of the Flintstones, the X-men, the Grinch and
Rocky and Bullwinkle to the big screen in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' kicks off the latest
round of cinematic cartoons when it opens Friday. The second
live-action movie about the modern stone age family, it recounts
the early romance of Fred and Wilma and Barney and Betty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a huge fan of the cartoon when I was kid,'' said Stephen
Baldwin, who plays Barney Rubble in the new flick. ''It's kind of
coincidental because Barney was my favorite character, because he
was seemingly the dopey guy who usually had the solution or answer
in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie co-stars Mark Addy as Fred, Kristen Johnston as Wilma,
Jane Krakowski as Betty and Joan Collins as Fred's mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Adaptations of two-dimensional characters pose a challenge for
filmmakers, who must try to satisfy fiercely loyal fans of the
originals while fleshing out the material for wider audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do our jobs right, audiences will love these characters
not just as cartoon characters but as people,'' said Brian Levant,
who directed the new Flintstones movie and its 1994 predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges facing the makers of ''X-men'' is dealing
with nearly 40 years of comic-book devotion to the intrepid band of
mutants.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has been abuzz with chat and pre-emptive carping.
</P>
<P>
   Though many fans seem pleased with much of the casting --
particularly Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen as lead mutants
Professor X and Magneto, respectively -- there are some devotees who
have been critical of how characters look in the movie's trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very passionate people,'' said ''X-men'' director
Bryan Singer.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen even has his own ''X-men'' site where he provides
information about the film, dispels rumors and offers reassurances
that the movie will adhere to the comic book's spirit despite a
modern, more realistic look to the costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I caution people to wait and see the movie,'' McKellan said.
''If they don't like it, they should go make their own movie, or
just stay with the original comic.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing for your cartoon movie dollars this summer will be
''The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' featuring
computer-generated versions of the moose and flying squirrel.
Co-starring as their real-life nemeses are Robert De Niro as
Fearless Leader, Jason Alexander as Boris Badenov and Rene Russo as
Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   ''These characters are part of our pop culture,'' said ''Rocky
and Bullwinkle'' director Des McAnuff. ''It's great to revisit
them, and for people with fond memories of the characters, you
hopefully want to spend 90 minutes with them in a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming in time for the holidays will be ''Dr. Seuss' How the
Grinch Stole Christmas,'' starring Jim Carrey and directed by Ron
Howard, and ''102 Dalmatians,'' the second live-action flick based
on Disney's animated classic.
</P>
<P>
   In the works over the next few years are live-action takes on
other Marvel comics, including Spider-man and the Incredible Hulk.
Also planned is a live-action movie of Josie and the Pussycats,
based on the comic-book and cartoon series about an all-girl rock
band.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ''Flintstones'' movie site: http://www.vivarockvegas.com
</P>
<P>
   ''Rocky and Bullwinkle'' movie site:
http://rockyandbullwinkle.com
</P>
<P>
   ''X-men'' movie site: http://www.x-men-the-movie.com
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellen site: http://www.mckellen.com/cinema/xmen/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
