<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Body found in case of kidnapped computer expert  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRICK, N.J. (AP) -- Authorities found a body in the search for a
British computer expert who has been missing for ten days but
wouldn't confirm it was that of Paul Jeffrey Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Gale was abducted from his hotel room in Kentucky by a New
Jersey man upset because Gale was dating his former lover,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The agents have recovered a body. But we have not received
medical reports that it is the body of Paul Jeffrey Gale,'' said
Sandra Carrol, special agent and spokeswoman of the Newark FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Kentucky in a statement yesterday said the corpse
belonged to Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Carrol said the corpse was found yesterday at about 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of federal agents converged on a cul-de-sac at the end of
a road two miles from the home of Gregory J. Marcinski. Marcinski,
23, a volunteer emergency medical technician, was charged last week
in Kentucky with kidnapping Gale, who had been dating Marcinski's
ex-girlfriend. He also was charged with impersonating an FBI agent.
Federal court documents indicate Marcinski flashed an EMT badge and
computer-generated FBI credentials to gain access to Gale's room at
the Holiday Inn in Florence, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The British man's relatives, who came to the United States after
the man disappeared 10 days ago, were notified of the search.
</P>
<P>
   Gale, a 28-year-old Naples, Fla., resident, recently lived in
Mount Laurel, where he worked as a computer programmer for TRW
Integrated Supply. He was working for TRW in Kentucky this month as
a consultant in the merger of two pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gale was reported missing April 17 by a friend and business
associate.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Marcinski became enraged Gale had been dating
his ex-girlfriend and drove his grandmother's Buick 800 miles to
confront Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski identified himself as Special Agent ''Trimble'' and
handcuffed Gale before placing him in the front seat of the Buick
early morning on April 17, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale's girlfriend, Darla Guidie, who had previously dated
Marcinski, told the FBI that Marcinski made the fake ID on his
computer and ''bragged that he had gotten the format for the phony
FBI credentials off of the Internet,'' according to affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, a member of the Community First Aid Squad and a
self-employed computer technician, was arrested last August when
another ex-girlfriend told police he assaulted her and grabbed her
new boyfriend by the neck, pushing him to the floor, the Asbury
Park Press reported in today's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski was being held without bail in Trenton, awaiting
extradition to Kentucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
