<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower on
Thursday, triggered by the most recent decline in U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 115.14
points, or 0.6 percent, to close at 18,019.17, following
Wednesday's losses on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average slumped 179.32 points, or 1.6
percent, to 10,945.50 at Wednesday's close. The Nasdaq composite
index dropped 81.14 points, or 2.2 percent, to 3,630.09 points.
</P>
<P>
   Traders in Tokyo said investors were also hesitant to buy on
fear that U.S. stocks may fall more during an upcoming long holiday
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was recently quoted at
106.36 yen, up 0.48 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and above the
106.27 yen level from late Wednesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong shares fell on concerns that the United States may
raise interest rates on the back of strong economic growth. The
Hang Seng Index slipped 34.52 points, or 0.2 percent, to close at
15,192.87.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, brokers also attributed the drop in the Hang
Seng to ongoing bickering between Taiwan and China. Taiwan accused
the mainland on Wednesday of engaging in a new round of war games.
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE:
</P>
<P>
   MANILA: Philippine shares fell after the central bank raised key
rates ahead of an expected U.S. interest rate increase soon. The
30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index slid 19.30 points, or
1.2 percent, at 1,620.53.
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL: Korean shares tumbled on fears over the financial health
of the Hyundai group, one of the country's biggest chaebols. The
Korea Composite Stock Price Index, or Kospi, slumped 21.16 points,
or 3 percent, to 692.07, the lowest level since April 14.
</P>
<P>
   BANGKOK: Thai shares declined on expectation that the U.S. may
announce an interest rate hike, after the U.S. government releases
economic data later Thursday. The SET Composite Index slipped 1.20
points, or 0.3 percent, to 393.36.
</P>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares rose slightly on cautious
trading. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks,
edged up 5.25 points, or 0.6 percent, to 904.25.
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE: Shares rose as foreign fund managers snapped up
stocks made cheaper by recent market declines. The Straits Times
Index rose 42.92 points, or 2 percent, to 2,151.72.
</P>
<P>
   TAIPEI: Taiwan shares edged up marginally despite concerns over
China-Taiwan tension and unstable U.S. stocks. The Weighted Price
Index gained 5.99 points, or almost 0.1 percent, to 8,541.95.
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY: Australian shares fell, paced by blue-chip stocks, on
recent losses in the U.S. markets. The All Ordinaries Index lost
11.4 points, or 0.4 percent, to 3,073.1.
</P>
<P>
   WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares fell on investor caution due to
volatility in the markets in the U.S. and around the world. The
NZSE 40-capital index lost 10.90 points, or 0.5 percent, to
2,005.91.
</P>
</TEXT>
