<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Bank Raises Interest Rates  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The European Central Bank raised interest rates by
a quarter percentage point today for the 11 countries using the
beleaguered euro currency. The euro sank to a new low against the
U.S. dollar after the decision was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurt-based bank pushed its main lending rate up to 3.75
percent, along with raising its other two key rates by a
quarter-point.
</P>
<P>
   ECB leaders had indicated an interest rate hike was imminent,
but still analysts had been split on whether the 17-member
governing board would make a move this week or hold off until its
next meeting in early May. The bank last increased its rates by a
quarter-point March 16, and enacted an earlier quarter-point
increase on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had been conflicted by the euro's decline to new lows
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers said the bank had to be careful to avoid the
impression it was panicking after the euro hit a new record low of
91.62 cents on Tuesday. At the same time, other analysts said that
doing nothing would create the impression that the ECB doesn't
care.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has been in a downward spiral since its introduction
last year, plunging almost 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the ECB's rate decision, the euro hit a new record
low against the U.S. dollar of 91.5 cents, compared with 92.37
cents late Wednesday in New York and around 92.17 cents today in
Europe before the rate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB said it made the decision to continue ''its policy of
reacting to upside risks to price stability in the medium term in a
pre-emptive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank also stuck by its opinion that the euro's current
weakness contradicts the underlying strength of the European
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governing council discussed recent movements in the
exchange rates between the major currencies, including the recent
decline of the euro, and examined their possible implications for
price stability in the euro area,'' the bank said in a statement.
''The ECB judges that the present level of the euro does not
reflect the strong economic fundamentals of the euro area.''
</P>
<P>
   The ECB had earlier been insistent that the weakness of the euro
was not its concern. But as the euro has continued its dive, the
bank started to warn that the currency's fall was also becoming a
threat to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB acknowledged today that the euro's rate was a continuing
worry, saying it was concerned about ''upside risks to price
stability which, given the prospects for strong economic expansion,
arise from strong growth in monetary and credit aggregates, as well
as from the present level of the exchange rate of the euro.''
</P>
<P>
   The ECB's main goal is maintaining price stability, and it is
charged with keeping inflation under 2 percent under its own rules.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the EU statistical office said average inflation
in the euro-zone countries rose to 2.1 percent in March -- the
highest since the euro currency was launched Jan. 1, 1999. An
overheating economy can spur inflation, and raising interest rates
tends to cool things off by making it more expensive to borrow
money.
</P>
<P>
   EU politicians have also insisted that the euro's decline
reflects the strength of the U.S. economy. Still, analysts say that
a perceived stubbornness on the part of European economies to make
structural reforms has also added to the euro's woes.
</P>
<P>
   That's on top of the ECB also still working to gain respect.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier today, France's finance minister said a rate hike
wouldn't do anything to help the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my view, it isn't with a strong increase in interest rates
that we will solve this problem,'' Laurent Fabius said in an
interview with French radio station RTL.
</P>
<P>
   Showing market participants that the ''European economic
situation is improving strongly'' is the solution to the euro's
current weakness, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 0837 </TRAILER>
