<DOCNO> APW20000427.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Win British Mobile Phone Licenses  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Four established British phone companies and a
Canadian newcomer emerged today as the winners in an auction for
Britain's next generation of mobile phone licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, which reaped a $35.6 billion bonanza for the
British treasury, ended when NTL Mobile dropped out of the
competition after eight weeks and 150 rounds of bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called third generation licenses represent precious
slices of Britain's airwave spectrum and give the winners a stake
in what's expected to be the hottest segment of the wireless
market.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the licenses now in use, they will enable wireless
companies to send far more information to a cell phone,
transforming the device into a mobile personal computer that can
roam the Internet, display video and provide constant access to
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The winners include four established players in the British
market: British Telecommunications; Vodafone AirTouch; One2One
Personal Communications, which is owned by Germany's Deutsche
Telekom; and Orange 3G, a unit of Germany's Mannesmann that will be
sold when Vodafone acquires the German company.
</P>
<P>
   TIW UMTS (UK) of Canada won License A, the fifth and most
powerful of those being offered. The government's
Radiocommunications Agency reserved this license for a newcomer,
hoping to stimulate greater competition in the mobile phone market.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Secretary Stephen Byers said that the auction will ensure
that Britain maintains its position as a leader in wireless
communications and represents a vital step toward his goal of
making the country ''the best place in the world for e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The licenses, which take effect in 2002, are good for 20 years
and payable over the first 10 years. Bidding began on March 6, with
each company depositing just $158 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding far exceeded initial expectations and forced eight
of the original 13 bidders to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone paid the most for a license -- $9.5 billion -- followed
by final bids from TIW of $7.0 billion and Orange of $6.5 billion.
BT and One2One will each pay $6.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Grindle, an industry analyst at investment bank Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson, said the high cost of the licenses will
inevitably be reflected to some extent in the charges that the
companies assess their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The money doesn't stop there. They have to build up the
networks as well,'' he said, estimating that each of the five
winners will have to invest up to $4.7 billion on equipment and
services. ''It's a long-term game.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction has inspired Germany and other countries that are
planning to put their own third-generation licenses up for bid. The
larger size of Germany's population suggests the auction there
could exceed the size of Britain's.
</P>
<P>
   The treasury plans to use the proceeds to repay part of the
national debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 0928 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford To Pay $1M Clean Air Penalty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will pay a $1.1 million penalty as
part of a settlement of alleged violations of the Clean Air Act,
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's consent decree with the EPA and the Justice Department
covers the Wayne Assembly and Michigan Truck Assembly plants, both
in Wayne, and the Dearborn Assembly plant in Dearborn.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Ford must pay one-third of the $1.1 million
penalty to the federal government, one-third to the state and
one-third to Wayne County.
</P>
<P>
   The consent decree incorporates Ford's plan to close Dearborn
Assembly by Oct. 31 and move its operations to a new plant being
built next to the existing facility.
</P>
<P>
   It also acknowledges that Ford has obtained required permits,
installed pollution control equipment and taken other measures to
comply with clean air rules at Wayne Assembly and Michigan Truck
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a $12 million environmental project, Ford will
install a waterborne primer system at the new Dearborn Assembly
plant that will replace a previously permitted solvent-based primer
system.
</P>
<P>
   The new system is designed to significantly reduce emissions of
volatile organic compounds, which combine in the air with other
chemicals on warm, sunny days to form ground-level ozone, or smog,
the EPA said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Detroit area achieved the health-based standard for ozone
in March 1995 after being out of compliance since the 1970s,'' said
Bharat Mathur, director of EPA's regional Air and Radiation
Division.
</P>
<P>
   ''EPA's goal is to ensure that Detroit continues to have air
quality that meets this health-based standard.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left with Ford official Terry Bresnihan was
not immediately returned late Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
