<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Defy Daewoo Strike Order  </HEADLINE>
By JAE-SUK YOO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Defying the central labor union's call
for a full-scale strike, thousands of rank-and-file workers of
Daewoo Motor Co.'s second plant kept their assembly lines open
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The disobedience showed a deep crack in the months long struggle
by Daewoo union leaders against plans by creditor banks to sell the
ailing automaker to a foreign investor.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Daewoo's main plant in Bupyong west of Seoul have
been on partial or full-scale strikes since Feb. 15 to oppose the
planned sale. They fear mass layoffs under foreign ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Tuesday raided the main plant and arrested 20 labor
activists. All but seven were later released. Those under detention
included Chu Young-ho, the union's top leader and organizer of the
strike outlawed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the arrest of their leaders, 7,500 workers of the
main plant suspended all operations and pledged to step up
protests.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, 500 Daewoo workers tried to march to a district
police headquarters near their main plant. When blocked by riot
police, the workers hurled eggs and rocks into the compound.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of arrests.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tuesday police raid, the company's central labor union
ordered a full-scale strike which also should involve its second
plant in Kusan on the southwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   But 3,000 workers in Kusan ignored the order and kept their
assembly lines running.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Kunsan plant is only five years old and won't be affected
by foreign takeover, but the plant in Bupyong is over 30 years old
and may likely be closed,'' said Park Jin-ho, an official from
Daewoo's labor-management cooperation office.
</P>
<P>
   He said a foreign buyer would like to relocate the outdated
facilities in Bupyong to Kusan where land and other prices are
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo's main plant has an annual capacity of 500,000 vehicles
and its second plant can produce 30,000 vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo Motor, South Korea's third largest car firm, is in
financial trouble after its parent conglomerate, Daewoo Group,
collapsed under huge debts last year.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo's creditors have invited international bidding to sell
the carmaker to a foreign investor by September. General Motors
Corp. and Ford Motor Co. are reportedly the leading contenders in
the bidding called in February.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at South Korea's two other main carmakers -- Hyundai
Motor Co. and Kia Motors Corp. -- staged a one-week joint strike
early this month in support of Daewoo workers.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that foreign carmakers will encroach upon the local
market and sharpen competition. Hyundai, which took over Kia last
year, controls over 70 percent of the local market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1018 </TRAILER>
