<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced
this morning that he has prostate cancer and indicated the disease
could affect his plans to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was diagnosed yesterday with prostate cancer. It's a
treatable form of prostate cancer,'' said Giuliani, 55, whose
father died of the disease in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it would affect his run for the U.S. Senate against
Hillary Rodham Clinton, he said: ''I have no idea. ... I hope that
I'd be able to run, but the choice that I'm going to make is going
to be based on the treatment that's going to give me the best
chance to have a complete cure.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed on whether he would continue his campaign he said:
''I don't think it's fair to answer questions about the Senate race
right now. ... Should I do it? Would I be able to do it the right
way? I hope that's the case but I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Treatment options include radiation and chemotherapy. ''Some
forms of treatment would require taking some time off,'' he
acknowledged, but said he didn't expect it to be a significant
amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor smiled frequently during the announcement and joked
with reporters. Asked whether he would be nicer, he replied, ''No
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was diagnosed at an early stage,'' he said. ''It came about
as a result of taking a PSA (blood screening) test 2{ weeks ago.
The PSA was elevated. I took antibiotics for awhile. I went in for
a biopsy yesterday. The biopsy revealed several of the samples, not
all, not most, were indicative of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made the announcement a day after he was seen leaving
Mount Sinai Medical Center. He had undergone a second round of
tests for prostate cancer following an annual screening for the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer can be diagnosed early thanks to the PSA blood
test, and is considered highly curable if caught in a preliminary
stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
