<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Thursday, April 27, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless IPO Has Strong Start
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T's new wireless stock didn't fly to the sky
like an IPO in the good old days just months ago, but at least Ma
Bell found enough buyers to sell a mammoth $10 billion worth of
stock in its latest offspring. Shares of the new AT&AMP;T Wireless
Group, created through the biggest initial public offering in U.S.
history, debuted on the open market today, bobbing higher from the
IPO price of $29.50 set last evening. In morning trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, where AT&AMP;T executives rang the opening bell,
the stock rose as high as $31.87{ before pulling back to $31\.
Despite concerns that Wall Street's foul mood might derail the IPO,
AT&AMP;T announced late yesterday that it was selling 360 million for a
total of $10.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wages, Benefits Jump 4.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. workers' wages and benefits rose by 4.3
percent in the 12 months ending in March, the fastest growth in pay
in eight years, the government said today. The increase in the
Labor Department's Employment Cost Index was up sharply from the 12
months ending in December, when wages and benefits rose by a more
moderate 3.4 percent. While higher wages and benefits are good news
for workers, economists are concerned that if companies pass on
rising labor costs to buyers of their products, it could trigger
higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economy Grows at 5.4 Percent Rate
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy, propelled by the biggest
jump in consumer spending in nearly 17 years, grew at a 5.4 percent
annual rate during the first three months of 2000, the government
said today. The increase in the gross domestic product -- the
country's total output of goods and services -- as measured by the
Commerce Department was weaker than the 6 percent rate many
analysts were expecting. Growth in the January-March quarter was
slightly slower than the breakneck 7.3 percent rate posted in the
last three months of 1999, the strongest showing in nearly 16
years. First-quarter growth was led by a whopping 8.3 percent rate
of increase in consumer spending -- the largest gain since a 8.6
percent rate posted in the second quarter of 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Jobless Claims Rise by 26,000
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department announced today that that
new claims for unemployment benefits rose by 26,000 to 283,000, the
biggest one-week increase since early February. Even with the rise,
weekly jobless claims remain at a level indicating labor markets
are the strongest they have been in decades. Jobless claims had
fallen the previous week to a 26-year low of 257,000.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports Push Stocks Lower
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in morning trading after an economic
report showed wage pressures are rising, but a broad selloff was
averted after a report on the gross domestic product showed
slightly lower-than-expected growth. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the
Dow industrials were down 143.34 at 10,802.16. On the NYSE,
decliners led advancers 1,620-781. The Nasdaq was down 3.15 at
3,626.94. Traders had nervously anticipated today's economic
reports, fearful that one or both would show that the economy was
growing much too fast for the Federal Reserve, resulting in another
interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial Figures;
Dow Industrials:        10802.16 - 143.34
NYSE Issues:         Advances  781  Declines 1620  Unchgd  519
NYSE Volume:         282,869,200
Most Active NYSE issue:         AT&AMP;T Wireless Grp 31\  UP 1} 
S&AMP;P 500:         1445.00 - 15.99
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          894.16  - 2.27
Nasdaq Composite Index:       3626.94  - 3.15
</P>
<P>
   European Bank Raises Interest Rates
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The European Central Bank raised interest rates by
a quarter percentage point today for the 11 countries using the
beleaguered euro currency that fell to a new all-time low against
the U.S. dollar earlier this week. The Frankfurt-based bank pushed
its main lending rate up to 3.75 percent and also raised its two
other key rates by a quarter percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon Reports $122 Million Loss
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Leading online retailer Amazon.com has reported
wider losses from a year ago even as revenues nearly doubled and
its customer base continued to expand. Amazon yesterday posted a
loss of $122 million, or 35 cents per share, on sales of $574
million. While revenues were up 95 percent over the $294 million
from the first quarter a year ago, losses deepened from $36
million, or 12 cents per share, a year ago. Analysts had predicted
a loss of 36 cents per share. Amazon said it gained 3.1 million new
customer accounts in the first three months of the year, increasing
its customer base to more than 20 million people. Amazon stock was
down 1 9/16 at 51 15/16 this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg Reports 1st Q Earnings Jump
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Despite slower cereal sales, Kellogg
Co. reported today a nearly 12 percent jump in its first-quarter
earnings, excluding restructuring charges. The report was in line
with Wall Street expectations. The cereal manufacturer said net
earnings during the January-March period climbed 11.9 percent to
$161.7 million from last year's $144.4 million. Earnings per share
during the same time were up 11 percent to 40 cents per share
compared to 36 cents per share a year ago. Analysts had projected
first-quarter earnings of 39 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna Earnings Beat Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc.'s first-quarter operating profits
leaped a better-than-expected 28 percent as the health insurance
company benefited from higher premiums and slightly lower medical
costs. Aetna said today it earned $184 million, or $1.29 per share.
That beat Wall Street expectations by 17 cents a share. Revenues
rose 39 percent to $7.9 billion from $5.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Asian Stock Markets Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower today,
triggered by the most recent decline in U.S. stocks. Japan's
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 115.14 points, or 0.6 percent,
to close at 18,019.17, following yesterday's losses on Wall Street.
Hong Kong shares fell on concerns that the United States may raise
interest rates on the back of strong economic growth. The Hang Seng
Index slipped 34.52 points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 15,192.87.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports this week:
</P>
<P>
   Employment cost index: up 4.3 percent over 12 months
</P>
<P>
   Gross domestic product: up at 5.4 percent rate in first quarter
</P>
<P>
   Jobless claims: up 26,000 to 283,000
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Personal income
</P>
