<HEADLINE> BMW Rejects Exec's Offer for Rover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- BMW on Thursday rejected an offer by
former Rover manager John Towers to take over the troubled British
automaker, saying it was ''financially not secured.''
</P>
<P>
   But talks with another group of British venture capitalists who
want to acquire Rover are proceeding and a decision is expected in
early May, the German luxury carmaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Towers, a former Rover chief executive who left the company in
1996, stepped in two weeks ago to make a rival bid for Rover to the
original offer by Alchemy Partners, a British venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   But BMW said Thursday it saw no basis for negotiations for
Towers in a statement implying that he lacked funds to sustain the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement followed a visit to BMW's Munich headquarters
by British labor union representatives, who believe Towers would
lay off fewer Rover workers than Alchemy would.
</P>
<P>
   British Industry Secretary Stephen Byers has also urged BMW to
consider the Towers bid.
</P>
<P>
   Towers' proposal reportedly would see Rover's Longbridge plant
losing perhaps only 1,500 of its 9,000 workers. Under the Alchemy
proposal, job losses could rise into the thousands.
</P>
</TEXT>
