<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Country Music Marathon Run Planned  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Ready, set, twang?
</P>
<P>
   With starting help from Vince Gill and Amy Grant, the Country
Music Marathon will be off and running Saturday with at least
10,000 competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''A perfect location for a theme marathon and a perfect location
for country music,'' said Tracy Sundlun of Elite Racing Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He would know. Sundlun and Elite Racing are the organizers
behind the Rock 'n' Roll Marathon in San Diego, which set the
record for the largest first-time marathon with 19,978 entries in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea for hitting Nashville came from some record
company executives who heard about that first Rock 'n' Roll
Marathon and wondered why not stage a music marathon in a town
known as Music City.
</P>
<P>
   ''They spoke to folks in the mayor's office here. They had some
representatives come out to the first marathon, and everybody's
eyes got lit up as to the possibilities,'' Sundlun said. ''It's a
natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming less than two weeks after the Boston Marathon, the
Country Music Marathon's field will feature 20 elite runners,
including Philip Chirchir of Kenya, whose personal best is 2 hours,
8 minutes and 51 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Grisales and Edgar Sanchez will be trying to land spots
on Colombia's Olympic team. Nadja Wijenberg, winner of the 1998
Rock 'n' Roll Marathon, also is entered.
</P>
<P>
   The 26.2-mile course winds near the Country Music Hall of Fame,
along Music Row and near the Ryman Auditorium, former home of the
Grand Ole Opry, with a variety of bands playing at 27 stages. Kenny
Rogers, Collin Raye and Linda Davis will perform Saturday night in
a concert open to both racers and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are trying to learn from mistakes made in San Diego
the past two years, when they ran out of water, had traffic
glitches and bands long gone by the time late racers passed.
</P>
<P>
   This time, 48 bands are lined up to play, and cheerleaders will
be placed along the course.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to be entertained,'' Sundlun said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
