<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM-NY--Gambling House Killings, 1st Ld-Writethru,0296  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A 21-year-old man was arraigned today on
charges he killed two men and critically wounded another during a
robbery at an illegal gambling house.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan C. Hunter, who was arrested Tuesday night in Auburn, 30
miles west of Syracuse, was charged with two counts of
second-degree murder and one count each of attempted murder and
robbery. He will appear again in City Court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter had a loaded handgun in his possession but surrendered
without incident, said Sgt. Joseph Sweeny. Police gave no other
details of Hunter's arrest because the investigation is still under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities accused Hunter of being among a group of masked
robbers who barged into Henderson Griffin's house in Syracuse
Friday night, shot three people and robbed the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's house was a popular neighborhood gambling spot. He had
been ticketed several times for selling alcohol and running games.
Local thieves knew about the high-stakes games, too, and the house
had been robbed before, including as recently as April 13, Sweeny
said.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in Friday's shootings were Griffin, 62, and another man,
Vernon Griffin, 39, no relation. Henderson Griffin was shot in the
legs but suffered a fatal heart attack. The third victim, Robert
Anderson, 47, remained in serious condition today at University
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Additional charges against Hunter will be considered when the
case is presented to a grand jury, said Chief Assistant District
Attorney Nicholas DeMartino. Charges could be increased to
first-degree murder under the state's 1995 death-penalty statute
because the crime involved multiple victims and occurred during a
robbery.
</P>
</TEXT>
