<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Civil Rights Leader  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The memory of civil rights leader Daisy
Bates stands tall in the eyes of President Clinton. He was just 11
when she counseled nine black students who strode into an all-white
high school here and nudged America toward desegregated schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'd like to say to you is that I really liked Daisy
Bates. I liked her for who she was. I liked her because she was a
brave woman who fought the civil rights battle,'' Clinton said
today at a memorial service for Bates, who died last year after a
lifetime of civil rights activism. ''But I liked her also because
she was a brave woman who kept her spirits up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Bates never lost her ability to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Daisy's getting a big kick out of us making such a
fuss about here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gospel music filled Robinson Auditorium where several hundred
people gathered to remember the woman, who received more than 200
awards for her work toward equality.
</P>
<P>
   Pianist Ricky Banks gave an emotional rendition of the civil
rights anthem, singing ''We shall overcome. We shall overcome,
yeah. ... Oooh, deep in my mind, I do, I do believe -- yes I do.
...''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you believe that?'' he asked the people in the crowd, who
responded with applause and then stood, joined hands, slowly swayed
and sang along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Gatson Bates died Nov. 4, 1999, at the age of 84. On the
day of her funeral, Clinton praised the courage of the nine black
students as they accepted the Congressional Gold Medal in
Washington. Some of the students, dubbed the Little Rock Nine, were
given a standing ovation at today's memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Whites rioted outside Central High School in 1957 when National
Guardsmen, on orders from Gov. Orval Faubus, turned the nine
students away. President Eisenhower sent in Army troops to escort
the students to class. It was a clear sign that Washington was
going to enforce the 1954 Supreme Court ruling in Brown vs. Board
of Education that school segregation was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after their tense days at school, the nine black
students took solace at Bates' home. She was their mentor, advising
them how to stand up to intimidation and physical threats.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, Bates said: ''I'm 75{, But I'm not too tired
to stand and do what I can for the cause I believe in. I would like
to see, before I die, that blacks and whites and Christians can all
get together.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wish is not yet reality.
</P>
<P>
   Her second cousin, David Neely, an attorney in Elmhurst, Ill.,
who was at the service with other relatives, said that in addition
to civil rights, Bates was vocal on issues involving children,
women and rape. Her mother was raped and murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Neely said Bates was a serious-minded woman, who liked to have
fun, but thrived on the discussion of issues. ''She loved to talk.
She loved attention,'' he said. ''Even after she had her first
stroke and her second stroke, her mind continued to work. But she
couldn't express herself because her speech was impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration announced today that it has begun a
process to designate Bates' home in Little Rock a National Historic
Landmark -- a structure that symbolizes an ''unflattering period in
our nation's history,'' Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Later today, Clinton was to speak at the dedication of the
William H. Bowen Law School for the University of Arkansas. Bowen,
a Little Rock attorney, businessman and former dean of the law
school, was chief of staff to Clinton when the president was
governor of Arkansas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1304 </TRAILER>
