<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reporter Gets OSCE Award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Russian journalist Andrei Babitsky,
who was arrested by the Russian military in Chechnya and held
captive for weeks, won a prestigious $20,000 prize Thursday for his
coverage of the war in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky ''has been one of the very few critical voices
commenting on the situation and recent developments in the
region,'' said the Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe, citing the 36-year-old correspondent for Radio Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's reporting on the conflict in Chechnya has been widely
recognized for its objectivity and fairness,'' said the OSCE in
awarding the journalist its annual Prize for Journalism and
Democracy. ''(He) reported on the conflict in Chechnya with
complete disregard for his personal safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, a 15-year journalism veteran, covered the war from
rebel positions, angering Russia's military, which arrested him in
January for allegedly failing to have proper accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   While held for two weeks in a detention center in Chechnya,
Babitsky said he saw innocent men tortured by Russian police.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities next announced they had traded him to rebels
in exchange for captive Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   No one heard from Babitsky for weeks, and co-workers said they
feared the military had killed him.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, Babitsky resurfaced in Russian custody in the
neighboring republic of Dagestan and said he had been held by men
he believed were working for the Russian secret services.
</P>
<P>
   The $20,000 OSCE prize, first awarded in 1996, is given to
reporters or organizations that have helped develop principles of
human rights and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners include Adam Michnik, a former Polish dissident and
editor of Poland's first independent newspaper, the Paris-based
organization Reporters Sans Frontiers, British journalist Timothy
Garton Ash and CNN's Christiane Amanpour.
</P>
<P>
   The prize will be awarded the prize July 6 at the OSCE's annual
session in Sofia, Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky is a seven-year veteran of Radio Liberty, which has its
headquarters in Prague, capital of the Czech Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
