<HEADLINE> $5M Awarded in Fence Accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- A jury awarded nearly $5 million to
the parents of a college student killed when her car struck a roll
of chain-link fence that had fallen off a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannetta Jordan, 25, of Delray Beach and her friend Sherika
Nelson, 20, of Jacksonville were driving through Georgia on their
way to South Carolina State University in Orangeburg, S.C., when
their car struck the fence, veered off Interstate 95 and
overturned. Both were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Herman and Pearl Jordan sued Southeastern Wire for wrongful
death in the 1998 crash.
</P>
<P>
   The jury on Wednesday decided Southeastern should pay the
Jordans $2.475 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern has not decided whether to appeal, attorney Harvey
Jay said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's family reached a confidential settlement with the
company last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordans said they will put the money to work and lobby for
tougher safety laws for trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
