<HEADLINE> Gene Therapy Helps Two Babies  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- French scientists have used gene therapy to
restore an apparently normal immune system to two babies born with
a rare, life-threatening immune disease.
</P>
<P>
   It's far too soon to know if the babies are cured, experts
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   But the research, reported in Friday's edition of the journal
Science, ''is a very important milestone,'' said Dr. Jennifer Puck,
a geneticist at the U.S. National Institutes of Health. ''It looks
like this really worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The babies have SCID, or ''severe combined immunodeficiency
disease,'' a rare disease that afflicted David, the Houston
''bubble boy'' who lived in a germ-proof plastic enclosure. SCID
prevents babies' bodies from producing lymphocytes, the immune
cells that ward off infection, meaning they can die from the most
minor of germs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, SCID patients receive bone marrow transplants to provide
them with healthy stem cells, the special cells that produce
lymphocytes. Transplants have cured some babies and extended the
lives of others. But because they're not always successful,
scientists have hoped gene therapy could offer an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alain Fischer of the Hospital Necker-Enfants Malades in
Paris took bone marrow from two babies when they were ages 8 months
and 11 months, and culled some of their stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   The babies have a defective gene that literally blocks
lymphocyte formation. Lift that roadblock, and the body should
generate normal immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer took a normal version of that immune system gene and
added it to a harmless virus. In a lab dish, he infected the
babies' stem cells with the gene-carrying virus. Then he
transplanted the stem cells back into their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the babies started making germ-killing immune cells.
Eleven months later, both have immune systems comparable to healthy
children their age, without any side effects, Fischer reports in
Science.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know how long this benefit is going to last,'' and
more children need the experiment to prove it really works,
cautions Puck, who hopes to begin a similar gene therapy study this
fall on U.S. babies. But, ''for now they seem to be doing just as
well as if they'd been cured.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
