<HEADLINE> Tentative settlement reached in 4-month nurses strike  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NYACK, N.Y. (AP) -- The end could be in sight for a four-month
strike that kept Nyack Hospital nurses on the picket line through
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses' representatives reached a tentative settlement with the
hospital on Thursday, although picketers promised to continue their
demonstrations until the official contract vote on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kriz, spokeswoman for the hospital, and Mark Genovese of
the New York State Nurses Association said the agreement was
reached just after 3 a.m., 12 hours into a bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed not to release details of the deal until
the nurses vote on whether to ratify it, but Genovese said there
must have been movement on three issues: merit pay, vacation and
staffing levels.
</P>
<P>
   Kriz said the nurses' bargaining committee recommended
ratification.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-dozen nurses picketed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meena Ananth, who worked as a substitute school nurse and on
other nursing jobs during the strike, said she will be happy to be
a full-time employee again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sympathize for the people who really needed the job and had
to stand out here on picket lines,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came three days after all but four of the 425
striking nurses disregarded a hospital ultimatum that could have
cost them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital had said it would begin hiring permanent
replacements for any nurse who did not return to work then.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a big surprise,'' said Maureen O'Connell, a nurse at
Nyack for a year and a half. She said the ultimatum by hospital
President Gregor Andersen was ''his last trump.''
</P>
<P>
   Only four nurses crossed the picket line Monday, after the
ultimatum, bringing to 25 the total number that left the strike
since it began Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Other nurses chanted ''Unity!'' on their picket line and shouted
'Scab!' at potential replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was our feeling that the hospital was more willing to
settle after they saw the nurses were not intimidated by their
attempt to replace them,'' Genovese said. ''We're very proud of the
nurses for standing together.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital had proposed shifting much of the pay scale to a
merit system rather than seniority. Each nurse would get a 10
percent raise over the five years of the proposed contract, but
some could get 22.5 percent depending on their evaluations. The
nurses wanted pay to be based on seniority to diminish the affects
of managerial whims.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital also wanted to trim the number of paid days off,
including vacation and sick days, from 45 to 40.
</P>
<P>
   The union, complaining that a heavy work load could endanger
patient care, wanted guaranteed nurse-to-patient ratios and less
forced overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
