<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A rash of school tax hikes despite record school aid  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- There has never been a sustained period of
state taxpayer support for public education in New York like the
one that has been in progress since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, the state has upped the state tax dollars going
to public schools, from $10.3 billion in the 1996-97 state budget
to a projected $13.2 billion in the yet-to-be-adopted 2000-01
budget.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost like the Legislature and governor are in a
bidding war, with themselves as the only participants. ''An $800
million increase in 1998? We'll see that and raise you another $800
million in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   When this year's budget is finally enacted, it will include the
biggest increase yet -- $1.2 billion, according to state
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the state leaders were hoping to forestall property tax
increases with such largesse -- if not actually causing a district
here and there to roll back tax bills -- they will be sorely
disappointed at the spending plans of schools in New York for the
2000-01 school year. The new budgets being outlined by districts
are calling, almost without fail, for school tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   The trend exasperates state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason on this earth why the school districts in
this state have to raise taxes,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators say there are plenty of reasons why
districts are looking at higher taxes: increases in the cost of
teacher contracts and benefits; the districts' share of a very
popular state school construction program; adding programs to meet
higher state scholastic standards; the expenses caused by
unexpected increases in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the district expenses have increased at a rate much
higher than the rate of inflation,'' said David Ernst, a spokesman
for the state School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   Not unusual, either, is the experience of Marlboro Central
School District in Ulster County, Ernst said. Property owners there
are facing a 23 percent tax hike in the new school budget after
Central Hudson Gas &AMP; Electric argued successfully in court that the
school district had overassessed the value of the utility's
property and must repay $1.55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many districts have lost such ''tax certiorari'' court rulings
to utilities, Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in most places outside New York's largest cities will
vote May 16 on new budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst said districts will be asking voters for authorization to
spend up to a certain amount in the next school year. The actual
size of the tax increases will depend on how liberal local
districts have been at estimating the size of the 2000-01 state aid
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Districts who based budgets on Gov. George Pataki's proposed
$400 million education aid increase will likely see smaller tax
increases than more prescient -- or reckless -- districts who gambled
that the Legislature would add another $800 million in school aid
onto Pataki's proposed budget. Districts send out final tax bills
on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, roughly 45 percent of public school costs in
New York are paid for by the state, 50 percent by local taxes and 5
percent by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The seeming incongruity of tax increases at a time when the
state is in such a giving mood toward schools is heightened by the
presence of the state's ''STAR'' property tax abatement program. It
will be expanded in the new state fiscal year to provide homeowners
with about $2 billion in breaks on their property tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   STAR has nothing to do with increasing or decreasing the amount
of money available to schools, it merely increases the proportion
paid by the state. But a program combining ''property taxes'' and
''tax reductions'' seems to provide the promise of lower overall
tax bills to New York property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, those bills are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno says he favors a proposal from Pataki to have the state
send STAR tax rebate checks directly to residents instead of using
the current system, where residents' tax bills are reduced by the
amount homeowners are qualified for and localities collect
reimbursement from the state on a dollar-for-dollar amount.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Pataki wants to get more credit from voters for
STAR. But Bruno said the billing change would be a sort of
truth-in-taxing provision to prevent school districts from
camouflaging tax hikes in tax bills which have fallen because of
STAR.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much more honest,'' Bruno said. ''It's much more upfront.
It's what the Legislature and the governor originally intended when
they put that (STAR program) in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, Pataki's proposal has been unpopular with
school boards and Democrats in the state Assembly and the
governor's spokesman Michael McKeon said this week Pataki was
considering ''alternatives to rebates.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
