<HEADLINE> Tree Runs for Congress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) -- Voters looking for congressional timber
may want to consider filmmaker Michael Moore's candidate: a ficus
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Moore brought a 3-foot tree to Morris County on Wednesday to
announce its write-in campaign for the seat held by Rep. Rodney
Frelinghuysen, a Republican seeking his fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing this because the American people no longer show up
to vote,'' Moore said. ''The majority of people feel they have no
choice. Candidates make promises and go to Washington and do
nothing. We believe a potted plant could do no worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen's spokesman, Mark Broadhurst, called it a
publicity stunt to drum up interest in Moore's comedy show ''TV
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore acknowledged that leafy candidates are no real solution.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sad commentary on the state of electoral politics in
this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is serving as campaign manager for 21 ficus trees running
in congressional races around the country. The trees are
challenging representatives who have little or no competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
