<HEADLINE> European Stocks End Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks ended lower on
stronger-than-expected U.S. economic figures, but suffered little
damage from another plunge in the euro against the dollar and a
European Central Bank rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies ended
2.96 points, or 0.8 percent, lower at 385.71, with the media sector
particularly weak. Telecoms issues also fell heavily after some
early gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, ended down 6.11 points
at 428.42. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 73.1 points
at 5172.0 and the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index 20.3 points lower at
4985.6.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the sharp turnaround in Europe after U.S. data
were released, sparking fears the Federal Reserve would hike
interest rates at its May meeting, illustrates the tightening hold
of the U.S. markets over equity trends in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the markets' general decline, food and beverages,
pharmaceuticals, tobacco and cyclicals gained.
</P>
<P>
   Helsinki and Stockholm bourses both rose on the back of strong
Nokia results, which also increased confidence in mobile phone
stocks across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia's first quarter mobile phone unit sales and operating
profit were both up 88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Helsinki's General Index rose 4.7 percent, while Nokia climbed
by 7.6 percent. Stockholm's OMX index was up 1.1 percent as
Ericsson rose.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE 100 index fell 77.2 points, or 1.2 percent, at
6179.3, after falling to 6127.9 on the release of the U.S. data.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index declined by 2.3 percent, while the
Paris CAC-40 Index was down 2.2 percent, Milan's MIBtel Index fell
0.6 percent and Amsterdam's AEX Index rose 0.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
