<HEADLINE> Dow Down 80; Nasdaq Up 80   </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were mostly lower today after a
widely watched economic report showed wage pressures are rising and
suggested that the Federal Reserve is likely to continue raising
interest rates to contain inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad selloff was averted by a report on the gross
domestic product that showed slightly lower-than-expected growth.
Technology stocks rose on the latest wave of corporate earnings
reports.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 80.67 at 10,864.83.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 80.57 at 3,710.66 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 3.63 at 1,457.36.
</P>
<P>
   Traders had nervously anticipated today's economic reports,
fearful that one or both would show that the economy was growing
much too fast for the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   The reports confirmed that the economy is on a tear. The gross
domestic product grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate during the first
three months of 2000, the Commerce Department said today. But many
economists had anticipated a 6 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The more troubling statistic to inflation-wary traders: the
Employment Cost Index. In the first quarter, the index rose 1.4
percent, the biggest quarterly advance in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Economists fear that rising wage pressures will stimulate
inflation, prompting more and steeper interest rate increases by
the Fed. Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy is not showing the signs of slowing that the Fed
is looking for, and investors are correct to be concerned about
that,'' said Eric Wiegand, director of the private client group at
Warburg Pincus.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are most sensitive to inflation, led the
Dow lower. American Express fell 2 3/16 to 152 7/16 and J.P. Morgan
fell 4 3/8 to 130 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's wireless business made a modest debut in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange, rising from an offering price of 29 1/2 to
31 13/16. The tracking stock is the largest initial public offering
in history, with 360 million shares valued at a total of $10.26
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AT&AMP;T itself fell 3 1/8 to 47 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks that posted strong earnings growth were
helping the Nasdaq outperform the blue-chip Dow. MCI WorldCom rose
3 3/4 to 44 5/8 after announcing it beat Wall Street's
first-quarter earnings expectations by 1 cent a share. The telecom
company saw net income soar to $1.3 billion from $730 million a
year ago on surging data and Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications company Nextel narrowed its
first-quarter loss and rose 9 5/8 to 113 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 750.51 million
shares, well ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 1.75 to 485.99.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
