<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Publisher, Bishop Spar  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A bitter newspaper strike at one of Calgary's two
major dailies has provoked an extraordinary public dispute between
newspaper baron Conrad Black and the city's Roman Catholic bishop.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict so far has included name-calling, with Black
referring to Bishop Frederick Henry as a ''little twerp'' in
response to Henry's intimation that Black's company was
un-Christian in its handling of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Despite letters exchanged by the two men last week in what a
Black associate called the resolution of the rift, Henry said
Wednesday that the central issue -- the refusal of management at the
Calgary Herald to negotiate -- remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue is still not over and done with,'' Henry said in a
telephone interview. ''I haven't changed my stance. I still have
not seen any indication that the people of the Herald have
addressed any of the substantive issues I raised.''
</P>
<P>
   A desire to set up collective bargaining at the newspaper in
Alberta led to the strike that began in November and has continued
through the winter and early spring.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 workers -- including reporters, editors,
photographers and other editorial personnel -- demanded seniority
rights and other benefits. Negotiations quickly collapsed and
management brought in replacement workers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Henry wrote an opinion piece for the
Catholic Register magazine that explained why he had refused to
give interviews to Herald reporters and criticized the newspaper's
management.
</P>
<P>
   Henry supported the workers' right to strike and said Black,
whose holdings control 60 percent of Canadian newspapers and dozens
of others around the world, failed to consider legitimate demands.
The bishop also implied such intransigence by Black, who converted
to Catholicism 14 years ago, went against Christian teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ''Church teaching encourages Catholic workers to become actively
involved in their own unions and urges the Catholic community as a
whole to support the essential role that labor unions have to play
in society,'' the bishop wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Black responded in a Herald column by writing: ''If your
jumped-up little twerp of a bishop thinks I'm not a very good
Catholic, I think he's a prime candidate for exorcism.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to write that Henry shirked a fundamental duty by
making a moral statement on an important issue without having
''informed himself fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Leninist terminology that would be familiar to the
strike leaders, he has made himself a perfect 'useful idiot' to
them,'' Black wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Henry initially said he wanted an apology from Black and
indicated he might take legal action, then later said he would let
the matter rest. The Vatican said it has no comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Colson, the vice chairman of Black's Hollinger International
publishing empire, said Wednesday in London that Black received a
letter from Henry last week explaining that the bishop never
intended his column to be interpreted as suggesting Black was
un-Christian.
</P>
<P>
   According to Colson, Black responded with a letter that thanked
the bishop for his gracious gesture, and the dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, however, said there was more. While his letter to Black
began as described by Colson, it also offered forgiveness for what
Henry called ''cheap shots'' by Black and concluded by noting that
nothing had changed regarding the newspaper strike.
</P>
<P>
   He said Black's response ''started off graciously, but near the
end he started telling me in very Black-esque language, 'Bishop,
you still don't know know what you're talking about.'''
</P>
<P>
   Henry noted that he and other Calgary clergymen have tried to
intervene in the newspaper dispute but were rebuffed by management.
He said the newspaper appeared unwilling to negotiate in good faith
on the seniority question, which would restrict management's
freedom to hire and fire at will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
