<HEADLINE> Computer Consultant Body Found  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRICK, N.J. (AP) -- Authorities searching for a missing computer
consultant recovered his body from a swamp Thursday, 10 days after
he was believed to have been kidnapped from a Kentucky motel by a
man brandishing fake FBI credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of federal agents converged on a cul-de-sac two miles
from the home of Gregory J. Marcinski, who is accused of kidnapping
Paul Jeffery Gale from a Florence, Ky., motel.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities wouldn't say why they knew to go to the site where
the body was found. The FBI would not immediately confirm the body
was Gale's, but Linda Tally Smith, an assistant commonwealth
attorney for Boone County, Ky., said it was his. An autopsy was
pending to determine cause of death, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The understanding, at this point, is that (the death) occurred
somewhere between Kentucky and New Jersey. The exact point is
unknown,'' Smith said. Regardless of the location, Kentucky can
charge Marcinski with murder because the crime originated there,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, motel employees saw Gale, a 28-year-old British
national who was dating a former girlfriend of Marcinski's,
handcuffed and put into a white Buick with New Jersey license
plates. He had not been seen since. Kidnapping charges against
Marcinski were brought three days later.
</P>
<P>
   The British man's relatives, who came to the United States after
Gale disappeared, were notified of the search.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, 23, a volunteer emergency medical technician, was
charged last week in Kentucky with kidnapping and impersonating an
FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski gained access to Gale's motel room by flashing an
emergency medical technician badge and computer-generated FBI
credentials identifying him as ''Special Agent Trimble,''
authorities have said. He told motel employees that Gale was in the
federal witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   Gale recently lived in Mount Laurel, where he worked as a
computer programmer for TRW Integrated Supply. He was working for
TRW in Kentucky this month as a consultant in the merger of two
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gale's girlfriend, Darla Guidie, told the FBI that her former
boyfriend Marcinski made the fake ID on his computer and ''bragged
that he had gotten the format for the phony FBI credentials off of
the Internet,'' according to affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit, Marcinski told authorities he drove
from New Jersey to Florence and picked up Gale because he wanted to
''clear the air.'' But he insisted he drove around for up to two
hours and then dropped Gale off unharmed at another Florence hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinksi's New Jersey housemate, Preston Foree, was arrested
Wednesday night on a federal charge of being an accessory after the
fact, said Alan Ables, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office
in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Foree, 21, was not in Kentucky and does not face charges in that
state, Smith said, but ''we believe he helped conceal the body once
the defendant brought it back to New Jersey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
