<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cable TV Sparks Hollywood Walkout  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actor Gary Epp sees it this way: He can
strike, or he can become a ''perpetual waiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Epp, 46, who has mostly made a living playing ''the regular guy
next door'' in TV commercials for everything from Budweiser to
Motrin, is one of 135,000 actors threatening to walk off the job
Monday. They are angry about how the rise of cable TV has hurt
their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by the Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television &AMP; Radio Artists would be the first major
Hollywood walkout in 12 years. It would affect only radio and TV
commercials, not movies or TV series.
</P>
<P>
   TV commercials are low-prestige and typically low-paying,
offering a minimum of $478 for a day's work. The important money
comes from ''pay-per-play'' residuals -- ranging roughly from $50 to
$120 -- that the actor gets each time a commercial airs on network
television.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cable TV ads, actors receive only a renewable
flat fee of $1,000 or less for each 13-week run. But with
two-thirds of all TV ads now being made for cable, actors are
demanding pay-per-play rights.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want the opposite -- to expand flat fees to network
commercials. They contend a proposed increase in the flat rates
would more than make up the difference for the actors.
</P>
<P>
   Epp doubts it. He said he used to earn as much as $18,000 in a
year in residuals from a single network commercial -- three times
what a cable ad might provide.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the joke among actors is ''it actually pays better to
make the french fries at McDonald's than to make the McDonald's
commercial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract arrangement dates to the 1950s and '60s,
when ABC, NBC and CBS claimed up to 95 percent of the audience.
Nowadays, six networks fight for 50 percent of the audience, while
200 or so cable and satellite channels claim the rest, said Ira
Shepard, whose Washington-based law firm is representing the
Association of National Advertisers and the American Association of
Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The fragmented audience means advertisers must show the same
commercial much more often to reach as many viewers, so a
pay-per-play fee ''would create an inappropriate windfall to
performers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The union's demands would mean a 350 percent increase in cable
commercial residuals, Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   Screen Actors Guild President William Daniels doesn't buy the
argument. Advertisers are making record revenue, he said, because
they can better target audiences through specialized channels such
as ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Epp, a SAG vice president, was on the negotiating team. He said
performers account for less than 2 percent of the cost of a
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I sit across the table from them and I see them in their
$400 Gucci shoes, telling me I'm overpaid, it really sticks in my
craw,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers say viewers won't even notice the strike. They have
stockpiled commercials and plan to continue production with both
union and nonunion actors.
</P>
<P>
   However, Steve Marcus, head of Florida-based Marcus Productions
Inc., which has done national commercials for Chrysler, L'Oreal and
others, said at least two advertising agencies have told him they
are holding off on commercials because of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're used to working with top talent, and their clients are
expecting the best,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: http://www.sag.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aftra.org
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Advertising Agencies:
http://www.aaaa.org
</P>
<P>
   Association of National Advertisers: http://www.ana.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
