<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intruder Attacks Germaine Greer  </HEADLINE>
By IAN PHILLIPS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Feminist author Germaine Greer, threatened in her
home this week by a ranting female intruder, admits to being
slightly obsessive about privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am as territorial as a robin, who will drill his beak into
the skull of any interloper robin who wanders on to his patch,''
she said in excerpts of an account of her ordeal published Thursday
in The Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the author of ''The Female Eunuch'' was pushed back
inside her walled Georgian house near the southern England town of
Great Chesterford by a woman who, while screaming at her, smashed
some of her belongings with a poker.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how long the ordeal lasted or how violent it was.
</P>
<P>
   Police, alerted by friends who heard the shouting as they
dropped by, said Greer, 61, had been badly shaken.
</P>
<P>
   They said Karen Burke, a 19-year-old student at Bath University
in southwest England, would appear in court May 4 on charges of
causing bodily harm and unlawful imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see that I'm not hurt, that I can walk,'' Greer
snapped at reporters at Heathrow Airport on Thursday after
returning from a work appointment in Ireland. ''I haven't lost my
sense of humor or my tolerance of dreadful behavior ... Now, you
can go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, outside her home, she said she long suspected she would
one day be targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ever since I published 'The Female Eunuch,' there has always
been an off-chance that someone was going to pick me off.
Somewhere. Some nutter -- seeing some of the hostility we get in
letters,'' she said. ''I feel a bit like Caesar. The brave man dies
but once. The coward dies many times. In this case, it is a brave
woman. I refuse to be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer chose her house because it is far from prying eyes with
only one point of entrance.
</P>
<P>
   She said she invited Burke into the house after the student
knocked on the door during the weekend, but called police after
their conversation became tense. Burke returned Monday, the author
said, pouncing from some bushes as Greer left for a dinner date.
</P>
<P>
   She said the woman should be prosecuted but expressed sympathy,
saying many university students are ''under great stress ... and
very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the full account of her ordeal, to appear in Saturday's Daily
Telegraph, Greer, who in recent years has often opened her doors to
the homeless or needy, admits being on edge when confronted by
strangers at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why is it that when my space is invaded my heart beats like a
sledgehammer?'' she writes. ''If I see a stranger wandering down my
drive, my hackles rise and I pounce out of the workshop roaring
'Can I help you?' as if what I really meant was 'Can I slit your
throat?'''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no signs saying Private Property or Keep Out or
Trespassers will be Prosecuted, but the mad glint in my eyes is
meant to speak volumes,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, a native of Australia, teaches women's studies at
Cambridge University and is professor of English and Comparative
Literary Studies at Warwick University.
</P>
<P>
   As well as ''The Female Eunuch,'' published to great acclaim in
1970, she wrote the 1999 work ''The Whole Woman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1453 </TRAILER>
