<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Public Workers May Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Germany's main public workers union
said Thursday that it will hold warning strikes next week to press
demands for a 5 percent pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   The OeTV public transport and service workers union in Stuttgart
said the job action was planned for Thursday and Friday just before
a crucial third round of pay talks.
</P>
<P>
   The third round of wage talks will be held Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The union said the warning strikes aimed to force a decent
counteroffer out of the employers in response to union demands for
5 percent pay increases for the some 3.1 million public workers in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It said the employers were offering raises of 2 percent, or
equal to expected inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst-Otto Stueber, the employers' negotiator for German
communities, and Saxony state Finance Minister Georg Milbradt, who
represents the states, warned the union about misuse of strike
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ''No problems are solved with strikes,'' Stueber said.
</P>
<P>
   But OeTV Chairman Peter Blechschmidt said that if no responsible
wage offer came, warning strikes would take place nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''The employers must finally make a move,'' Blechschmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides 5 percent increases, the union is asking for approval of
a step-by-step plan to bring wages of eastern Germans, currently at
86.5 percent of that of workers in the West, up to western levels.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern public workers also have a 40-hour workweek, compared to
38.5 hours for their western colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Germany's public workers settled for 3.1 percent
raises after demanding 5.5 percent increases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, an 11-day strike by the public service unions --
including transport, office workers, bank employees, garbage,
hospital and airport ground crews -- closed Frankfurt International
Airport, shut down public transportation and left garbage piled in
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   After that action, the unions accepted 5.4 percent increases,
just over half of what they were demanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
