Gold(final) -    $277.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
</P>
<P>
   Wages, Benefits Jump 4.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. workers' wages and benefits rose by 4.3
percent in the 12 months ending in March, the fastest growth in pay
in eight years, the government said today. The increase in the
Labor Department's Employment Cost Index was up sharply from the 12
months ending in December, when wages and benefits rose by 3.4
percent. Higher labor costs are a concern to economists for fear
employers will pass on the cost to consumers, raising inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Economy Grows at 5.4 Percent Rate
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy grew at an annual rate of 5.4
percent in the first quarter, driven by an 8.3 percent rise in
consumer spending, the largest since 1983. The increase in the
gross domestic product -- the country's total output of goods and
services -- as measured by the Commerce Department was weaker than
the 6 percent rate many analysts were expecting. The economy grew
at a 7.3 percent rate in the last quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: Net Will Lift Rural Life
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The technological boom that is transforming
the nation's cities is also providing greater job opportunities and
a better life in rural areas, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said today. In the Internet and computer age, rural
citizens are gaining access to a broader range of goods and
services and the already existing goods and services are available
more expeditiously and at lower cost,'' Greenspan said. in remarks
to a conference on rural America sponsored by the Federal Reserve
regional bank in Kansas City, he noted satellite television, and
also innovations being developed, such as telemedicine, which
enables doctors in rural areas to diagnose illnesses through TV and
computer hookups.
</P>
<P>
   EToys' Sales Rise but Losses Widen
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- EToys Inc.'s quarterly sales nearly
quadrupled from a year ago, but the online retailer's losses
widened significantly as it spent heavily on marketing and
expanding its warehouse space. EToys reported today that it lost
$36.6 million or 30 cents per share, in the quarter that ended
March 31, compared with a loss of $8.9 million, or 10 cents per
share, a year ago. The results beat a 32-cents-per-share loss
forecast by analysts. Sales jumped to $23 million, up from $6.1
million a year ago. The company expects to be in ''striking
distance'' of break-even by the holiday quarter of 2001 and should
reach profitability in 2002, said eToys president and chief
executive Toby Lenk.
</P>
<P>
   BAE To Buy Lockheed Unit for $510M
</P>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- A subsidiary of British Aerospace has
agreed to buy Lockheed Martin's control systems division for $510
million in cash, the U.S. defense contractor announced today. BAE
Systems, a wholly-owned subsidiary of British Aerospace, will buy
the division, which has facilities in Johnson City, N.Y., and Fort
Wayne, Ind. The division supplies electronics controls for the
commercial and military markets, including aircraft, space, and
ground transportation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner Loses Bank Voting Rights
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Credit Lyonnais has suspended the voting rights of
Dresdner Bank AG for two years after its German rival failed to
declare its recent purchase of a 3.6 percent in the French bank,
chairman Jean Peyrelevade said today. The decision came at the
demand of one or more of Credit Lyonnais' core shareholder group,
which has a 33 percent stake in the bank. Peyrelevade, speaking at
the bank's annual meeting, said he expects members of the core
shareholder group to protect Credit Lyonnais from any takeover bid
and abstain from taking control of the bank on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Ford To Pay $1M Clean Air Penalty
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will pay a $1.1 million penalty as
part of a settlement of alleged violations of the Clean Air Act,
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency said. Ford's consent
decree with the EPA and the Justice Department covers the Wayne
Assembly and Michigan Truck Assembly plants, both in Wayne, and the
Dearborn Assembly plant in Dearborn. Under the agreement, Ford must
pay one-third of the $1.1 million penalty to the federal
government, one-third to the state and one-third to Wayne County.
The consent decree incorporates Ford's plan to close Dearborn
Assembly by Oct. 31 and move its operations to a new plant being
built next to the existing facility.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing To Add Net Hook-Ups to Jets
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Boeing Co. today announced plans to install
special phone jacks in the armrests on airplanes to allow travelers
to connect to the Internet with laptop computers, check e-mail and
watch television. Boeing expects to begin installing the new
service at the end of next year. Initially the service would only
be available on flights over North America, but the company hopes
to make the service available in flights over oceans and other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   6 Airlines Forming Net Marketplace
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Six major airlines announced plans today to start
an Internet marketplace to handle about $32 billion in annual
purchases of items such as fuel, engines and maintenance services
for the airlines. The carriers are Air France, American, British
Airways, Continental, Delta and United. The new Internet company,
which has not been named, will be based in the United States. The
airlines did not disclose their planned financial stakes in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia's Profit Rises 76 Percent
</P>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Telecommunications equipment maker
Nokia's profit rose by 76 percent in the first quarter as sales of
cellular phones soared. The results were slightly higher than
market expectations and its share price jumped 3.6 percent on the
Helsinki Stock Exchange. Nokia earned 891 million euros ($860
million) in the January-March period, up from 505 million euros a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   BMW Rejects Exec's Offer for Rover
</P>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- BMW today rejected an offer by former
Rover manager John Towers to take over the troubled British
automaker, saying it was ''financially not secured.'' But talks
with another group of British venture capitalists who want to
acquire Rover are proceeding and a decision is expected in early
May, the German luxury carmaker said. Towers, a former Rover chief
executive who left the company in 1996, stepped in two weeks ago to
make a rival bid for Rover to the original offer by Alchemy
Partners, a British venture capital firm.
</P>
