<HEADLINE> Sentencing for killer mom delayed, judge to consider abuseallegation  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) -- A judge agreed Thursday to hear evidence of
domestic abuse before sentencing a woman who says she killed her
teen-age autistic son to stop him from raping and abusing her.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Davis was scheduled to be sentenced by Cayuga County
Judge Peter Corning. Instead, her attorney asked for a last-minute
adjournment so Corning could consider whether Davis was responsible
for her actions because of the alleged abuse.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis' case meets the criteria under the state's domestic
abuse laws, she could receive a significantly lighter sentence,
even probation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The defense is entitled to make its case,'' said Corning.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors at one time considered bringing death
penalty charges against the 37-year-old Davis, she was allowed to
plead guilty in March to first-degree manslaughter and use an
''affirmative defense.'' That defense argued that she suffered from
''extreme emotional disturbance'' the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Davis admitted using a candle and nail polish remover to start a
fire in her Fleming home last Sept. 4, killing her 13-year-old son,
Daniel Leubner, who was asleep on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Her plea came several days after a closed four-day hearing on
whether to suppress her statement. It was later revealed that in
her statement, Davis alleged her son had raped her and beaten her
several times, including the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they investigated Davis' claim and found no
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Corning will hold a hearing to consider the domestic abuse
claims. If witnesses are available, the hearing will begin
Wednesday, otherwise it could be late May or early June before it
is held, the judge said. Defense attorney David Elkovitch said
testimony would focus on the effects of post-traumatic stress
syndrome and rape trauma syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Davis remains free on bail pending her sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being disappointed by the delay in seeing his
ex-wife punished, Leroy Leubner welcomed the hearing. Leubner said
Davis made up the rape allegations to obtain leniency. He said his
son, although a big 13-year-old at 5-foot-7, 155 pounds, was not
violent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Danny was convicted of a crime and has never had a chance to
defend himself. None of this is true and a hearing will give us a
chance to challenge her lies,'' Leubner said outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   First-degree manslaughter carries a maximum penalty of 25 years
but it was expected Davis was going to receive a term of three to
five years Thursday. Leubner is confident the hearing will
undermine Davis' story and convince the judge she should receive a
longer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''She deserves to spend a lot more time in jail for what she
did. If we have to wait a little longer to see that happen, we can
wait,'' Leubner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-27-00 1510 </TRAILER>
