<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Weighs Gay Discrimination Ban  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate supporters of a federal law banning
workplace discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation pointed
Thursday to a study showing that similar state laws don't result in
a flood of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the facts are clear, there has been no litigation
explosion as a result of laws preventing employment discrimination
based on sexual orientation,'' said Sen. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office study requested by Jeffords found
that in the 11 states and the District of Columbia that have sexual
orientation anti-discrimination laws, there was ''no indication
that these laws have generated a significant amount of
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The study by GAO, the investigative wing of Congress, also
revealed that sexual discrimination cases are a relatively small
proportion of all employment discrimination complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In California, which has had a sexual orientation law since
1993, there were 154 sexual orientation discrimination lawsuits in
1999, 0.8 percent of all employment discrimination complaints. The
state with the highest percentage in 1999 was New Hampshire, where
sexual orientation cases were eight out of a total of 241, or 3.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords said the study disproved the arguments of opponents of
federal legislation that it would lead to a ''rush to the
courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords and Sens. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., are sponsoring a bill that would give federal
protections against sexual orientation discrimination. Current
federal law protects against workplace discrimination on the basis
of race, gender, religion, national origin or disability, but not
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Senate defeated a similar bill by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel legislation has been introduced in the House by Reps.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill number is S. 1276: the House bill number is H.R.
2355.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1531 </TRAILER>
