<HEADLINE> Ransom Plot Foiled by Suspicious Mom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROKEN ARROW, Okla. (AP) -- When her son told her drug dealers
were after him for $10,000, Denise Six gave him the money. But when
a ransom note for the young man appeared on her door five days
later, she got suspicious and called police.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived at the arranged drop spot in Broken Arrow,
outside of Tulsa, on Monday to find Six's son, Nathaniel Reid Six,
20, in a rented limousine with his friends and an empty bottle of
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears other parties in the vehicle had no idea they were
supposed to be kidnappers,'' Lt. Paul Kroutter said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Six was arrested and accused of obtaining money by
false pretenses and marijuana possession.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Six told police she gave her son $10,000 on April 19
after he told her drug dealers were threatening him.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, she found the note and phone messages from her son
saying he had been kidnapped by people who were driving him around
in a limousine and demanding $10,000 or they would harm him,
Kroutter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the kidnappers not giving up and kidnapping him again,
she started to think that something doesn't add up,'' Sgt. Heath
Arning said.
</P>
