<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Tone Down Chechnya Talk  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- With Russian troops bogged down in the mountains
of Chechnya and suffering heavy losses, the Kremlin is hinting it
may no longer be counting on an overwhelming military victory to
end the war.
</P>
<P>
   Russian jets keep flying daily air raids and tens of thousands
of federal troops are locked in a hit-and-run war in Chechnya. But
President Vladimir Putin and other top officials have toned down
their harsh rhetoric of accepting nothing less than total victory.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have repeatedly defied Russian claims that they are
on the verge of defeat, repeatedly ambushing federal troops. The
government, reacting to pressure from abroad and faltering public
support at home, admits it is talking with Chechen intermediaries
about a political solution and would consider negotiating with
rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the war dragging on, at some point or another, Russia has
to come to an agreement with the people it's fighting against,''
said Emil Pain, a former adviser to Boris Yeltsin who directs the
Center for Ethno-Political Studies.
</P>
<P>
   While the government shows no sign of calling off the military
campaign, it has recently acknowledged swapping peace proposals
through intermediaries with Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov,
nominal leader of the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has said Maskhadov, who has been seeking a deal with
Moscow, could qualify for amnesty. Putin said last week that he was
prepared for talks with Maskhadov, but only if he gets the rebels
to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal with Maskhadov would further split the already
fractured rebel command and give Russia an important propaganda
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not clear what negotiations with Maskhadov -- or any
Chechen leader -- could achieve. Several Chechens are vying for the
top spot in the republic, but none has the authority to enforce a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such a person must have influence with the illegal armed
formations,'' Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said in an
interview with the newspaper Izvestia. ''Unfortunately, there is no
such person in Chechnya at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushailo also said the government was working with at least two
prominent Chechens outside the rebel ranks: Bislan Gantamirov, who
was pardoned and released from prison last fall to lead a
pro-Moscow militia in Chechnya; and a religious leader, Mufti
Akhmad Alidkhadzhi Kadyrov. But neither is thought to have any real
support in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of negotiations comes as Russian popular support for
the war -- initially very high -- has begun to slowly erode,
according to Natalia Laidinen, a researcher at the independent
ROMIR polling agency.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have inflicted heavy casualties recently, and
official figures put the death toll for federal troops at over
1,800 since the military entered Chechnya in September.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent reported attack, Chechen rebels attacked a
Russian squad from the front and rear on Wednesday, killing 10
federal troops and 17 rebels, Russian officials said. The firefight
took place near Serzhen-Yurt, a town near the entrance of the key
Vedeno Gorge that leads into the mountains. An ambush Sunday near
the town killed at least 13 Russians.
</P>
<P>
   If the rebels counterattack this spring, as some analysts
predict, support could evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the federal forces take larger losses, if the Chechens
launch terrorist attacks elsewhere in Russia, this war will be far
more present in people's minds,'' Laidinen said. ''They will want
the problem decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is under pressure from the West to end the war. With
Putin seeking better ties, Moscow may want to avoid major new
offensives in Chechnya that would only sour relations. The cost of
such attacks would also be high in manpower and material.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Putin could lose credibility if he steps back from
promises of a decisive victory in Chechnya that helped make him
popular before he won the March 26 presidential elections. And most
Russians still believe order must be brought to Chechnya, which was
overrun by violence after rebels defeated Russian troops in the
1994-96 war.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way Putin can backpedal now,'' said independent
political analyst Pavel Felgenhauer. ''He hasn't left himself an
exit strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain, of the Center for Ethno-Political Studies, said Russia
would probably try to scale down fighting, but that it wouldn't
risk withdrawing troops and the conflict could drag on for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are all the signs of a widening guerrilla war in
Chechnya,'' Pain said. ''I don't rule out that it could last for
the entire four years of Putin's term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1542 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Bill in Limbo in Senate  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to increase U.S. military ties
with Taiwan may be put on hold in the Senate to use as future
leverage over China, a sponsor of the bill suggested Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said he has recommended to
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that the Senate not
move forward on the bill at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see a need for it,'' Murkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Murkowski said Taiwan's president-elect, Chen
Shui-bian, and other leaders told him that a Senate vote on the
measure now could serve as an irritant to already-frayed relations
between China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who will be sworn in May 20, is under great pressure to
improve relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very interested now in getting the president
inaugurated and having a smooth transition,'' said Murkowski, who
visited Taiwan last week. He said Chen and other Taiwanese leaders
had reached a consensus that Senate action on the bill at this time
''would not be in the best interests of Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress would have more leverage over China if it keeps
the legislation pending, rather than passing it and needlessly
provoking China at a sensitive time.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed the House 341-70 in February, would
establish formal links between the U.S. and Taiwanese military. It
has drawn strong opposition from Beijing and a veto threat from
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent decision of Lott and other Senate leaders to allow
the Taiwan legislation -- passed overwhelmingly by the House in
February -- to languish a little longer on the Senate calendar was
cheered by supporters of granting China permanent trade benefits.
They do not want the issue of increased military support for the
island to interfere with the China trade vote scheduled for later
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott spokesman John Czwartacki said Thursday that ''no
decision has yet been made on scheduling'' on the Taiwan bill,
despite Murkowski's appeal that it be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Lott earlier this month put the bill on the Senate calendar to
allow it to be taken up at any time.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for Lott is that some influential Senate
conservatives, including Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., are pressing for Senate action on the legislation --
particularly after the administration's decision last week not to
sell Aegis destroyers and certain other sophisticated weapons to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republican sources speaking on the condition they not
be identified said they expected Lott to honor Murkowski's request.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatically, the United States deals with Taiwan carefully,
avoiding any suggestion it is promoting independence for the
island.
</P>
<P>
   The bill to increase military ties with Taiwan already was
viewed as in trouble in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a leading Senate sponsor of the China
trade bill, put a ''hold'' on the legislation -- implying that he
would use procedural obstacles to block the bill vote should Lott
choose to bring it up.
</P>
<P>
   Such obstacles are time-consuming to overcome and require 60
votes instead of the simple 51-vote majority generally needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that the Senate is taking a momentarily thoughtful
approach to the issue surrounding U.S. relations with Taiwan,''
Baucus spokesman Michael Siegel said. ''That's encouraging.
However, Senator Baucus is intent on ensuring that he can do all he
can to separate the issue of this legislation from the upcoming
trade debate. Therefore, his hold still stands.''
</P>
<P>
   The House will start debating the bill to extend China permanent
normal trade relations on May 22 and both sides are predicting a
close vote. The Senate, where support for the trade bill is more
broadly based, has not yet set a date for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Leading supporters of the legislation want the Senate to vote
first to help build momentum before the crucial House vote. But
recent back surgery undergone by Senate Finance Committee Chairman
William Roth, R-Del., could mean the Senate won't vote on the
measure until June.
</P>
<P>
   Roth is the chief Senate sponsor of the trade bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1549 </TRAILER>
