<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Director of Yugoslav Airline Buried  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POZAREVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Zika Petrovic, an ally of President
Slobodan Milosevic who was gunned down two days ago, was buried
Thursday in his native Pozarevac.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred people, including several top Yugoslav officials,
attended the funeral in this central Serbian town, which is the
hometown of Milosevic and his influential wife Mirjana Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Zoran Uskokovic, a well-known Belgrade underworld
figure, and his friend were killed in a gangland-style shooting,
independent Studio B television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Uskokovic, alias Skole, was driving with a friend in his black
sedan in a Belgrade suburb when assailants sprayed machine-gun fire
on the two from another car.
</P>
<P>
   He had been targeted already earlier this week when a bomb went
off in front of the high-rise apartment building in which he lived.
No one was harmed in that blast.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade tabloids had implicated Uskokovic in the January
slaying of Zeljko Raznatovic, known as Arkan, Serbia's most
notorious warlord and underworld don -- something Uskokovic later
denied in the papers.
</P>
<P>
   In Pozarevac, some 48 miles east of Belgrade, Milosevic and
Markovic were not present at the burial service. Serbia's ruling
couple sent a wreath instead.
</P>
<P>
   Petrovic was an associate of Milosevic and head of Yugoslavia's
national carrier, JAT. He was killed in front of his home in
downtown Belgrade on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the killing, no arrests had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Petrovic was not believed involved in any of the financial
scandals in Serbia in the past decade nor did he have any political
function or ties to the underworld.
</P>
<P>
   Previous high-profile deaths in Serbia -- most of which remain
unsolved -- involved either mafia bosses, such as Arkan, or police
or state officials.
</P>
<P>
   A top Serbian official, Nikola Sainovic, said Thursday that
Petrovic's killing represented a ''revolting crime,'' Beta news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''Crimes are committed by criminals. Criminals should be
prosecuted and they will be found and punished,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities declared Petrovic's killing a ''terrorist act'' and
blamed it on foreign intelligence services. But the opposition saw
the slaying as a sign of growing lawlessness and demanded the
resignation of Serbia's police chief, Vlajko Stojiljkovic.
</P>
<P>
   Stojiljkovic, one of four Yugoslav officials indicted by the
U.N. war crimes tribunal along with Milosevic, was seen at
Petrovic's funeral along with the head of state security, Rade
Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's deputy prime minister and ultranationalist leader
Vojislav Seselj also claimed the slaying of JAT's manager was the
'dirty work'' of American and other Western intelligence services
who continue ''intensive espionage and subversive activities'' in
Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   As Petrovic was buried, three Cessna 172 planes performed an
honorary flyover.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not just a shot at Zika, it was also a shot at JAT
and the state,'' Ljuba Acimovic, head of Belgrade airport said in a
funeral speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
