<HEADLINE> Seal Bites German Mayor's Hand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- One of the Frankfurt zoo's 10 dwarf
seals bit the hand of the city's mayor and nearly sent her tumbling
Thursday, just after she had dedicated a new enclosure for the
''seadogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Petra Roth had been standing on a slippery rock in
high-heel shoes. She was trying to feed the seals when one of them,
Daisy, nipped the 56-year-old mayor's right index finger and nearly
knocked her into the pool. A zoo escort grabbed Roth just in time.
</P>
<P>
   Roth immediately received medical treatment, which included a
bandaged finger, tetanus shot and prescription for antibiotics, her
office said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo director Christian Schmidt defended the ''seadogs,'' saying
they had always been well mannered in the past. Daisy's bite was
not out of aggression, he said, but more a playful reflex.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's not a mean animal, and the mayor understands that,''
Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt zoo claims to have the largest group of dwarf seals in
captivity, and had to expand its facilities at a cost of $2.7
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
