<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Raises Rates  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The European Central Bank raised interest rates
Thursday for the third time in three months, citing a continued
risk of inflation, but that did nothing to keep the battered euro
currency from tumbling to a new low and flirting with 90 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter-point increase in short-term rates by the Frankfurt,
Germany-based central bank followed similar increases on Feb. 3 and
March 16.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB said in a statement that it acted to counter continued
''upside risks to price stability in the medium term,'' including
the weak euro.
</P>
<P>
   As the euro falls, it drives up the cost of goods imported into
the 11 European nations that adopted the single currency, adding to
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little comfort to investors from a central bank
statement that ''the present level of the euro does not reflect the
strong economic fundamentals of the euro area.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell as low as 90.59 cents Thursday after the ECB
raised rates and ended the trading day in New York at 91.01 cents,
down from 92.33 cents Wednesday. The previous low of 91.62 cents
was reached during trading Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's closing rate, the euro was down 23 percent from
the all-time high of $1.1886 reached on the first day it traded --
Jan. 4, 1999 -- and down almost 10 percent from where it ended last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB's main goal is keeping prices stable, and it has set a
guideline of keeping inflation under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the EU statistical office said average inflation
in the euro-zone countries rose to 2.1 percent in March -- the
highest since the euro currency was launched.
</P>
<P>
   Monetary officials had been indicating they planned to raise
rates, but the timing of Thursday's move was questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The German Labor Federation said a retreat in world oil prices
should bring inflation back down on its own -- adding it couldn't
understand why the ECB acted now for any reason other than to try
and prop up the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new interest move has absolutely no basis in looming
dangers to price stability,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising interest rates can cool an economy by making it more
expensive to borrow money, dampening spending. A slowing economy
would aggravate already high unemployment in parts of the euro
region.
</P>
<P>
   Since the impact of central bank interest rate decisions is not
immediate -- policy-makers must look to longer-term indicators and
not just the ups and downs of the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers said the bank had to be careful to avoid the
impression it was panicking after the euro set new lows this week.
At the same time, other analysts said that doing nothing would
create the impression that the ECB doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB raised its key short-term rate up to 3.75 percent from
3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The step is OK, but they should communicate the right thing --
that they can't target or steal the exchange rate,'' said Michael
Schubert, an economist with Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
   Most European politicians contend the main reason for the euro's
woes continues to be the strong U.S. economy, and the sluggishness
of Europe to reform.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Thursday that America's
total output of goods and services, called the gross domestic
product, rose at an annual rate of 5.4 percent in the first
quarter. Consumer spending, which has been driving the economic
expansion, had its strongest increase in almost 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   France's finance minister said Thursday a rate hike wouldn't do
anything to help the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my view, it isn't with a strong increase in interest rates
that we will solve this problem,'' Laurent Fabius said in an
interview with French radio station RTL.
</P>
<P>
   Showing market participants that the ''European economic
situation is improving strongly'' is the solution to the euro's
current weakness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newly appointed Italian Prime Minister Giuliano Amato in his
first speech to parliament Thursday called on lawmakers to press
ahead with structural reforms to help boost the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''The euro is undervalued and destined to grow,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
