<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastman Music School Gets $1M Gift  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A frugal piano teacher with a flair for
investing in the stock market is giving away her third $1 million
gift -- this time to the Eastman School of Music where she studied
as a child in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Murray Trebert, 88, equates her self-taught success in
accumulating money with her musical talents. ''I use my eyes, I use
my memory and I'm not slow -- when I want to do anything, I don't
fuss around,'' she said with a hearty chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   But holding onto the riches she has built up since the 1960s has
never interested her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't like money,'' she said Thursday. ''I guess being
in music from a tender young age, that was my love. Everything was
the music. The value of music is important, not money. My mother
used to say, 'Oh, that's only filthy lucre.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she managed to earn millions while teaching piano,
Trebert deadpanned, ''Well, I charged about $8,924 a half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Invoking her modest upbringing -- her father died when she was 10
-- Trebert recalled many times not being able to afford a dime to
ride a street car or buy an ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   Among the valuable lessons of childhood were persistence and
patience. ''You have to be awful patient with the stock market,''
she said, adding that ''thriftiness and investing ability'' also
play a big part.
</P>
<P>
   Trebert always liked to dabble in stocks but only got going in
earnest after her husband, William, a lawyer, died in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to be like my mother, cry all over the house and
moan and groan,'' she said. ''So I said, I'm going to sit down and
concentrate and get my mind on some of these companies. I want to
know all about them, their earnings and stuff. So I did, and I
stuck with it.''
</P>
<P>
   She relies on her own instincts and research -- often poring over
annual reports -- and only rarely on her broker's advice. In the
past, she often favored ''well-managed companies'' like Merck, IBM
and Texas Instruments or industries with long-term promise. But
nowadays, because of her age, she's not averse to rolling the dice
on a surging Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got to have a tough stomach,'' she cautioned.
''Everything is a risk even if it's well-managed. Of course when I
lost my husband, my attitude was, 'Well, I've lost everything, I
can face it.' If you don't love money, you've got it made.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining an investment club like the Beardstown Ladies wouldn't
cut it for Trebert. ''Too much discussion, wasted time and then
they can't make a decision at the tail end,'' she said
dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to quantify her worth, Trebert said she has not
yet given all her money away. ''I'm going to continue to do it just
for fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Trebert has given $1 million to Rochester's
Hochstein School of Music, where she taught piano for years, and
another $1 million to the Al Sigl Center, a partnership of agencies
that help people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by her music-loving mother, Clara, Trebert earned a
master's degree in musicology at Eastman in 1941, then taught at
Western Maryland College and worked as an organist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1610 </TRAILER>
