<HEADLINE> Senator Pushes More IMF Reforms  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senator warned the Clinton administration
Thursday that if it wants to win congressional approval for greater
debt relief for poor nations, it will have to offer more sweeping
reform proposals for the International Monetary Fund and World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm said he supported
the administration's proposal to forgive all debt owed to the
United States by the 40 poorest nations and provide the U.S. share
to provide relief on loans owed by those countries to the IMF and
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm, R-Texas, told Treasury Under Secretary Timothy
Geithner, ''I can't see doing either without some fairly
substantial reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, whose committee has jurisdiction over the issue, said he
would like to take up legislation in mid-May to approve revaluation
of a portion of IMF gold reserves in support of debt relief plus
approve the U.S. share of the debt forgiveness program.
</P>
<P>
   However, he and other Republican members of the Banking
Committee pushed the administration to adapt reform proposals more
along the lines being recommended by a congressional advisory panel
headed by Allan Meltzer, an economics professor at Carnegie Mellon
University.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time for reforming the IMF is upon us and we have to act
now,'' said Michael Crapo, R-Ind., who called it unacceptable to
have 70 countries holding IMF loans for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reforms being pushed by the Meltzer commission would
restrict the IMF to providing short-term loans in crisis
situations, leaving long-term lending to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Geithner said it made sense for the IMF to continue making
long-term loans to poor countries because they often need the
expertise provided by IMF economists to adapt proper reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Geithner also attacked another major Meltzer commission reform
which would limit IMF loans in most situations to countries who
have pre-qualified for the loans by adopting various reforms such
as strengthening the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   He called adoption of such reforms a good idea but no guarantee
that foreign investors will not suddenly panic and begin pulling
their money out of a particular country, the process that triggered
the cascading Asian crisis in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Geithner said the pre-qualification requirement would have
prevented IMF assistance from going to many of the crisis
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find the core recommendations of the majority report
troubling and fundamentally incompatible with our compelling
national economic and strategic interests,'' Geithner told a Senate
Banking subcommittee hearing, promising to have a complete
administration response to the Meltzer proposals ready soon.
</P>
<P>
   Geithner later told reporters that the administration could
accept less restrictive requirements for reform of the IMF included
in legislation passed by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. He
expressed the hope a compromise could be reached with Gramm on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Geithner insisted during the hearing that the IMF and World
Bank, under prodding from the administration, have gone a long way
toward implementing reforms based on lessons learned from the
global currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Both institutions held their spring meetings in Washington last
week under heavy police security. Police made 1,300 arrests during
the week and the 750 delegates and staff attending the meetings
were forced to take shuttle buses starting at 5 a.m. to avoid
protesters who clogged streets around the IMF and World Bank
headquarters, two blocks from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: IMF site: http://www.imf.org
</P>
<P>
   World Bank site: http://www.worldbank.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1619 </TRAILER>
