<HEADLINE> Demand for Workers Still Strong  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The volume of help-wanted advertising in major
U.S. newspapers dipped in March, but the demand for workers remains
strong nationwide, the Conference Board said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The business-financed research organization said its Help-Wanted
Advertising Index fell to 87 in March from a revised 90 in
February. That compared with a reading of 89 a year earlier and was
the lowest since the 86 reported in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, labor demand remains strong because the economy
continues to grow by more than 4 percent per quarter,'' board
economist Ken Goldstein said in a statement accompanying the
report. He predicted that this ''will send the unemployment rate
below 4 percent this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported earlier this month that the
nation's unemployment rate in March was close to a three-decade low
at 4.1 percent. The Commerce Department reported Thursday that the
economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate in the first quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein added that ''employers are not cutting back on job
recruitment efforts in print, and efforts to assess the change in
activity on the Internet suggest that job recruitment is even
stronger there.''
</P>
<P>
   The index measures help-wanted advertising volume in 51 major
newspapers every month. The index is used as a gauge of changes in
job supply and is watched by economists as an indicator of labor
market conditions to help form estimates of unemployment rates.
</P>
<P>
   The report Thursday said that in the first three months of the
year, help-wanted advertising rose in five regions and declined in
four.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest increases were in the Middle Atlantic region, which
includes New York, Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, where help-wanted
advertising rose 6.3 percent, and the West South Central region,
which covers Texas, Oklahoma and Louisiana, where it went up 5.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest declines were in New England, where help-wanted ads
dropped 8.4 percent, and the East South Central region, including
Birmingham, Ala., and Nashville, Tenn., where it was down 5.1
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
