<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Seeks Teamsters Support  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- George W. Bush says he asked the
Teamsters union to endorse his Republican presidential bid, and
while he didn't get a promise he saw the ''beginnings of a good
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in North Carolina Thursday for a fund-raising luncheon and
speech to a teachers' conference, said he and Teamsters President
James Hoffa ''had a very frank discussion of a variety of issues''
on Wednesday while the Texas governor was in Washington for a GOP
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did ask for his union's endorsement and he said he hadn't
made up his mind,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   A Teamsters spokesman said the meeting was one of a series that
Hoffa has held with major party candidates, including earlier this
month with Vice President Al Gore, the presumed Democratic
presidential nominee, and with Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is part of the continuing conversation with all of the
major presidential campaigns,'' said spokesman Bret Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hoffa has made a commitment ''from the beginning to make
an endorsement based on the best interests of the members of the
union, and that requires having a serious conversation with each
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   While labor unions are traditionally thought of as Democratic
supporters, the Teamsters have swung between the Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, the Teamsters backed then-President Nixon, a
Republican, but they stayed neutral in 1976. They supported Ronald
Reagan, another Republican, in 1980 and 1984, and endorsed Bush's
father, also the GOP nominee, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, however, the Teamsters abandoned Bush and joined the
AFL-CIO -- of which it is the largest member -- in endorsing Democrat
Bill Clinton. In 1996, the union did not endorse President Clinton,
but also rejected the GOP candidate, Bob Dole, because of his ties
to corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Hoffa has withheld a Teamsters endorsement in the
current race is that he opposes a Clinton-Gore administration plan
to give permanent normal trade status to China.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the union joined the United Auto Workers in
abstaining as the AFL-CIO decided to endorse Gore. At the time,
Hoffa said the union needed more time before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Following his meeting with Hoffa, Gore said they disagreed on
China's trade status, but he wouldn't talk about details of their
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the two talked Wednesday about the North American Free
Trade Agreement and truck safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman, said the governor requested the
session. ''America's working people share an awful lot with
Governor Bush and we're going to work awful hard for their
support,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came to North Carolina for a $1,000-a-plate luncheon
attended by 250 supporters and to speak briefly at a teachers'
conference attended by 1,600 people.
</P>
<P>
   For both audiences, the Texas governor promoted bipartisanship
in reaching excellence in education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised improvements in student achievement in both Texas
and North Carolina. The conference theme was closing the
achievement gap for minority and poor students, and Bush said
student achievement must be measured to avoid the ''soft bigotry''
of old education strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The old way of thinking used to ask the question, 'How old are
you? If you're 12, you're supposed to be here.' Guess who got left
behind? The inner city kids,'' Bush said. ''What we ought to ask is
what do you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Access to education was the battle of past decades, while today
access is universal ''but excellence is not,'' Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1634 </TRAILER>
