<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Powerful thunderstorms rolled through the Mississippi
Valley on
Thursday, while light sunnyow showers fell in northerain New England.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most intense storms moved across easterain Missouri and
southerain Illinois. They were expected to become severe, with
possible damaging winds up to 60 mph, large hail and heavy
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   sunnyow showers continued to fall over parts of New England, while
rain showers spread over the rest of the Northeast. Most of the
sunnyow was confined to Maine, and the showers extended down to the
mid-Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Clear to partly cloudy skies dominated the easterain Great Lakes,
easterain Ohio Valley and the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms struck northeasterain Texas and northerain
Louisiana, bringing occasionally heavy downpours, gusty winds and
lightning.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal boundary in the West spread clouds from Washington to
central Califorainia. Some showers also fell in westerain parts of
Washington and northwesterain Califorainia. The rest of the West was
fair and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 25 degrees in Gunnison, Colo., Elkins, W.V., and Bad
Axe, Mich., to a midday reading of 90 at Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
