<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victims' Rights Bill Withdrawn  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Backers of a victims' rights amendment to the
Constitution said they were pulling the measure from the Senate
floor Thursday after onslaught of criticism that it needlessly
tinkers with the nation's charter.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of support likely kills any prospect of passage this
election year, when lawmakers must get through appropriations bills
and return home for campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained it was the third attempt to amend the
Constitution in just 30 days and one by one several lawmakers
railed against the proposal over three days of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., one of the amendment's sponsors, told
lawmakers he wanted permission ''to withdraw the motion . . . and
move to other business.''
</P>
<P>
   Going forward would only encourage more ''unproductive speeches
that really don't go to the heart of the constitutional
amendment,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure lacked the 60 votes to even limit debate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will fight again another day,'' cosponsor Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., added.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has been debating the amendment since Tuesday. It
would give victims rights such as reasonable notice of court
proceedings and an offender's release or escape, the right to
attend and be heard at legal proceedings and court-ordered
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two states have enacted some form of victims' rights. The
House has not taken up the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Had it passed with two-thirds majorities in the Senate and the
House, the amendment would have had to be ratified by three-fourths
of state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl criticized the Clinton administration Wednesday, which had
not endorsed their amendment because of lingering concerns. After
news of the withdrawal, the White House released a statement from
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to reiterate our strong commitment to continue to work
towards passage of a constitutional amendment that will ensure that
victims' rights are fully considered in the criminal justice
process,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents had complained the Constitution was the wrong place
for the victims' rights. They noted that the proposal was the
latest in a string of proposed constitutional amendments. Last
month, lawmakers rejected attempts to amend the Constitution to ban
desecration of the flag and give Congress powers to limit campaign
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''The goal of expanding victims' rights is one that we fully
share, but the method should be by changes in our laws, not in our
Constitution,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. and the ranking
Democrat on the Judiciary Committee.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   The bill is S.J. Res 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
