<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Civil Rights Heroine  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Daisy Bates is best remembered by the
public as the mentor for nine black students who walked into Little
Rock's all-white Central High School and took a bold stride toward
desegregating American schools. To President Clinton, the civil
rights activist was much more.
</P>
<P>
   She was a brave woman who was harassed and ostracized, yet
inspired confidence and action, Clinton said Thursday at a memorial
service for her. Bates, who died last year, was the only woman who
spoke on the National Mall in August 1963 when the Rev. Martin
Luther King gave his ''I have a dream'' speech, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like Daisy Bates, not only because of what she did at Little
Rock, but because of the way she lived right to the end,'' he said.
''And when she lost things that are painful for any person to lose,
somehow what was left became more pure, more strong -- almost like a
diamond that was chipped away in form and shines more brightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Gatson Bates died Nov. 4, 1999, at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of her funeral, Clinton praised the courage of the
nine black students as they accepted the Congressional Gold Medal
in Washington. Some of the students, dubbed the Little Rock Nine,
were given a standing ovation at the service.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Little Rock Nine, Carlotta Walls-Lanier, said when
she was 10 years old, Bates gave her a job delivering newspapers.
She said she admired Bates because her persistence uncovered ''the
nation's hypocrisy and dirty laundry'' about separate but equal
education.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Bates walked the talk of freedom for all,'' she said.
''She was one of the brighter lights of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whites rioted outside Central High in 1957 when National
Guardsmen, on orders from Gov. Orval Faubus, turned the students
away. President Eisenhower sent in Army troops to escort the
students to class. It was a sign that Washington was going to
enforce the 1954 Supreme Court ruling in Brown vs. Board of
Education that school segregation was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after their tense days at school, the students took
solace at Bates' home. She counseled them on how to stand up to
intimidation and physical threats. Clinton announced at the service
that a process has begun to designate Bates' home a National
Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, Bates said: ''I'm 75{, but I'm not too tired
to stand and do what I can for the cause I believe in. I would like
to see, before I die, that blacks and whites and Christians can all
get together.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wish is not yet a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people gathered in Robinson Auditorium to honor
Bates, who received more than 200 awards for her work toward
achieving equality. Gospel music filled the hall. Pianist Ricky
Banks gave an emotional rendition of the civil rights anthem,
singing ''We shall overcome. We shall overcome, yeah. ... Oooh,
deep in my mind, I do, I do believe -- yes I do. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you believe that?'' he asked the people in the crowd, who
responded with applause and then stood, joined hands, slowly swayed
and sang along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he thought Bates was ''getting a good kick out of
us making such a fuss about her today.'' But Bates' second cousin,
David Neely, an attorney in Elmhurst, Ill., who was one of several
of her relatives who attended the service, remembers her more
serious side.
</P>
<P>
   ''She didn't joke a lot. She was a very serious person,'' he
said. ''Even after she had her first stroke and her second stroke,
her mind continued to work, but she couldn't express herself
because her speech was impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   After the service, Clinton spoke at the dedication of the
William H. Bowen Law School for the University of Arkansas. Bowen,
a Little Rock attorney and businessman, was chief of staff to
Clinton when the president was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen recalled that Clinton had a picture of his maternal
grandparents in the governor's office and two of his grandfather's
sayings hung on the wall. One of them was about public service. The
other said: ''It never hurt a good man to take a few unfair
lickings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
