<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Co. GTE Meets Expectations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Strong sales of data, wireless and
long-distance services in the first-quarter helped
telecommunications company GTE Corp. meet analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months ended March 31, GTE said that net income
fell to to $807 million, or 83 cents per share, from $882 million,
or 90 cents per share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time items in both quarters, GTE said its
operating profits rose to $796 million, or 82 cents per share, up
from $723 million, or 74 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   The results matched the expectations of analysts surveyed by
First Call/Thomson Financial
</P>
<P>
   The Irving-based GTE, which is being acquired by Bell Atlantic
Corp., said its consolidated revenue increased to $6.1 billion,
compared to an adjusted revenue of $5.6 billion in the first
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   GTE said it adjusted the previously reported amount of $5.9
billion downward in part to account for the sale of its government
systems unit, though net income and earnings per share were not
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from domestic wireless services grew 30 percent, and
revenue from its data-services wing jumped 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our core operations continue to produce solid results,
allowing us to invest in higher-growth opportunities,'' said
Charles R. Lee, GTE's chairman and chief executive. ''As a result
we experienced significant growth in our data, wireless and
long-distance businesses as well as in bundled offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, GTE said its Internet unit will spend $11
billion to $13 billion over five years to build its network,
limiting profit growth to less than 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it would spend $1.8 billion to $2 billion
this year -- roughly doubling earlier projections -- on its Genuity
unit, previously called GTE Internetworking, which provides
Internet data services to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   GTE has indicated it plans to spin off Genuity as part of a
proposal to win federal approval for its acquisition by Bell
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   GTE shares fell $2.31\ to $69.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
