<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor, police, question civil rights draft critical of NYPD  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The mayor and police commissioner on Thursday
questioned the political motivations behind a draft report from a
federal civil rights panel suggesting that the New York Police
Department engages in racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Al Sharpton, a frequent critic of the NYPD and the
mayor, praised the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights report for
reinforcing what he says the minority community has known all
along: that police target them more than their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report clearly indicates what we have been saying for some
time -- that there is a real inherent practice of discrimination in
areas of promotions, employment, search and seizure, and other
police activities in the city,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The data validates all of the protests and all of the points
that have been raised since the Abner Louima case,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission began its probe into the police
force last year in the wake of the 1999 shooting of Amadou Diallo
and the 1997 torture of Louima, both at the hands of New York City
cops.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of the commission were appointed by Democrats and
two by Republicans. The panel has no enforcement powers but can
make recommendations to the president, Congress and federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The political makeup of the panel was noted by Giuliani and
Safir, the main targets of the probe. Giuliani called the draft ''a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My reaction to the Civil Rights Commission is they're an
embarrassment,'' he said. ''The chairman of the commission donated
to Hillary Clinton, donated to other Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Frances Berry, the commission's chairwoman, contributed
$250 dollars to the U.S. Senate campaign of Giuliani's Democratic
rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was just as harsh, saying when he testified last year
before the commission, the chairman stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chairman of the committee stopped the proceeding, went out
of her way to praise and welcome Rev. Sharpton. She did not do that
for any other individual. That may give you some indication of her
motivation and where her politics are,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the commission, Kimberly Alton, said she could
not discuss the draft until it had been approved for release by the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   The draft was released to Safir and Giuliani on Wednesday -- they
have 20 days to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-page draft concludes that ''the NYPD's data strongly
suggests that racial profiling plays some role in the
stop-and-frisk practices of the overall department,'' reported The
New York Times on Thursday, which obtained a copy of the draft. For
example, the draft cites data from 1998 indicating that 51 percent
of the people stopped on Staten Island were black, even though the
island's population is only 9 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani disagreed, saying statistics show that the police
department searches a lower percentage of minorities, and police
are only searching people based on the descriptions they are given.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report also suggests that the city create an undefined
mechanism to prosecute serious accusations of police brutality,
instead of using local district attorneys ''who must work with the
police on a routine basis,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the draft suggests the reshaping of the department's
diversity training, which it found defective, and an independent
monitor to review how citizen complaints of police misconduct are
handled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-27-00 1706 </TRAILER>
