<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold War Spy Powers Gets Honors  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER COLEMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Francis Gary Powers, the U-2 spy plane
pilot who was shot down over the Soviet Union and captured in 1960
during the height of the Cold War, is at last being honored for the
fateful mission.
</P>
<P>
   Powers was held by the Soviets for two years. But the former Air
Force captain was considered a CIA employee, not military, so he
was not recognized as a prisoner of war until 21 years after his
death, when declassified Cold War documents in 1998 revealed his
mission was a joint operation of the CIA and Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to make sure he's honored for his
contribution,'' his son, 34-year-old Francis Gary Powers Jr., said
Thursday. ''He never thought of himself as a hero, he thought of
himself as a pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, exactly 40 years after Powers' capture by the
Soviets, his wife, son and daughter will accept the Air Force
Distinguished Flying Cross, the Department of Defense Prisoner of
War Medal and the National Defense Service Medal on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony will take place at Beale Air Force Base, about 60
miles north of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Distinguished Flying Cross award is awarded at the direction
of the president.
</P>
<P>
   When the U-2 plane crashed over Russia, President Eisenhower at
first said it was a weather research plane lost over Turkey. The
United States eventually was forced to admit that Powers was spying
on the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   ''When my father was shot down, captured and shown to be alive
in the Soviet Union, it was the first time a president was caught
lying,'' said Powers Jr., who manages an Internet design and sales
company in Manassas, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Powers was sentenced to 10 years in prison but was exchanged for
KGB master spy Col. Rudolph Abel in 1962. He died in 1977 when a
news helicopter he was piloting crashed in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Growing up he was just Dad. But when he died, the press, the
burial at Arlington, the floods of letters and news reports -- I
figured out that maybe Dad's job was a little different than other
people's,'' Powers Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would always ask, 'Dad, how high were you flying?' And he'd
say, 'Not high enough,''' he said. ''He respected his duty and his
country and never revealed any of the technical information, even
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   One the Net: Powers Jr.'s Cold War Museum is
http://www.coldwar.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
