<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Park Service Bans Snowmobiles  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Snowmobilers, stay away!
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service, saying there's significant evidence
that thousands of snowmobilers are causing environmental damage to
the nation's parks, announced Thursday it is banning the offroad
winter vehicles from most of the park system.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time has come for the National Park Service to pull in its
welcome mat for recreational snowmobiling,'' Assistant Interior
Secretary Donald J. Barry said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The broad ban applies to 25 national parks, recreation areas,
monuments and other park units where snowmobiles have been allowed
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone and Grand Teton in Wyoming are not included in the
immediate ban, but the vehicles are likely to be phased out, or
possibly banned, this fall. However, a formal decision on that must
await completion of a winter-use study, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against snowmobiles is part of a broader Park
Service effort to curtail use of motorized vehicles in parks. In
March, the agency announced new restrictions on the use of Jet Skis
and similar motorized watercraft in some parks, and efforts also
are under way to limit private automobile traffic to reduce
congestion and air pollution at some of the busiest parks.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobilers have been the source of controversy for some time.
Critics contend they are too noisy and disturb park tranquility,
account for much of the winter air pollution in parks, damage
vegetation, and endanger wildlife. Last year, an estimated 180,000
snowmobilers visited the park system, conservationists estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Park Service is finally waking up to the lasting harm
motorized thrill-craft such as snowmobiles cause to parks,'' said
Sean Smith of the San Francisco-based Bluewater Network, which
filed a petition more than a year ago accusing the government of
violating its own regulations by allowing snowmobile use.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 conservation and other park advocacy groups
supported the petition, to which the Park Service responded
Thursday with its action, banning recreational snowmobiling in 10
national parks and 15 national recreation areas, trails, seashores,
monuments and historic sites from Maine to California.
</P>
<P>
   Parks in Alaska and the Voyageurs National Park in Minnesota
were exempted from the ban because Congress specifically allowed
snowmobile use in those parks. The Park Service said the vehicles
also will be allowed in limited areas when they are needed for
access to private land within or adjacent to a park.
</P>
<P>
   Barry of Interior called snowmobiles ''noisy, antiquated
machines that are no longer welcome in our national parks'' and
said the industry ''has had many years to clean up their act and
they haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no final decision on the future of snowmobiling is
expected for Yellowstone -- which stretches into Montana and Idaho --
until November, Doug Schmier, who runs a snowmobile rental service
in West Yellowstone, Mont., fears the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ''The writing's on the wall. ... They're just taking our rights
away from us,'' Schmier said, adding that a ban on snowmobiles
would ''will devastate this community'' that is near an entrance to
the park and relies heavily on income from park visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists and other park advocates have long argued that
since the 1970s, the Park Service has largely ignored the problems
posed by snowmobiles, contrary to its own regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Galvin, the agency's deputy director, acknowledged that
for ''years inattention to our own regulatory standards on
snowmobiles generated the problem we have before us today.'' He
said the agency long failed to monitor environmental harm from
snowmobile use in the parks.
</P>
<P>
   A Park Service study, completed in February, confirmed that
snowmobiles have had a significant impact on air pollution at the
parks. It also found the vehicles had affected wildlife and the
quiet of the parks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the Park Service's newfound concerns are
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Collins of the National Parks and Conservation
Association, a private parks advocacy group, said that the Park
Service's own studies have shown 78 percent of the carbon monoxide
and 94 percent of the hydrocarbons emitted annually within
Yellowstone can be attributed to snowmobiles.
</P>
<P>
   In its petition, the Bluewater Network argued that snowmobiles
are many times dirtier than automobiles that travel through parks.
Over a year, 60,000 snowmobiles enter Yellowstone, expelling 13.8
million pounds of hydrocarbons, compared with 203,000 pounds from
visitors' automobiles, the petition said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1718 </TRAILER>
