<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, Rowland near agreement on budget  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Gov. John G. Rowland and legislative
leaders said Thursday they are close to sealing a budget deal that
will include tax cuts on gasoline and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Tax credits for parents who send their children to private
elementary and secondary schools are not a part of the pact, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The nature of the beast is that nothing is agreed to until
everything is agreed to,'' said Senate Majority Leader George
Jepsen, D-Stamford. ''I think it is very close to being finished.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislative session ends at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting Rowland's proposal to enact a 7-cent gas tax cut
on July 1, Senate Democrats said they're near agreement on that
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it will be 7 cents, although that's not fully
resolved,'' Jepsen said. ''And it will be July 1st.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the gas tax cut, Rowland and Jepsen said they've
agreed on doling out $75 million in tax breaks to the state's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think those will be the two essential ingredients for the
tax cut package,'' Rowland said. ''The spending portion looks like
its pretty much concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats want something in return -- namely an increase on
clothing tax exemptions. Currently, clothing priced below $50 is
tax free. Democrats want to raise that limit to $75.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they want to include that as part of the package, I think
there would be enough room,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never run into a tax cut I didn't like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the legislative session started in February, Democrats
have railed against Rowland's plan for a one-time, 7-cent gas cut.
They argued that such a slash would suck money out of the state's
fund for road and bridge repairs and fail to give drivers relief at
the pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats have since softened their stance, suggesting
last month they would be willing to cut the tax 7 cents over three
years. Then they proposed cutting the 32-cent tax to a quarter for
one year, with the understanding that it could be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk with the gas tax -- in addition to compromising the
transportation fund -- is that it's impossible to control how the
large oil companies ... are not pocketing the profits and not
passing the savings on to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the gas tax cut say it would mean a savings of $85
to $140 a year for a family that drives 30,000 miles. In addition,
lowering the tax would keep Connecticut drivers from crossing state
lines to fill their tanks at cheaper prices, they say.
</P>
<P>
   While they've budged on the gas tax issue, Democratic leaders
are resisting Rowland's pitch to give parents a tuition tax credit
of up to $500 if they send their school-age children to private
school.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he predicts the credit plan will be passed as a
separate bill in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of bipartisan support for that,'' Rowland said.
''I think we'll have a vote on it, but it won't be part of the
negotiated settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jepsen said the plan doesn't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe there is support for tuition tax credits and
I'm personally and completely opposed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the tax credits say they're too much like vouchers
that would drain money from public education.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget -- about $12.2 billion -- would remain about
$50 million under the state's mandatory spending cap, Rowland and
Jepsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's really where we wanted to be,'' Rowland said. In
February, Rowland said he wanted to keep spending $84 million below
the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and lawmakers also want to use the state's surplus to
pay for one-time expenses and retire debt. As of April 1, the state
Comptroller estimated the surplus at $264.5 million. But that
estimate has been reduced to about $240 million, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the fluctuation will not effect the budget deal
he's reached with Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to disrupt the negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
