<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Photographer's Arrest Condemned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- The arrest of an Associated Press
photographer in connection with a newspaper office attack in
Zimbabwe drew protest Thursday from foreign press organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Obed Zilwa, a South African citizen based in Cape Town, was
detained after police claimed he matches an eyewitness description
of a person involved in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The South African Foreign Correspondent's Association sent a
letter to President Robert Mugabe requesting that he personally see
to Zilwa's release.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Zilwa is a respected member of the foreign press corps
based in South Africa and the idea that he should be involved in
terrorist activities is outrageous. Mr. Zilwa -- like other members
of the FCA -- covers news events. He does not organize them,'' wrote
Werner Vogt, chairman of the FCA.
</P>
<P>
   The South African based Freedom of Expression Institute called
Zilwa's detention ''just a further ploy to silence the press and,
more specifically, the foreign press.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute said it was distressed by the disrespect shown to
the media during the recent violence in Zimbabwe and the
government's refusal to protect reporters. It also accused the
government of blaming the foreign press for the country's ills.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa was held in a Harare jail after his arrest Wednesday.
Police have the right to detain him for 48 hours without charge.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jonathan Samkange said Zilwa was being asked to make a
written and sworn statement at the main police precinct in the
Zimbabwe capital, indicating he would spend a second night in
detention before being either charged or released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa was preparing to return home Wednesday from covering the
political crisis in Zimbabwe when police arrested him at Harare's
airport, Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   Police questioned Zilwa for more than seven hours, not only
about the explosion at the offices of The Daily News, but also
about his opinions on Zimbabwe's political parties and the recent
occupation of white-owned land by black squatters, Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We protest in the strongest terms the detention of our
photographer, Obed Zilwa, and we demand his immediate release,''
said Terry Leonard, AP's southern Africa bureau chief. ''We are
protesting to the Zimbabwe government, and we urge other
governments and news organizations to call for an end to the
intimidation of the foreign press. The Associated Press will
provide whatever assistance is needed to help obtain Obed's speedy
release.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press sent a letter of protest to Zimbabwe's
ambassador to the United States, Simbi Veke Mubako, demanding
Zilwa's immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Zilwa matches a description of a person in a car from
which the explosive device was hurled at The Daily News on
Saturday, Samkange said. No one was injured in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa was one of the first photographers on the scene after the
explosion. He had just driven by when he heard the loud noise, and
stopped to ask a police officer what had happened, Samkange said.
The officer said he thought it was a bomb. Zilwa then rushed to his
hotel, fetched his cameras and went back to take photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The Meikles Hotel, where Zilwa and most other international
journalists were staying, is just a few blocks from The Daily News,
and many foreign journalists quickly arrived at the scene. After
the bombing, authorities said the media's quick arrival raised
their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
