<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some doubt state tactics in overseeing Camden finances  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- New Jersey is stricter than almost every
other state in overseeing local government finances. So some
critics want to know why the state didn't do more about Camden's
financial crisis years ago and why it might take a near takeover of
the city to correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Next week a state Superior Court judge will hear arguments on
why the state Division of Community Affairs should assume direct
supervision of nearly all aspects of Camden's financial operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''DCA year after year after year approved the municipal budgets.
Year after year they have certified municipal budget officers, tax
collectors, municipal clerks,'' said Bill Dressel, executive
director of the League of Municipalities. ''The question has to be
asked, why weren't affirmative steps taken when these things were
uncovered.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials allege that Camden officials repeatedly ignored
warnings to correct faulty financial practices. Camden -- where 70
cents of every city dollar spent comes from state aid -- does not
keep proper financial records, including a general ledger and an
account of city payouts, all of which are required by law, the
state says.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of Community Affairs already oversees much of
Camden's operations through a Financial Review Board put in place
last year. If the judge agrees after the May 5 hearing, the next
phase would be a complete supervision, one step shy of a takeover
of the New Jersey's poorest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state already has power, oversight functions. What have
they done with the power to date. How are they going to solve the
problem with more power'' Dressel said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Local Finance Board told the attorney general on
April 14 to sue Camden and its officials after Camden failed to
comply with a dozen orders outlined in a state ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the state Division of Community Affairs had given
Camden two weeks to correct the long-standing problems. The
deadline came March 24, a day after Mayor Milton Milan was named in
an indictment charging him with extortion, money laundering and
mail fraud. Authorities say Milan accepted payoffs and gifts from
city contractors and took bribes from organized crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne R. Bryant, D-Camden, at a Senate budget committee
hearing Wednesday, asked Division of Community Affairs Commissioner
Jane M. Kenny why the state wants full supervision of the city now,
when it had the chance to fix the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant argued that the division should have used its oversight
powers before threatening the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me to give you more powers if you don't exercise the ones
you already have doesn't make sense,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenny claimed that state supervisors were thwarted by
Milan's administration ''at nearly every turn.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can stop the hemorrhaging and we've done that. But you
can't make government work efficiently and effectively,'' Kenny
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Milan threatened to file bankruptcy before he accepted
a deal to allow a state financial review board some oversight of
city operations. But despite that monitoring, the state alleges
Camden officials continued to ignore the problems.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the state says Camden filed annual audits more
than two years after they were due. When the audits were filed,
some contained a notice from the auditor that the examinations
could not be done because Camden kept no records of its
expenditures. And in 1998, Camden overspent its $116 million budget
by nearly $500,000, according to the state's legal brief.
</P>
<P>
   ''We lay down the rules. Did Camden follow the rules, no. That's
the reality,'' Ulrich Steinberg, the state's director of the
Division of Local Government Services, told the Senate panel.
</P>
<P>
   Milan did not return three telephone messages left at his City
Hall office on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is the only state that requires each town to submit
its yearly budget for approval. The state also mandates that towns
include detailed information about accounts and expenditures in
their budgets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
