<HEADLINE> Pork Bellies at 4-Yr. High  </HEADLINE>
By BENNIE M. CURRIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pork belly futures closed at the highest level in nearly four
years Thursday as demand for bacon from fast-food restaurants put
pressure on fresh supplies for a second straight day.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, platinum rose sharply while crude
oil prices increased slightly.
</P>
<P>
   While hog futures closed mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, pork bellies continued to show the effect of crackling
demand for bacon, which is made from hogs' bellies.
</P>
<P>
   Pork bellies for May delivery are at the highest price levels
since August 1996, up more than 77 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Market observers said the trend to add bacon to sandwiches,
pizzas and other fast-food items is pitting consumers' taste buds
against supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting stronger demands in what normally is an off-type
season,'' said Chuck Levitt, an analyst with Alaron Trading Corp.,
a brokerage firm in Chicago. ''The prime consuming period is the
summer when people or vacationing and have more time for big
breakfasts. Meanwhile, restaurants are cooking hamburgers longer to
kill bacteria and are adding bacon to make up for the fat that's
being cooked out.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pork consumption is at a 20-year high, according to
the National Pork Producers Council. Pork sold to U.S. food
companies increased 17 percent between 1996 and 1999, with bacon
making up nearly one-fifth of all sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon was the most popular product used by restaurants last
year, according to the National Pork Producers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The spurt in pork consumption could send prices as high as $1.05
before the interest in bacon settles down, Levitt added.
</P>
<P>
   May pork bellies rose .20 cents to 99.92 cents a pound. Also,
June live cattle fell .32 cent to 69.40 cents a pound, while May
feeder cattle rose .10 cent to 84.32 cents a pound and June lean
hogs fell .42 cent to 77.05 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum futures
ended 5 percent higher amid continued speculation about Russian
exports. Skittish investors have been dumping the metal in response
to last week's announcement that Russia's largest producer, Norilsk
Nickel, was resuming exports.
</P>
<P>
   Platinum futures jumped to a one-week high of $463.50 for July
before settling at $462.10, up $24 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the New York Merc floor, crude oil futures closed
higher as investors sought bargains after two days of losses,
according to market-watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Light, sweet crude for June delivery rose 77 cents, or 1
percent, to $25.42 a barrel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1804 </TRAILER>
