<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child-Rearing Costs Jump To $160K  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- That new baby will cost a bundle. The cost of
rearing a child born last year will be $160,140 for a middle-income
family, up about 2 percent from 1998, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For low-income families, those earning less than $36,800, the
cost of rearing a child through age 17 is lower -- $117,000 --
because they spend less on food, housing and other needs. For
high-income families, those earning more than $61,900, the total
expenditure is estimated at $233,850.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department compiles the estimates each year to
help state agencies and courts determine payments for child support
and foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the modest increase in
child expenditures last year is ''a testament to the amazingly
strong U.S. economy and our low rate of inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   The department estimates a middle-income family could expect to
spend $8,450 to $9,530 a year on each child, depending on the age.
</P>
<P>
   Costs vary by region, with the highest expenses in the urban
West, followed by the urban Northeast and the urban South. Rural
areas and the urban Midwest are the least expensive places to rear
children.
</P>
<P>
   Housing is the biggest expenditure, $53,310, or 33 percent of
the cost of raising a child for 17 years. Food is next at $27,990,
or 18 percent of the total. Next comes transportation costs at
$22,980. Child care and education expenditures are estimated at
$15,750.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, total child expenditures for a middle-income family
were estimated at $25,230.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   USDA's Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion:
www.usda.gov/cnpp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
