<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian Shipwreck Leaves 14 Dead  </HEADLINE>
By JESSICA ROBERTSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- A ship carrying nearly 300 Haitian boat
people ran aground in the southern Bahamas, and 14 victims died
apparently of dehydration, Bahamian and U.S. officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard rushed rescuers to the scene, immediately
evacuating 31 people suffering from severe hypothermia, dehydration
and kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fifteen of the migrants still on Flamingo Cay are in pretty
poor shape,'' said Petty Officer Gibran Soto. Two Coast Guard
helicopters deployed from Clearwater, Fla., were continuing the
rescue Thursday afternoon, and four Coast Guard cutters would soon
be on site.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Bahamas sent a Defense Force vessel to pick up
survivors, who will be returned to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   The boat was carrying about 275 Haitians -- the largest single
load of migrants to reach the Bahamas in years. It ran aground
Wednesday afternoon off Flamingo Cay in the Ragged Island chain,
Bahamian immigration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Three sailing vessels spotted the wreck and alerted officials,
Soto said by telephone from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   When the Coast Guard arrived that night, they found 14 of the
Haitians already dead, Soto said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip through Atlantic Ocean waters to the Bahamas or to
Florida's coast is a risky journey, but more and more impoverished
Haitians have been willing to take.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, another 122 Haitians landed on Inagua, the
southernmost island in the Bahamian chain just over 100 miles from
Haiti's northern coast. And on Friday another group of 224 Haitians
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Florida said they arrested 15 Haitians dropped off
Wednesday night near Key Biscayne by a motor boat running without
lights. The smuggling vessel was stopped by customs officers, who
arrested two suspects, one Bahamian and one Haitian, according to a
statement from the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Haitians said they paid $4,000 each for the trip, Border
Patrol spokesman Joseph Mellia said.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic increase in the number of Haitians seeking refuge
in the Bahamas coincides with increasing violence in Haiti as the
nation gears up for long-postponed legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the director of Haiti's National Migration Office, Carol
Joseph, said he did not believe politics had a hand in the
emigration.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sign of economic despair,'' he said Thursday, noting
that it takes months to prepare such voyages and that most migrants
were subsistence farmers from Haiti's northwest, not the capital
where most of the political violence has been occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian officials say they have no idea how many Haitians
manage to reach the islands undetected. Though there is no official
figure, some estimate as many as 40,000 Haitians live among the
300,000 Bahamians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
