<DOCNO> APW20000427.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sales Lift Dow Chemical Earnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) -- Dow Chemical Co. said Thursday its
first-quarter earnings rose 26 percent as a big increase in sales
volume overcame higher raw material and energy costs.
</P>
<P>
   Dow said it earned $415 million, or $1.83 a share, in the three
months ending March 31. The company earned $329 million, or $1.47 a
share, in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter results exceed Wall Street expectations. A
survey of 13 analysts by First Call/Thomson Financial had predicted
earnings of $1.65 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 22 percent to $5.38 billion from $4.42 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares rose $3.43}, or more than 3 percent, on the news to
$109 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Dow said its energy and raw material costs rose $700 million in
the quarter, while its prices rose only $540 million, or 12
percent. But that was offset by a 10 percent increase in its sales
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Chief financial officer J. Pedro Reinhard said the results
''demonstrate once again our ability to overcome major hurdles such
as the substantial increase in raw material and energy costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales were particularly strong in the Asia-Pacific region, where
volume rose 26 percent, compared with a more modest 3 percent in
the United States. Overall, non-U.S. sales volume rose 17 percent,
including 12 percent in Europe and 10 percent in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Midland-based Dow has announced plans to merge with Union
Carbide of Danbury, Conn., to form the world's second-largest
chemical company behind DuPont Co. The merger has received
stockholder approval but remains under review by regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
