<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel OKs Anti-Suicide Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Right-to-life supporters cheered a Senate
panel's passage Thursday of a bill that would thwart Oregon's
landmark law allowing physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''A sad chapter in our nation's history may be nearing an end,''
said Richard Doerflinger of the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-8 Senate Judiciary Committee vote was largely along party
lines, with just one Republican, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania,
voting against the bill and one Democrat, Joe Biden of Delaware,
voting for it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. and a leading bill opponent, said he was
heartened because the committee approved a similar bill by an 11-6
margin in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still think we've got an uphill battle, but today was
certainly better than we expected,'' Wyden said. ''We've gained
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   No Senate floor vote has been set, but the bill's author -- Don
Nickles of Oklahoma, the Senate's No. 2 Republican -- said he has
the votes to pass it and the 60 votes needed to shut off a
threatened filibuster by Wyden. The House already has passed a
version.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has not taken a position on the bill, which is
supported by some groups that opposed the 1998 version, including
the American Medical Association and the National Hospice
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would revoke the licenses to prescribe drugs of
doctors who deliberately use federally controlled substances to aid
a patient's death. Violators also would face a 20-year prison
sentence, according to the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   All 43 people who have taken their lives under Oregon's Death
With Dignity Act have used federally controlled substances.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also authorizes $5 million in annual grants for
medical schools to teach doctors better ways to treat pain.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday's vote, Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
amended the bill with changes sought by the AMA, including a
provision saying states will continue to regulate medical
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The new version also sets a ''clear and convincing evidence''
standard for federal authorities to prove doctors were trying to
aid in a patient's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terminally ill patients deserve better pain control
management,'' Hatch said. ''I am troubled by laws that single out
these patients as candidates for assisted suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel said the bill would hinder doctors'
ability to treat pain.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., told of holding her husband as
he was dying of cancer and suffering excruciating pain. Physicians
who give out large doses of pain medication to dying patients would
risk investigation by the Drug Enforcement Administration under the
bill, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's just plain wrong,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide opponents have pressed for the bill since June 1998,
when Attorney General Janet Reno ruled federal drug agents cannot
move against doctors who help terminally ill patients die under
Oregon's assisted suicide law.
</P>
<P>
   The act was approved by 51 percent of Oregonians in 1994, and 60
percent voted against repealing it in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar could the main ally of bill opponents, as senators
may be unwilling to chew up precious floor time in an election year
with lengthy debates on amendments Wyden would offer.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Senate Judiciary Committee:
http://www.senate.gov/~judiciary/
</P>
<P>
   Compassion In Dying: http://www.compassionindying.org/
</P>
<P>
   Physicians For Compassionate Care: http://www.pccef.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
