<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regis Has Artery-Clearing Procedure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Regis Philbin underwent a procedure that
successfully cleared a blocked artery, the television host said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin had the procedure done Monday, while he was on vacation,
and stayed one night in the hospital, he said on his morning show,
''Live With Regis and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm fine, I'm fine,'' he assured co-host Kathie Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old has been juggling his talk show with nighttime
duties on ABC's hit ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   He said doctors had been monitoring a small blockage on his
right side since 1993, when he had a similar one removed from his
left side. A stress test several weeks ago revealed that the right
blockage had grown, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it got a little heavy, so they decided, 'Would you like to
come in and have an angioplasty?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin instead ended up getting an atherectomy, a procedure in
which doctors use a rotating shaver on the end of a catheter to
clear coronary arteries blocked by plaque. The catheter is
generally inserted through a blood vessel in the leg or arm and
threaded through vessels to the blocked artery.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's just the Roto-Rooter,'' Philbin said. ''It's quicker
and safer,'' than angioplasty, which involves a small inflatable
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin said he'd kept the procedure quiet because he didn't
want to worry anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'What am I going to call everybody? ... (Walt Disney
Co. Chairman) Michael Eisner would be jumping out a window. I don't
want to do that to him, so I just had it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney owns ABC, which has enjoyed a major boost from
''Millionaire's'' high ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
