<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Up 143; Dow Down 57  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks regained leadership of the
stock market Thursday, rising sharply and helping blue-chip names
shake off a pair of economic reports that suggested more
interest-rate increases are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 143.94 to close at 3,774.03.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which fell as much as 197
points in early trading, pared its loss to just 57.40, closing at
10,888.10.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 rose 3.93 to 1,464.92.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications stocks led the Nasdaq's advance after posting
strong corporate earnings reports. MCI WorldCom rose 4{ to 45]
after announcing it beat Wall Street's first-quarter earnings
expectations by 1 cent a share. The telecom company saw net income
soar to $1.3 billion from $730 million a year ago on surging data
and Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications company Nextel narrowed its
first-quarter loss and rose 8 5/16 to 112 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AT&AMP;T's wireless business made a successful, if
modest, debut in trading on the New York Stock Exchange, rising
from an offering price of 29{ to 31 15/16. The tracking stock,
which reflects just one segment of AT&AMP;T's operations, is the
largest initial public offering in history, with 360 million shares
valued at a total of $10.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T itself fell 3 to 48.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of large-capitalization technology stocks rose.
Qualcomm gained 6\ to 103{ and Applied Materials rose 9~ to 100
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The strength in telecom and technology helped the broad market
recover from initial weakness in the wake of government reports on
the gross domestic product and the Employment Cost Index. Many on
Wall Street had been fearful that one or both would show that the
economy was growing much too fast for the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   The reports confirmed that the economy is on a tear. The gross
domestic product grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate during the first
three months of 2000, the Commerce Department said. But many
economists had anticipated a 6 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The more troubling statistic to inflation-wary traders: the
Employment Cost Index. In the first quarter, the index rose 1.4
percent, the biggest quarterly advance in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Economists fear rising wage pressures will stimulate inflation,
prompting more and steeper interest rate increases by the Fed.
Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy is not showing the signs of slowing that the Fed
is looking for, and investors are correct to be concerned about
that,'' said Eric Wiegand, director of the private client group at
Warburg Pincus.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are most sensitive to inflation, led the
Dow lower. Citigroup slipped 27/32 to 61{ and J.P. Morgan fell 3
3/16 to 131].
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's ability to shrug off the inflation reports provided
the most conclusive sign to date that the technology sector has
stabilized, said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime
Charter Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq has been trying to hammer out a bottom,'' he said.
''The fact that it was able to rally despite some bad news on the
economic front tells me that it's finally found one.''
</P>
<P>
   Massive selloffs earlier this month knocked the Nasdaq as much
as 34 percent below its March 10 record of 5,048.62. The last
crushing selloff came on Monday, when the Nasdaq shed 161 points.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's purge may have been the last for a while, Bleier
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is that a lot of Nasdaq stocks have been
crushed,'' he said. ''It will be a more selective environment going
forward, but many stocks will do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's gains, the Nasdaq is about 25 percent below its
peak and 7 percent below its level at the start of 2000. But since
last April 27, the Nasdaq has risen 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange Thursday, declining issues
outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-9 margin. Volume totaled 1.31
billion shares, compared with 1.21 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 10.34 to
494.58.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 2.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
lost 1.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
