<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall on Inflation Fears  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The price of 30-year Treasury bonds fell
Thursday as traders reacted to two strong economic reports that
again put the spotlight on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark bond slipped 19/32 point, or $5.94 per $1,000 in
face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose
to 5.98 percent from 5.94 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders responded to a Labor Department report that wages and
benefits for American workers climbed by 4.3 percent during the 12
months ending in March, the sharpest advance in eight years. In
addition, the Commerce Department said the U.S. economy, propelled
by the biggest jump in consumer spending in nearly 17 years, grew
at a 5.4 percent annual rate during the first three months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That news reinforced expectations that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates at its May 16 meeting to hold down inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Both rising interest rates and rising inflation hurt investments
like bonds, which pay a fixed return.
</P>
<P>
   Losses might even have been greater, except for the Treasury
Department's repurchase of an additional $3 billion repurchase of
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury on Thursday bought back 24 issues of 30-year bonds
maturing between February 2015 and August 2025. The bonds carried
yields ranging from 6.250 percent to 11.250 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, prices of short-term notes fell
between \ point and 5/16 point, while intermediate notes fell 15/32
to 11/16, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.73 percent as the
discount fell 0.01 percentage point from Wednesday to 5.58 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.05 as the discount rate rose 0.05 point to
5.80 percent. One-year yields were 6.13 percent as the discount
rose 0.03 percentage point to 5.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, remained unchanged at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 13/32 point to 94 5/16. The average
yield to rose to 6.01 percent from 5.98 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
