<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's New Leader Seeks Support  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy's new premier courted an unenthusiastic
Parliament on Thursday, saying his stopgap center-left coalition
would concentrate on electoral reforms if lawmakers let it serve
out the 11 months until general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Giuliano Amato outlined the aims of his 2-day-old
government to the Chamber of Deputies, where a vote of confidence
on Friday will determine whether his unstable, eight-party
coalition gets a chance to see the plans through.
</P>
<P>
   ''A little legislation and a lot of action, results: That's what
we want to do in the little time available,'' the 61-year-old
political veteran told the 630-seat lower house.
</P>
<P>
   Amato needs 50 percent of the vote, plus one -- 316 votes,
assuming there is a full house Friday. His prospects improved
Thursday when the wavering Green party decided to stick with the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news came later when a smaller party, the Republicans, said
it was leaning toward abstaining in the vote, threatening what for
Amato promised to be at best a few-vote margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Amato first served as premier for 10 months in the early 1990s,
earning respect for seeing through rigorous budget cuts at a time
when corruption scandals were pulling apart Italy's Cold War
political order.
</P>
<P>
   He was treasury minister under the 18-month government of former
Communist Massimo D'Alema, who resigned when forces allied with
conservative media magnate Silvio Berlusconi triumphed in April 16
regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left turned to Amato to put together a new
government. He came up with a reshuffled version of the old one,
which was divided by squabbles over Cabinet seats and held together
chiefly by the desire to stave off Berlusconi's demand for
immediate general elections.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left has argued it must stay in power to see through
electoral reforms, particularly a May referendum that would do away
with a proportional allotment system credited with giving Italy's
many tiny parties undue influence.
</P>
<P>
   Amato's introductory speech stressed the electoral reforms, but
drew some of the warmest response when he rejected links between
immigration and crime -- saying his own uncle was no criminal when
he went to America to look for work.
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, he said he would push for an Italian seat on
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to work for more flexibility in the labor market to
fight unemployment, telling lawmakers: ''We need to take the hand
brake off the Italian economy.''
</P>
<P>
   That and his promises to fight crime followed much the same line
as Berlusconi's conservatives. Berlusconi said the ideas sounded
less than fresh to his own ears.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we expected thunderbolts, we were struck by boredom
instead,'' the TV mogul said after Amato's speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1819 </TRAILER>
