<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Say Giuliani Likely OK  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Doctors said Thursday that if Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's prostate cancer was detected early he has a good
prognosis and the treatment should not keep him from continuing his
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Formerly most patients had prostate cancer which invaded or
extended beyond the prostate gland itself,'' said Dr. Steven
Carabell, chief of radiation oncology at Catholic Medical Centers
of Brooklyn and Queens. ''Now in most patients it is detected while
the cancer is still limited to the prostate gland and has not
spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his cancer was diagnosed at an early stage. He
said he had not decided on a course of treatment and did not know
how it would affect his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second-most common type of cancer in American men, behind skin
cancer. The American Cancer Society estimates that 180,400 American
men will be diagnosed with prostate cancer in 2000 and 31,900 will
die of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer spreads slowly in elderly men, and their doctors
often recommend leaving the cancer untreated as the men are likely
to die of other ailments.
</P>
<P>
   But a man of Giuliani's age, 55, will likely be advised to
choose between surgery to remove the cancerous prostate and
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harmon Eyre, chief medical officer of the cancer society,
said both treatments are about equally successful, with five-year
survival rates of more than 90 percent. And neither course of
treatment should keep the mayor out of commission for longer than a
few weeks, the doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main types of radiation therapy for prostate
cancer: external beam radiation, in which high-energy X-rays are
aimed at the prostate gland in a series of treatments over several
weeks, and the implantation of radioactive ''seeds'' directly in
the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Cancer Society: http://www.cancer.org
</P>
<P>
   National Cancer Institute: http://www.nci.nih.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1820 </TRAILER>
