<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papers Look At Vietnam War Policy  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the morning of Oct. 22, 1972, Henry
Kissinger believed he had achieved a breakthrough agreement to end
the Vietnam War. By the end of the day, South Vietnam's leader was
accusing him of conniving with the Soviets and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Council files made public Thursday, 25 years
after the war's end, include previously top secret government
cables that trace Kissinger's agonizing quest to get South
Vietnamese agreement for a peace accord with the North Vietnamese
communists 2 1/2 years before the fall of Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are among 130,000 pages from the Nixon presidency
released by the National Archives. Most deal with foreign policy
matters.
</P>
<P>
   One cable, with some portions still blacked out, reports that
Laotian Prime Minister Souvanna Phouma had ''concluded the North
Vietnamese have accepted that they have lost and are willing to
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable was dated four days before Kissinger, then the
president's national security chief, declared to the world that
''peace is at hand.'' Negotiations later collapsed, and the war
went on. The United States withdrew its forces in 1973 and the
South Vietnamese surrendered on April 30, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Souvanna, who had remained neutral in the war, was described as
elated by the prospect of peace and hopeful that the North
Vietnamese would not try to gain more Laotian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Cables to Washington from Kissinger and U.S. Ambassador
Ellsworth Bunker, all on Oct. 22, document the up-and-down course
of the talks with South Vietnamese President Nguyen Van Thieu.
</P>
<P>
   Bunker reported that Thieu began the day's meetings in ''a
highly emotional state,'' accusing Kissinger and embassy personnel
of leaking statements concerning the peace proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thieu's attitude became more relaxed as we examined the
alternatives before us,'' Bunker cabled. ''We (Bunker and
Kissinger) both left with the impression we had finally made a
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from Laos, Thailand and Cambodia was all optimistic,
Bunker said in other cables.
</P>
<P>
   But in a later message, after an evening meeting with Thieu,
Bunker said Thieu declared he was being sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   Thieu was quoted as telling Kissinger he thought the United
States had connived with the Soviet Union and China. He was
concerned about North Vietnamese who would remain in the South
under the proposed peace. ''The South Vietnamese people will assume
that we have been sold out by the U.S. and that North Vietnam has
won the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger told Thieu he resented the charge that he was in
collusion with the Soviet Union and China.
</P>
<P>
   The cable said that just before his return to Washington,
Kissinger saw Thieu again briefly and told him he considered his
course ''suicidal for him and for his country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1821 </TRAILER>
