<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Fund Assets Are Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's money market mutual funds
fell in the past week, the Investment Company Institute reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Total money market assets stood at $1.669 trillion for the week
ended Wednesday, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
Assets for the previous week were $1.697 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of retail money market mutual funds fell by $23.52
billion in the latest week to $980.85 billion, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category fell
by $17.11 billion to $817.64 billion. Tax-exempt fund assets fell
by $6.42 billion to $163.22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of institutional money market funds fell by $4.42 billion
to $688.43 billion for the same period. Among institutional funds,
taxable money market fund assets fell by $3.67 billion to $639.85
billion; assets of tax-exempt funds fell by $753.8 million to
$48.57 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 5.45 percent from 5.47 percent the
previous week, said Money Fund Report, a service of iMoneyNet Inc.
in Westboro, Mass. The 30-day average yield rose to 5.46 percent
from 5.44 percent, according to Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day compounded yield fell to 5.60 percent from 5.62
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield rose to
5.61 percent from 5.59 percent, Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
47 days, down from 48 days, said Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage
yield available on money market accounts fell to 2.03 percent as of
Wednesday from 2.04 percent a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing
checking accounts rose to 0.84 percent from 0.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.96 percent
on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged from the previous
week. Yields were 5.33 percent on 1-year CDs, down from 5.34
percent; 5.62 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 5.64 percent; and
5.99 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 6.00 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
