<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Net Unit Fuels MCI WorldCom Gains  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOORE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- MCI WorldCom, riding the performance of
its Internet, data and international operations, reported
first-quarter earnings nearly double from a year ago and slightly
ahead of Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second biggest long-distance phone company said
Thursday it earned $1.3 billion, or 44 cents per share in the first
three months of 2000. That compared with earnings of $730 million,
or 24 cents per share, during the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   After the report, MCI WorldCom's stock gained more than 11
percent to end the day at $45.37{, up $4.50, on the Nasdaq Stock
Market. Wall Street analysts had expected earnings of 43 cents a
share for the quarter, according to a survey by First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter revenues rose to $9.15 billion, compared to $8.03
billion a year ago, excluding Embratel, a Brazilian phone company
part-owned by MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   ''The revenue was a little bit better than expected and really
strong on the Internet side,'' said Ramkrishna Kasargod, an analyst
with Morgan Keegan &AMP; Co. in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Data, Internet and international revenues grew a combined 32
percent to $4.6 billion, accounting for about half of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Like many phone companies grappling with falling rates in local
and long-distance services, MCI WorldCom has been placing a greater
emphasis on faster-growing, higher-margin areas such as providing
network and Web services for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company launched a new initiative --
dubbed ''generation d'' -- to provide one-stop shopping for
businesses needing services including Web site hosting, design and
domain registration.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts and reporters, Vice Chairman
John Sidgmore said revenue from Internet operations will increase
in the coming months with the renewal of a contract to carry
network traffic for America Online. Sidgmore also said the deal
could lead to more opportunities after AOL merges with Time Warner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
