<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK, Zimbabwe Meeting Yields Little  </HEADLINE>
By MARA D. BELLABY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British and Zimbabwean officials on Thursday
failed to reach agreement on ending deadly clashes between black
squatters and white farmers in the African nation, prompting
Britain to withhold land reform aid.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, weary and clearly
frustrated by the talks with a visiting Zimbabwean delegation, told
reporters that Britain would freeze $57 million earmarked for land
reform until Zimbabwe's president, Robert Mugabe, halts the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made it clear we could not take any of these steps against a
background of occupations and violence,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people have been killed in the former British colony since
armed black squatters began occupying white-owned farms in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ''An end to the violence and the occupations is the essential
next step,'' Cook said. ''In the event that these conditions are
met, we are willing to enter into dialogue and discussions with the
government of Zimbabwe on how to take forward our commitment to
fund land reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Zimbabwe delegation, which held a separate briefing at
the Zimbabwe High Commission after the talks concluded, said it did
not accept the conditions set by Britain.
</P>
<P>
   While giving assurances that Zimbabwe was working to solve
resolve the dispute, the delegation head, Minister John Nkomo, said
''the problems we have at home'' were not legitimate reasons for
Britain to hold up the funding, which was originally agreed to in
1998. Britain later blocked release of the funds after claiming
that the land was being distributed to Mugabe's cronies and not to
poor, black Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a real problem which we did not create, which we must
resolve,'' Nkomo said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has said it would provide $57 million to give blacks a
chance to own some of their nation's most productive farmland. Cook
also said that he would help organize funding from the
international community.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook reiterated Britain's demands that the land reform be
fair and that Zimbabwe prove its commitment to free democratic
elections first.
</P>
<P>
   The Zimbabwe delegation said the demand for free elections --
expected in May -- has already been met.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our response was in fact that the process is on,'' said Nkomo.
''Our commitment to the holding of elections in accordance with the
constitution is unquestioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's opponents have charged that the forcible occupations --
supported the president -- are designed to boost his lagging
popularity before the parliamentary elections and intimidate the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change. The farmers and black
activists who have been killed in recent weeks have had connections
to the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Zimbabwe police announced sweeping new powers to
curb political activity, a move they said was necessary to stop the
political violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1842 </TRAILER>
