<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albert Pirro alleges campaign to derail DA's career  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- District Attorney Jeanine Pirro's
husband said Thursday that a new allegation in his tax fraud case,
focusing on his wife, is part of a federal campaign to smear her
and ''derail her career.''
</P>
<P>
   'Everybody knows that my wife could have been and should have
been a statewide candidate for political office by now,'' Albert
Pirro said at a news conference. ''The only thing that has held her
back is the fact that her husband ... has been subjected to
constant spotlight, scrutiny and criticism for business
transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White had no comment, spokesman Herb
Haddad said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro, one of the state's top lobbyists and a major
Republican fund-raiser, spoke the day after prosecutors alleged
that a loan taken out by Jeanine Pirro in 1993, ostensibly to buy a
$40,000 Mercedes, was ''an empty financial transaction, a sham''
used by her husband to cover up tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pirro, Westchester County's biggest vote-getter, a national
TV commentator and a veteran of People magazine's ''50 Most
Beautiful People'' list, will not comment until the case is
concluded, said spokeswoman Anne Marie Corbalis.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney has never been charged in the case. It
alleges that her husband and his brother Anthony, who was Pirro's
accountant, conspired to hide about $1 million in Albert Pirro's
income by masking personal expenses as business deductions. Pirro
says he has paid all the back taxes and blames his brother for bad
tax returns. His brother blames him.
</P>
<P>
   Though the indictment alleges that many of the expenses were
family-oriented, like vacations, baby sitters, toys and veterinary
expenses, the alleged loan arrangement is the closest connection so
far between the district attorney and her husband's tax case.
</P>
<P>
   ''These allegations are totally nonsense,'' Albert Pirro said
Thursday. Prosecutors are ''trying to create ... artificial issues
to inflame and influence the jury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro's lead attorney, Gustave Newman, said in court Thursday
that he would not be arguing that Pirro was a victim of ''selective
prosecution.'' But Pirro said later that ''the motives in this case
will be coming out and will be issues in this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the defense has information that federal agents
pressured witnesses into testifying by threatening to prosecute
them ''in the event that they do not cooperate with the point of
view that the agents were proferring.''
</P>
<P>
   The new court papers say that Albert Pirro, in the name of one
of his many companies, leased a 1989 Mercedes-Benz for his wife in
late 1988. The lease payments were fraudulently deducted as
business expenses through 1992, although the car was used by Mrs.
Pirro, then a county judge, ''for personal purposes,'' the papers
say.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1992, she was considering a run for district attorney
and Albert Pirro, ''anticipating that the car might become an issue
in the upcoming campaign,'' tried to make it look as if Mrs. Pirro
had purchased the car, the court papers allege.
</P>
<P>
   She took out a $41,000 loan in January 1993 and paid her
husband's company $39,470 from her personal account. However, the
prosecution says, the company made the payments on Mrs. Pirro's
loan and paid it off entirely in November 1993, the month she was
elected district attorney. It then sold the car to a dealership for
$32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The loan taken by Jeanine Pirro was an empty financial
transaction, a sham intended to make it look like Jeanine Pirro had
purchased the vehicle ... and was responsible for the payments,''
the papers say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
