<HEADLINE> NTRA Thoroughbred Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- News and notes from around the Thoroughbred
racing world, compiled by NTRA Communications (All time EDT):
</P>
<P>
NTRA RACING EXPERIENCE HITS THE ROAD WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA Racing Experience, the first national mobile marketing
tour for Thoroughbred racing, will debut at Churchill Downs on May
3 during Kentucky Derby Week. The 60-foot interactive exhibit will
be on display in the Louisville area through th e Derby on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA Racing Experience will be located at Churchill's
Longfield Gate on Wednesday beginning at 11 a.m and lasting through
the final race. On Thursday, the exhibit will move to the Churchill
Downs infield for the Festival of the Fields at 11 a.m. The Chow
Wagon at Papa John's Cardinal Stadium will host the display on
Friday from 11 a.m.-11 p.m. On Saturday, the truck will be located
at the Churchill Downs Sports Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
DERBY FAVORITE PUTS ON EARLY MORNING SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, the likely favorite for the May 6 Kentucky
Derby, turned a routine morning jog into a spectacle Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   While being led off the track just near the clockers' stand, the
son of Mr. Prospector reared on his back feet and tossed exercise
rider Nuno Santos. Losing his balance, the three-year-old colt fell
to the racetrack on his backside and rolled ov er. He came to his
feet, somewhat ''startled'' according to his trainer Neil Drysdale,
who led the colt off the track.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the colt's notorious behavior would affect his
performance on Derby Day, Drysdale said, ''I think 130,000 people
may get his attention. He's fascinated by people.''
</P>
<P>
JOCKEY TO BE HONORED AT SUFFOLK DOWNS
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Baez, a champion jockey in New England, will be honored
Saturday at Suffolk Downs in East Boston, Mass., when the feature
race of the day, the Faneuil Hall Stakes, is permanently renamed
the Rudy Baez Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Baez, who is paralyzed from the chest down as a
result of a racing accident at Rockingham Park on August 4, 1999,
will be at the track to greet fans in his first public appearance
since the accident.
</P>
