<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Polio Eradication  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The goal of wiping out polio worldwide is within
reach but trouble spots still exist, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial progress has been reported in all World Health
Organization regions since 1988, the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention said.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Pacific Region is expected to be declared polio-free
this year. The American region was the first in 1994. A region must
have no polio cases found for at least three years to be declared
free of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Assembly resolved in 1988 to wipe out polio
worldwide by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC said the number of known or suspected countries
originating polio cases decreased from 50 to 30 from 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC said occurrences remain high in northern India and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Significant decreases were recorded in the eastern Mediterranean
Region and Southeast Asian Region in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Polio circulation in the African Region is confined largely to
the Horn of Africa and western and central Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
