<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Squabbling Endanger Barak's Gov't  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A long-running dispute between two members of
Israel's coalition government escalated Thursday, endangering Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's efforts to make peace with the Palestinians
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The dovish, secular Meretz party announced it would bolt from
the coalition rather than hand government funds to the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party to run its corrupt and debt-ridden school
system.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz leader Yossi Sarid, who is Israel's education minister,
has refused to turn over administration of the Shas education
system to his deputy minister Meshulam Nahari, who is from the Shas
party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has indicated that he will rule in favor of Shas in the
dispute, according to Israeli media.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs the support of Shas, the third largest faction in
the parliament, to assure a majority in favor of peace deals he
hopes to make with Syria and the Palestinians, including deep
territorial concessions in the Golan Heights and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   That has opened the way for Shas to make a series of escalating
demands on Barak, especially money for its school system. Barak has
appealed to Meretz to swallow the pill for the sake of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz refuses, charging that Shas must not be allowed to
supervise a system that it has already mismanaged. ''We will not
write a corrupt check ... and it will not come from our
government,'' said Trade Minister Ran Cohen of Meretz.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid said if Meretz quits the government over the Shas crisis,
it would stay in the coalition for a limited period of time to give
Barak a chance to achieve peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Shas say that its voters are mostly hawkish opponents
of concessions to the Arabs, and the 17 members of the Shas
parliament faction would vote against peace deals even if their
demands are met.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leader Eli Ishai said votes on peace issues would not be
connected to other matters. He said the party would vote according
to the rulings of its Council of Torah Sages, headed by Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
   If Meretz, with ten seats in parliament, quit Barak's
government, he would still command a majority in the house. If Shas
pulled out, another religious party might follow. Barak would be
hard pressed to muster a majority, and his government could fall.
</P>
<P>
   That could lead to new elections, delaying peace efforts for
many months.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was elected prime minister in May 1999, defeating
hard-liner Benjamin Netanyahu by a wide margin. But voters gave
Barak's One Israel bloc only 26 seats in the 120 seat parliament,
forcing him to form a motley coalition with parties representing
secularists, Orthodox Jews and immigrants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
