<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Reformist Loses  </HEADLINE>
By LOUIS MEIXLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's parliament failed to elect a
reformist president in the first round of voting Thursday in
humiliations for Prime Miinister Bulent Ecevit and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit believed he had gained the promises of every party leader
in the legislature to support Ahmet Necdet Sezer, chief of the
constitutional court who has advocated democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't even consider the probability that Sezer won't be
elected,'' Ecevit said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But parliament, which elects the chief of state, gave Sezer only
281 votes, instead of the 367, or two-thirds, of the 550 members,
needed for a first-round win. Nine other candidates split the
remaining votes, with the second highest vote getter, Nevzat
Yalcintas, netting just 61. The vote was by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   After Ecevit failed two weeks ago to get parliament to amend the
constitution to give President Suleyman Demirel another term, he
settled on Sezer as the ideal compromise candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As head of Turkey's top court and a supporter of constitutional
reforms, Sezer appealed to the European Union that has pressed for
changes so Turkey can join the group.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer also had also questioned the military's purge of officers
suspected of links with Islamic groups, which pleaed the Islamic
Virtue Party, which faces banning for challenging Turkey's secular
system.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer's views alarmed the military, which fears views political
Islam as a major threat to Turkey's secular state. The top generals
stayed away from a reception Sezer held this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition of the military to Sezer appeals to the
European Union, which believes that Turkey's generals have had too
much say in poliitics. The army has seized power three times since
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the first-round defeat for Sezer, Ecevit believes his
candidate will win in the next round or the one after that when
several candidates drop out.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear as of now that the results will be good for Mr.
Sezer,'' Ecevit said. ''I am very optimistic about the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidency in Turkey is a largely ceremonial post, but
presidents are often powerbrokers in times of crises and can exert
strong moral influence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1915 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Janvrin Rallies for Decathlon Win  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK SCHOFFNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Kip Janvrin once again played the 1,500
meters as his trump card in the decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing the entire day, Janvrin ran away from the field
in the 1,500, the last event, to win the Drake Relays decathlon for
the sixth straight year and the 11th time overall.
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin, the track coach at Central Missouri State, finished the
two days of competition with 7,794 points. Kamau Sullivan, who
trained under Janvrin for two years, was second with 7,620.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was in first place going into the 1,500 -- 102 points
ahead of Janvrin.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my ace in the hole,'' Janvrin said. ''But I was concerned
at about 1,000 meters. He wasn't that far back. Then I put down the
hammer a little bit and moved away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin, 34, needed to beat Sullivan by 16 seconds to win the
title. He ended up beating him by nearly 43 seconds to win the race
in 4 minutes, 22.78 seconds. Janvrin also sealed his Drake victory
last year with a strong performance in the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm coming back to the field. The field's getting closer to
me,'' Janvrin said. ''I was lucky to win again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wichita State's Mellanee Welty won the heptathlon for the second
straight year with 5,365 points. First-day leader Barbara
Szlendakova of Iowa State was second with 5,315, a school record.
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin was in fourth place after the first event Thursday, the
110 hurdles, and trailed Sullivan by 206 points with three events
to go. But he finished ahead of Sullivan in the javelin and pole
vault and that put him within striking distance in the 1,500, which
he finished with a 61-second final lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've still got some good events,'' said Janvrin, who has
topped 8,000 points more often than any U.S. decathlete. ''I can
still do a lot of things I could before, obviously not as good as I
could, but to keep winning, that's really what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking home that watch, getting that victory and feeling the
excitement of when I cross the line knowing that I've won again,
having all my friends and family out here being a part of it,
that's why I keep coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin also won the pole vault and Sullivan was first in the
hurdles. Brad Swanson won the javelin and discus.
</P>
<P>
   Welty got the lead from Szlendakova in the heptathlon by beating
her in the long jump, the next to last event. Then she stayed close
enough to the Iowa State sophomore in the 800 to keep the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Szlendakova won that race in 2:19.90 and Welty ran 2:21.62. If
Szlendakova had run 3.7 seconds faster, she would have won the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a matter of guts,'' Welty said. ''I just had to stay
with her. I couldn't let her beat me by five or six seconds. I just
had to stay on her heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty closed the gap by winning the javelin, the first event of
the day, then got a break when Szlendakova did not do as well as
expected in the long jump. Szlendakova is capable of going past 20
feet in that event but went only 18-6. Welty jumped 18-7\.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once she didn't jump well, I knew I had a chance,'' Welty
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
