<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census response could determine the state's largest city  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. Thursday, U.S. Census
Bureau employee Sharon Grant headed out to her own neighborhood to
count the uncounted.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that my neighborhood is being represented,''
she said, sporting a large red ''Census 2000'' button and an armful
of census forms in a black bag.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was one of thousands of Census employees who fanned out
across the state on Thursday to find the people who failed to mail
back Census forms as the Bureau prepares its once-a-decade
population estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Their success will help determine how much government funding
and political representation cities and counties get. But in Newark
and Jersey City, the bragging rights for the state's most populous
city also are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a realistic chance'' at overtaking Newark to
become the state's largest city, said Tom Gallagher, chief of staff
for Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler. ''We can surpass them if we
continue to gain and they continue to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Newark, long the state's biggest city, had 275,221
residents, according to Census figures, compared to 228,517 in
Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   But 1998 estimates showed that Newark had lost people to its
suburbs, dropping to 267,823, while Jersey City's waterfront
development and continued influx of new immigrants brought its
population up to 232,429 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's probably too close to call, but I think Newark will
probably maintain the edge,'' said James Hughes, the dean of the
public policy school at Rutgers University. He said that Jersey
City had to close a large gap from the 1998 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, only 43 percent of Newark households and 49
percent of Jersey City households had mailed back Census forms, and
officials in both cities agreed that the Census Bureau's ability to
accurately count the cities will hinge upon its ability to reach
immigrant populations.
</P>
<P>
   Luiggi Campana, who is heading Newark's Census outreach efforts,
said immigrants, particularly those of Caribbean and Haitian
descent, made up the bulk of residents who failed to respond.
</P>
<P>
   In Jersey City, the Egyptian and Filipino population has grown,
and a growing Vietnamese and Chinese community may be the hardest
to target because of a lack of publications in their own language
to launch an ad campaign, Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Newark sent 300 Census employees and Jersey City
sent 400 people door-to-door to obtain information ranging from
names and addresses to their medical history and whether they work
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail Carter, Newark's Census office manager, said that 750
employees would be out in the streets in two weeks for the
eight-week program. Many of the employees are bilingual and are
chosen to go to their own neighborhood, hopefully to offer more
approachable faces to wary residents, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City Census office manager Ervin Washington said the
city's most undercounted neighborhood was the predominantly black
Greenville district. Black leaders held a news conference Thursday
to announce an outreach program that will spread into churches and
neighborhood groups.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the office wasn't targeting any particular
neighborhood in Newark. The lack of specifics disturbed Campana,
who canceled a plan to send trucks out on Saturday to make public
service announcements because he didn't know what the Census Bureau
was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't deploy our support base because I have no idea yet of
how they're deploying their resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities with poor response rates included East Orange (41
percent), Asbury Park (43) and Camden (44), which rely on federal
financial aid. Of New Jersey's 21 counties, none had a lower
initial response rate than Cape May County, with its abundance of
summer homes.
</P>
<P>
   Cape May planning director Jim J. Smith said the response rate
will certainly rise when enumerators realize that about four of
every five homes on the barrier island towns that span the county
are owned by people who live elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Enumerators are to visit homes up to six times before declaring
them seasonal, unless a neighbor lets them know sooner, Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-27-00 1933 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Padres Await Reaction to John Rocker  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- John Rocker goes on the road this weekend for
the first time since his suspension for offensive comments, and San
Diego Padres officials aren't quite sure what to expect from their
normally easygoing fans.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended for the first two weeks of the season for making
disparaging remarks about foreigners, minorities and gays in a
magazine interview, Rocker rejoined the Atlanta Braves at the start
of a nine-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker got a standing ovation in his first appearance and had
four saves as the Braves swept the homestand to run their winning
streak to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Steinberg, the Padres' vice president for public
affairs, said he has no feel for how the fans will respond during a
three-game series with the Braves starting Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was interesting to see the ovation that the Braves fans
provided,'' Steinberg said Thursday. ''This is his first stop on
the road. I think we're at ground zero. We're interested in seeing
what the attitudes of people are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres don't plan to increase the number of security guards
for the Braves series, but will keep an eye on the Braves' bullpen
as the games progress, said Mark Guglielmo, director of stadium
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in contact with major league baseball. We know what
the concerns are,'' Guglielmo said Thursday. ''We'll treat this as
any other event and take appropriate actions as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Guglielmo said there will be some fans who will jeer Rocker,
''but I think those will be few and far between. I think our fans
are more in tune with supporting the Padres and watching a good
baseball game between two good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, who beat the Braves to win the 1998 NL pennant, have
not heard about any possible protests, Guglielmo said.
Representatives of the NAACP and the San Diego County Hispanic
Chamber of Commerce did not immediately return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the team's No. 1 concern ''is always with safety,
and right with that, sportsmanship. I think our fans have shown a
great ability to honor both of those concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   While generally considered laid-back, San Diego fans have shown
a nasty side toward three stars who left as free agents after
helping the Padres reach the 1998 World Series. Kevin Brown, Steve
Finley and, surprisingly, Ken Caminiti, the 1996 NL MVP and one of
the most popular Padres ever, have been booed on their returns to
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti and Padres officials were stunned when the Houston
Astros slugger was booed repeatedly on April 15, his first game in
San Diego since the '98 Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres owner John Moores went to the Astros' clubhouse afterward
and apologized to Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   While that episode bothered Moores, he had some fun when Brown
made his first appearance in San Diego in a Dodgers uniform in
April 1999. Moores suggested that the Beatles' ''Can't Buy Me
Love'' be played on the stadium PA system, one of several musical
jabs at Brown that night, when the fans, and even the club's
mascot, really let loose. Brown had turned down San Diego's $60
million offer to become baseball's first $100 million man.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a musical poke at Rocker. ''It's a non-subject,''
Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a baseball perspective, you hope you don't see him
because you hope you're beating the Braves. That would be the ideal
scenario.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 1937 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Squabbling Endangers Barak's Gov't  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A long-running dispute between two members of
Israel's coalition government escalated Thursday, endangering Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's efforts to make peace with the Palestinians
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The dovish, secular Meretz party announced it would bolt from
the coalition rather than hand government funds to the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party to run its corrupt and debt-ridden school
system.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz leader Yossi Sarid, who is Israel's education minister,
has refused to turn over administration of the Shas education
system to his deputy minister Meshulam Nahari, who is from the Shas
party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has indicated that he will rule in favor of Shas in the
dispute, according to Israeli media.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs the support of Shas, the third largest faction in
the parliament, to assure a majority in favor of peace deals he
hopes to make with Syria and the Palestinians, including deep
territorial concessions in the Golan Heights and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   That has opened the way for Shas to make a series of escalating
demands on Barak, especially money for its school system. Barak has
appealed to Meretz to swallow the pill for the sake of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz refuses, charging that Shas must not be allowed to
supervise a system that it has already mismanaged. ''We will not
write a corrupt check ... and it will not come from our
government,'' said Trade Minister Ran Cohen of Meretz.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid said if Meretz quits the government over the Shas crisis,
it would stay in the coalition for a limited period of time to give
Barak a chance to achieve peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Shas say that its voters are mostly hawkish opponents
of concessions to the Arabs, and the 17 members of the Shas
parliament faction would vote against peace deals even if their
demands are met.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leader Eli Ishai said votes on peace issues would not be
connected to other matters. He said the party would vote according
to the rulings of its Council of Torah Sages, headed by Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
   If Meretz, with ten seats in parliament, quit Barak's
government, he would still command a majority in the house. If Shas
pulled out, another religious party might follow. Barak would be
hard pressed to muster a majority, and his government could fall.
</P>
<P>
   That could lead to new elections, delaying peace efforts for
many months.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was elected prime minister in May 1999, defeating
hard-liner Benjamin Netanyahu by a wide margin. But voters gave
Barak's One Israel bloc only 26 seats in the 120 seat parliament,
forcing him to form a motley coalition with parties representing
secularists, Orthodox Jews and immigrants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
