<HEADLINE> Port authority elects new officers, fails to vote on budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey
re-elected its officers Thursday but did not vote on a $3.9 billion
budget that it had put on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the budget, which holds down increases in PATH
commuter rail fares and tolls at Port Authority bridges and
tunnels, would have ended a stalemate on all major business at the
board, which is hamstrung by a feud between the governors of New
York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-month-old dispute began when Gov. George Pataki refused
to sign off on a $200 million lease with a shipping company, saying
it would benefit New Jersey more than New York. New Jersey Gov.
Christie Whitman, in turn, demanded that the board not take action
on issues important to New York, such as the privatization of the
World Trade Center and expansion of the Howland Hook Marine
Terminal in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Each governor appoints and controls the votes of six
commissioners on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Lewis M. Eisenberg, a Whitman appointee, said at
Thursday's meeting that a vote on the budget would not take place.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg was re-elected, along with Pataki appointee and vice
chairman Charles A. Gargano and Pataki ally Robert E. Boyle as
executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
