<HEADLINE> U.S. Cautions Americans in China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department advised U.S. citizens
living and traveling in China to be cautious with the approach of
the May 8 anniversary of the American bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   China has refused to accept repeated U.S. statements that the
bombing was the result of a targeting mistake.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the United States and its NATO allies were
attacking Yugoslavia to force withdrawal of Serb troops from
Kosovo, where they were accused of criminal treatment of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Thursday it had not received any
information regarding demonstrations or threats against U.S.
interests in China.
</P>
<P>
   But the public announcement noted that the bombing, which it
described as a ''tragic event,'' was followed by sometimes violent
demonstrations at U.S. diplomatic offices in China and a few
isolated incidents of harassment of U.S. citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
