<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuits Abound in Sports  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   A guy who had one of the worst ideas ever is mulling over
another bad one. Orlando Brown, the Cleveland Browns lineman who
flattened a ref last December, is still having problems seeing and
is thinking about suing the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In a game against Jacksonville, referee Jeff Triplette threw a
penalty flag weighted with BBs in Brown's direction and wound up
striking Brown in the right eye. Viewing videotape of the incident
months later, one blow looks intentional, the other an accident.
But now that attorney Johnnie Cochran Jr., is involved, it's even
money which was which.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the NFL ended Brown's indefinite suspension and
gave back the $49,000 he was docked. But that gesture proved no
more effective than the finger-crossing at league headquarters.
Earlier this week, Cochran confirmed he was already on Brown's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will take a few weeks probably,'' Cochran's publicist,
Rachel Noerdlinger, said. ''Maybe longer just to obtain background
on the case, if there is a case.''
</P>
<P>
   But only if.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, the sports section looks like the rest of the
newspaper. First commerce swallowed chunks and now the law has come
along to take a bite. In the last few days, we've read stories
about coaches suing players, fans suing players and now another
player preparing to sue his league. None of the lawsuits is
unprecedented -- remember Latrell Sprewell, tired of being
''demonized,'' suing the NBA for $30 million -- they're just
occurring closer together.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the story was Toronto coach Butch Carter filing a $5
million defamation suit against Knick forward Marcus Camby, who
once played for Carter and called him ''a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he wouldn't sue, then sued anyway. Then he demanded
an apology from Camby, didn't get it, and dropped the lawsuit
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The story making the rounds now is the lawsuit wasn't even about
Camby. ESPN reports Carter was stung because his former Indiana
teammates wouldn't back up claims in Carter's book that Bob Knight
aimed racial slurs at a player. So when Camby attacked his
credibility, Carter went legal.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he came to his senses in time. All Yankee pitcher
Allen Watson and a 16-year-old Baltimore fan arrived at was an
out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Robbins of Arlington, Va., claimed Watson threw two
balls at his daughter, Cheryl, during batting practice at Camden
Yards last September. The sign probably said something stronger
than ''Yankee Go Home!'' because Watson's teammate, Jeff Nelson,
grabbed the sign from Cheryl, ripped it to pieces and threw it back
at her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't say anything,'' Watson said leaving the courthouse.
''You know I wish I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Robbins' attorney, Gregory Angst, said the
family's separate civil suit against the Yankees would be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the NFL has to buy out Brown still remains to be seen.
When the incident took place in December, the league's disciplinary
headache was approaching migraine status. It already had one player
facing a murder rap (Rae Carruth) and a second player (Cecil
Collins) charged with climbing through other people's bedroom
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue was itching for a test case to make
him look tough. And when the 6-foot-7, 350-pound Brown decked
Triplette, a slender 6-footer, it looked like he was auditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a guy who doesn't mind mixing it up. He had already
turned down an offer from the World Wrestling Federation and wanted
friends to call him ''Zeus.'' More damning, he went to the sideline
and appeared to have a grip on things before walking back on the
field and applying it to Triplette.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it's much harder picking out the villain. Brown's
father lost his sight to glaucoma in 1993. That shook Brown up. Now
he's worried about when -- and even whether -- he will resume his NFL
career.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is known: It's getting tougher by the minute for
pro sports leagues to call their own shots.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities -- real cops -- talked to the NHL's Marty
McSorley over his stick-swinging. And some of the White Sox and
Detroit Tigers suspended Thursday for last weekend's basebrawl have
already pulled out their cell phones and called the union.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of command in sports is being yanked at every
opportunity, from all sides, often with the aid of the court
system. But now, those inmates who want to run the institutions can
afford pricey legal help, too.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2034 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Targets Bush on Health Care  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, pressing his plan to
bring health insurance to all children, said Thursday that
presidential rival George W. Bush has done little to get coverage
to thousands of uninsured Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor, has been touting a health program of
his own as he works to make inroads on traditionally Democratic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I welcome him to this debate because he has some pretty
serious questions to answer,'' Gore said at Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to know why under George W. Bush, the state of Texas
has become first in the nation for the number of people without any
health insurance at all,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   About one in four Texans lacks health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer responded with national figures
showing the number of uninsured Americans has grown to some 44
million, including about 11 million children, despite the booming
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since he (Gore) was elected, there are 8 million more
Americans without health insurance,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's trip to Pennsylvania also netted more than $1 million for
the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, Gore also questioned why Bush wanted Texas to
impose stricter limits on the incomes of families participating in
the 2-year-old Children's Health Insurance Program, which provides
subsidized coverage to working poor families that earn too much to
qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why ... did Governor Bush fight to deny health coverage to
more than 200,000 children who were legally eligible for it under
the national law that President Clinton and I passed?'' Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning with sick kids in a swing state, Gore said no child
should go without care in these strong economic times. He visited a
playroom filled with children, most of whom had received or were
waiting for organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Few of their parents knew much about Gore's health plan but they
all welcomed his interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the last thing you want to worry about, who's paying the
bills,'' said Tim Colligan of Wellsville, N.Y., whose son just got
a transplanted heart.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan builds on the Clinton administration's approach to
incrementally expanding access to insurance, a strategy adopted
after the failure to get a universal health coverage plan through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would allow more children and many of their parents into
the Children's Health Insurance Program. He also would require that
states simplify the application process for that program and for
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened under Bush, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His state's Medicaid program requires now face-to-face
interviews ... before a child can be signed up, as if these
families were applying for high-security jobs rather than health
coverage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many states have similar requirements, designed to make sure
people are not getting government-funded coverage they are not
qualified for.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have traditionally enjoyed a political advantage on
health care, but Bush has signaled he will not concede the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with Republicans of the past, Bush has called for more
federal spending on traditionally Democratic issues such as health,
education and housing. But Gore argues there would be no money to
pay for them after Bush's $483 billion, five-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other side is proposing ... to go back to the promise of
no hard choices, have-it-all, risky-tax-scheme plus more spending
and don't worry about tomorrow,'' Gore told some 200 people at a
$1,000-per-plate fund-raiser luncheon for the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch was expected to raise $200,000. Afterward, Gore was
attending a DNC reception and dinner in Philadelphia that were
expected to raise another $1 million. Tickets to the reception were
$1,000; to the dinner, $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, the candidates' positions reflect their parties'
philosophies, with Gore preferring a government program that
guarantees a minimum set of benefits and Bush using the tax code to
encourage families to buy insurance on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Under the centerpiece of the Bush plan, estimated at $35 billion
over five years, families would get tax credits of up to $2,000 per
family to offset much of the cost of insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2040 </TRAILER>
