<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush: I'll Make Call on Big Cases  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush said Thursday that, if elected,
he would make the decision -- not his attorney general -- in cases
such as the fate of Elian Gonzalez that are a matter of ''national
conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would rely upon the advice of those who are fully involved
in the case, but this seems like a decision that would have risen
to the Oval Office to me,'' Bush said of reuniting the Cuban boy
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on the PBS ''NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,'' the
presumed Republican presidential nominee said he would rely on his
attorney general's advice, but make the final call himself.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno have said Reno
alone gave the go-ahead for the early morning raid last Saturday in
which armed federal agents snatched the 6-year-old Cuban boy from
the home of his Miami relatives and flew him to Washington, where
his father waited.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd make the decision on a situation that had risen to this
level in the national conscience, and I'd, of course, rely upon the
attorney general's advice,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said he understood the need to reunite father
and son, but repeated his position that the matter should have been
handled in family court.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rival, Democrat Al Gore, also has said -- in a break with
the Clinton administration -- that the case should have been decided
by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand the boy's being with his dad. Heck, I'm a dad,''
Bush said. ''But I wish it had been done in a place where there
wasn't a lot of suspicion about what took place.''
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   -- He would not be ''beholden'' to corporations and other big
money donors that support him and the Republican Party, which
raised a record $21.3 million Wednesday night at a Washington
dinner Bush headlined. ''Either you're crooked or you're not
crooked, I guess is the way to put it bluntly,'' he said. '' Either
you're somebody who can be bought, or you're somebody who's running
on principle. My job is to convince the American people that I'm a
man running on principle.''
</P>
<P>
   -- In the case of Microsoft, he hoped the government doesn't
''ruin this company'' in deciding whether to order a breakup. ''I
hope the judge would keep in mind that this company is an important
part of the technological revolution taking place in America.'' He
refused to say what a Bush administration would have done in the
antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   -- He hoped President Clinton would not sign an amended
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty that would prevent the United States
from developing a full missile defense system. ''I would hope he
wouldn't constrain me -- the next president -- or the next
administration's ability to move forward by signing a halfhearted
reform of the ABM,'' Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2042 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
