<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell Success Begs Trade Question  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN, AP Basketball Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Knicks general manager Scott Layden stood
outside the locker room with three Madison Square Garden
executives, keeping a straight face when somebody said: ''Good
thing you didn't trade him.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Layden's lieutenants burst out laughing -- nervous,
relieved laughter.
</P>
<P>
   It was no joke last fall, though, when Layden seriously
considered trading Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were talking to Seattle, Houston and the Lakers, but how
close they actually came to trading him I can't say for sure,'' an
opposing Eastern Conference general manager said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Layden is known to have spoken to the SuperSonics about a
Sprewell-Gary Payton trade, to the Rockets about a Sprewell-Pippen
trade before Pippen was dealt to Portland, and to Los Angeles about
a Sprewell-Glen Rice trade.
</P>
<P>
   No deal ever came off, and Layden now has the luxury of knowing
that the best trades -- as general managers often say -- are the ones
that don't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell outdid Vince Carter once again Wednesday night, giving
his second straight superstar-caliber performance to lead the
Knicks to an 84-83 victory over the Toronto Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell scored 13 of the Knicks' final 17 points, most of them
coming off one-on-one isolation plays with Carter helpless to stop
him. It was a performance reminiscent of Sprewell's mano-a-mano
battle with Tim Duncan in Game 5 of the NBA Finals last year, which
until this past week was Sprewell's brightest moment in a Knicks
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   With New York holding a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five series that
resumes Sunday, no one is more responsible that Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   His defense in Game 1 was a big reason why Carter shot 3-for-20.
His short jumper from the lane with 7.9 seconds left in Game 2 won
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last one was vintage Latrell,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
''Hard, two dribbles, pull up and shoot over a great shot blocker
in Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it might seem, the Knicks actually considered trading
Sprewell last October, even before he blew off training camp
without the courtesy of a phone call to explain his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell averaged 18.6 points for the Knicks, leading the team
in scoring 28 times while playing small forward instead of his
natural shooting guard position.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1{ years after re-entering the league following his
controversial attack on Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo, Sprewell
has been lauded all season by Van Gundy for his unselfishness.
</P>
<P>
   But it's his star power that makes Sprewell so valuable, and it
has re-emerged against the Raptors and their young star, Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been making eye contact during the games, but there
has been no trash-talking or bad blood -- even after Sprewell
flagrantly fouled Carter, bringing him down by the shoulders, near
the end of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing but respect,'' was how Sprewell characterized the duel
between the two, objecting when someone suggested it was a budding
rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Down the stretch of Game 2, Sprewell had the added advantage of
knowing Carter was playing with five fouls.
</P>
<P>
   It allowed him to be aggressive with the dribble and drive to
his right, even though Carter and the Raptors' coaching staff knew
that Sprewell doesn't go to his left quite as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once I got into foul trouble, it was hard for me to judge how
to play him because I didn't know what I could get away with and
how close I could play him,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   After Sprewell put the Knicks ahead, Carter got the ball for the
final shot and was isolated at the top of the 3-point circle
against Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   With Sprewell daring him to drive left, Carter left his feet and
decided in mid-air to pass to Dee Brown. The Raptors got a
wide-open shot, but not from the player expected to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who hadn't even attempted a shot all night, missed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the ball comes to you, you have to hit that shot. But it's
tough when you've been sitting,'' Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
