<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wind Power for Denver Agencies  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WELLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- All federal agencies in the Denver area will be
powered in part by wind under the biggest-ever federal contract for
''green power,'' Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies have agreed to buy 10 megawatts of power yearly
from wind farms operated by Public Service Co. of Colorado and
other utilities, Richardson said. That's enough energy to supply
3,500 households for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this is the single largest purchase of green power
ever by federal agencies,'' said Richardson, who last week ordered
his agency to make sure it buys at least 7.5 percent of its power
from renewable sources.
</P>
<P>
   Public Service began developing the first commercial wind farm
three years ago, according to the agency's general manager, Chuck
Fuller. The farm, near the Wyoming line, has 15 turbines that are
26 stories tall with 900-pound, 32-foot-long blades. Six more
turbines are being built, and Richardson's agency has provided a $3
million grant.
</P>
<P>
   Public Service has 15,000 wind-power customers and has a waiting
list of more potential users, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Wind-power users don't get their energy directly from the site,
but through the regional power grid that delivers electricity to
users in Colorado and other Western states. The wind-power buyers
agree to be billed extra to pay the added cost.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the wind power will cost about 2 percent more
than conventional power, but the cost is offset by reduced
pollution and less dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Wind Energy Association:
http://www.awea.org/default.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
