<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Coroner Blames Heartburn Study  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A hospital study designed to test a heartburn
remedy on children was partially to blame for the death of a
9-month-old boy, a coroner ruled.
</P>
<P>
   When Gage Stevens died in November, Allegheny County Coroner
Cyril Wecht blamed sudden infant death syndrome, but on Tuesday, he
amended the death certificate to say the boy's inclusion in a study
of the drug Propulsid was also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Janssen Pharmaceutical Inc. of Titusville, N.J., a subsidiary of
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, announced last month after consulting with the
Food and Drug Administration that it would stop marketing the drug,
also called cisapride, but would make it available on a limited
basis to some patients.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has been associated with heart rhythm abnormalities and
80 deaths, though the FDA said it can't prove the drug caused any
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don Fischer, medical director of Children's Hospital, said
Thursday there would be no way an autopsy could show whether Gage
died from an abnormal heartbeat, and he had no medical history of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot say that cisapride contributed to his death,''
Fischer said. ''I'm not sure that we will ever know how he died.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said thousands of children had taken the drug. ''This
was a highly effective drug in treating congenital abnormalities,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's parents, Scott Stevens and Gretchen Stewart of
Munhall, said they signed a consent form at the hospital that
incorrectly said the drug was approved by the FDA for infants.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Wednesday, Children's Hospital officials
admitted the form was wrong. They said it told parents the drug was
approved because officials believed approval was imminent. They
also said the form listed the drug's potential side effects and
risks, including heart rhythm problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to believe that it was verbally communicated to them in
an appropriate way,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonnie Stevens, the boy's grandmother, said Gage's parents
did not know the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not aware it could cause heart problems,'' said
Stevens, a retired registered nurse. ''Who in their right mind
would give it to a baby if they knew that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gage, who suffered from heartburn and chronic diarrhea, had been
enrolled in the study for six months when he died. He was one of
100 children participating in a clinical trial to determine the
safety of the drug to treat gastroesophageal reflux in children.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital halted the trial in March after the FDA told
officials of a possible link between the drug and Gage's death.
</P>
<P>
   Wecht said he reopened the case after being contacted by the
''CBS Evening News'' and reviewing additional information from the
baby's family and the FDA. CBS first reported the link between
Gage's death and the drug Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Food and Drug Administration: http://www.fda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
