<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Court Hears Graphic Details of Bernardo's Sex-and-torture Tapes
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) -- Lawyers, spectators and courtroom
staff sat in mortified silence Thursday during a graphic,
profanity-laced description of sex killer Paul Bernardo's chilling
sex-and-torture videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Cooper, who is defending Bernardo's former lawyer Ken
Murray, spent the day grimly reciting details of the tapes Murray
recovered from his notorious client's home in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes depict sexual assaults by Bernardo and ex-wife Karla
Homolka on four teen-age girls, including Homolka's slain sister
Tammy and murder victims Leslie Mahaffy and Kristen French.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was trying to counter the Crown's suggestion Wednesday
that Murray, on trial for obstruction of justice, intended to
protect his client by suppressing the tapes for more than 16
months.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran defense lawyer clearly didn't relish his task; he
had barely begun Thursday when he became so overcome with emotion
he was forced to ask Justice Patrick Gravely for a brief recess.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Sour Gas Probe Considered As Oilpatch Bomber Begins Jail Term
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- As oilpatch bomber Wiebo Ludwig begins
his jail term, the concerns over sour gas that helped put him there
may result in a public inquiry by Alberta's energy regulator.
</P>
<P>
   A decision will be made ''within days'' as to whether the Energy
and Utilities Board will grant Ludwig's request for such an
inquiry, board spokesman Greg Gilbertson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although some dispute the board's effectiveness, an inquiry
would be the latest in a series of responses it has made to growing
public concern about the deadly but lucrative resource.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig, 58, blames pollution from the energy industry for health
problems on his northwestern Alberta farm. He and several others
asked for an inquiry into sour gas in October 1998. But once
criminal charges were laid against Ludwig the following March, the
board decided to wait until the trial was over.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ludwig was sentenced to 28 months in jail after
being convicted on two counts of bombing and cementing in wellsites
and three dynamite possession charges.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Alberta Premier Ralph Klein's Son-in-law Convicted of Bigamy
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY (AP) -- It appears Alberta Premier Ralph Klein
unwittingly performed a marriage ceremony uniting his daughter to a
bigamist.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's son-in-law, Richard Philip Marcia, 37, was sentenced
recently to 30 days in jail after he pleaded guilty to bigamy in a
court in Drumheller, 130 kilometers northeast of Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   The premier, a licensed commissioner, officiated at the Oct. 4,
1997, wedding of his daughter Angela Klein to Marcia in the Alberta
government's Calgary office.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman in Klein's office said the premier would not talk
about the conviction, although he has said he knew nothing of the
previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Crown prosecutor Darlene Oco told the Drumheller provincial
court that Marcia was married to Angi Mari Marcia of Regina in
September 1994 and did not make any divorce attempt before he wed
Angela Klein-Marcia.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gordon Clozza gave Marcia credit for an early plea but
added bigamy should hold some serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia was already serving 2{ years in prison for property
charges, including theft and possession of stolen property. His
30-day bigamy sentence is to be served after that.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Vancouver Aquarium To Stop Keeping Whales in Captivity
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER (AP) -- The Vancouver Public Aquarium is phasing out
its killer whale display, an exhibit that has been the mainstay of
the aquarium for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The last killer whale in the aquarium -- Bjossa -- will go to a
Seaworld in the United States, Dick Bradshaw, chairman of the
aquarium's marine sciences centre, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw said Bjossa is being moved because the aquarium hasn't
been able to find a companion for her and she needs to be with her
own species.
</P>
<P>
   Bjossa was recently sick with an infection. Her former poolmate
Finna died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium said it will continue to keep dolphins, sea lions,
seals and otters.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activists have been lobbying for years for an end
to the whale display.
</P>
