<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student suspended for threatening to 'shoot' classmate with paperwad  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLAINSBORO, N.J. (AP) -- A fourth-grader at a Middlesex County
elementary school has been suspended and ordered to undergo a
psychological evaluation after telling a classmate he was going to
''shoot'' another student with a wad of paper launched from a
rubber band, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hagood told The Times of Trenton he only intended to
fling a piece a paper at the student on April 12. But his use of
the word ''shoot'' prompted the school district to implement its
zero-tolerance policy for school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Kamaria Hagood said her son told a classmate he planned to shoot
a ''paper wasp'' at a girl in their class. A paper wasp is a piece
of paper launched with a rubber band, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of another student apparently heard about the
conversation and notified the district. The district then alerted
police, district spokeswoman Geraldine Hutner told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess they just overhead 'shoot' and ran with that,'' Mrs.
Hagood said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutner said district reports on the incident are considered
confidential, and she wouldn't elaborate on what happened at the
Upper Elementary School in Plainsboro.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagoods said the matter was handled in an insensitive
manner. Two police officers came to the Hagood's home at 12:30 a.m.
to question the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are obligated to investigate things of that nature right
away,'' said Plainsboro Police Capt. Timothy Matheny. ''If it were
(a gun), we would have really heard it if we waited until (the next
day).''
</P>
<P>
   The Hagoods said the district's insistence on a psychological
evaluation was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   The district spokeswoman said the exam is not considered a
punishment. ''We just wanted to make sure that students were
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hagoods consented to the exam to get their son back in
school as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after the Columbine High School killings,
schools across the country are still using a heavy hand to dole out
disciplinary measures for behavior that previously would not raise
many eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   In March, four kindergarten students in Sayreville were
suspended for playing cops and robbers on the school playground.
</P>
<P>
   Hagood said he believes a Michigan incident, in which a
6-year-old boy fatally shot a classmate, may have skewed the
investigation of Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ''In that shooting, an African-American boy shot a Caucasian
girl. And in our case you are talking about an African-American
male and a Caucasian female. That sends all kinds of waves. I think
race had something to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutner said race was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagoods sent a letter of complaint to school Superintendent
John Fitzsimons, the school board and several administrators. A
copy of the letter was sent to the NAACP and the New Jersey Black
Ministers Council.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hagood said he is considering a lawsuit, but may settle for
a letter of apology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
