<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Sought in No Gun Ri Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Three lawyers for South Korean
survivors of an alleged wartime mass killing by U.S. soldiers urged
Washington on Thursday to expedite its probe of the case and
compensate survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are rumors that the U.S. government is dragging its feet
on the investigation it has promised to finish by the end of
June,'' Michael Choi, a lawyer from Philadelphia, told a news
conference in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Choi and two other American lawyers -- Robert Swift and Michael
Goss -- were in town for interviews with survivors of the Korean War
incident and a visit to the scene of the alleged mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   They warned that a delay in the U.S. investigation could result
in a lawsuit by the Korean survivors in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After the scene of the alleged incident in central South Korea,
the lawyers said they were appalled at the ''clear evidence of the
massacre,'' including bullet fragments stuck in cement holes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't a massacre. It was an annihilation of the villagers,
every single villager,'' Choi said in a telephone interview after
the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting dozens of Korean survivors and American veterans, The
Associated Press reported in September that retreating U.S.
soldiers killed unarmed Korean civilians during the early days of
the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors say 400 were killed, including many cowering under a
railroad bridge.
</P>
<P>
   They had been telling their story for years, but their accounts
had been dismissed by officials in Washington and in Seoul. After
the AP report, however, both the U.S. and South Korean governments
began investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The Army said last fall that its investigation could take a
year, but officials have said since that they are hoping it might
be completed by June, when Seoul and Washington plan special
ceremonies to mark the 50th anniversary of the start of the Korean
War on June 25
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2124 </TRAILER>
