<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pair win major awards for their inventions  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A doctor whose desire to make medical products
better initiated a wave of less invasive surgery has won the
world's largest single award for inventors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas J. Fogarty was given the Lemelson-Massachusetts
Institute of Technology prize -- along with $500,000 -- for American
invention and innovation during Thursday evening's award
celebration at the American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, who has 63 U.S. patents in surgical devices, is best
known for creating the world's first balloon catheter for
cardiovascular therapy in 1963. The device pioneered the effort to
make surgery less invasive and led to a technique for treating
blocked arteries.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 million people have benefited from catheter-related
technology -- some of whom would have lost limbs under previous
methods.
</P>
<P>
   While the technique is now a staple of modern medicine, getting
doctors to accept it proved to be difficult at the time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was such as radical deviation ... that they questioned it,
whether it would work, whether it was safe,'' Fogarty said, adding
that the process of getting people to use an invention is the final
obstacle for inventors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the innovation, Fogarty continued inventing by starting
and assisting more than a three dozen companies. He helped form a
venture capital fund, which works with young inventors who are
developing medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Jerome H. Lemelson established the Lemelson-MIT Program
with his wife, Dorothy, to honor the nation's finest inventors and
encourage youngsters to follow in their steps. Lemelson, who died
in 1997, had nearly 500 patents for many everyday devices,
including parts used in camcorders, computers and personal radios.
</P>
<P>
   ''We love inventors. We love innovation, and we would love to
see more of it,'' said Lester Thurow, the chairman of the
Lemelson-MIT prize board.
</P>
<P>
   Also honored during the evening gala was Al Gross for a lifetime
of innovation in the communications field.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, who won the Lifetime Achievement Award, created the
world's first walkie-talkie, built the first pager system during
World War II, and today assists a corporation in aerospace
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona man once studied under Albert Einstein and continues
to get his kicks thinking about people using his inventions.
</P>
<P>
   ''A friend of mine in the CIA told me they had learned Saddam
Hussein has a beeper and a cellular phone,'' Gross said. ''And I
was watching the news once and saw President Clinton reaching down
to his waist and tucking a pager into his pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lemelson said both men could be described as the
typical, yet extremely successful inventor.
</P>
<P>
   ''They contributed to society in a quiet way,'' she said. ''And
these two fellows obviously are very self-motivated and had to pull
themselves up by their bootstraps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
