<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgetown Wins Women's Relay Race  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL, AP Track Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Having four runners who are used to the cold
paid off for Georgetown in the women's 3,200-meter relay in the
Penn Relays on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the temperature at an unspringlike 43 degrees and rain
falling intermittently, the Hoyas runners from Oregon and New York
breezed to a 25-meter victory over defending champion Florida in 8
minutes, 34.37 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather was a factor, but we made sure we warmed up
well,'' leadoff runner Tyrona Heath from Endicott, N.Y., said after
Georgetown's third victory in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather doesn't make for ideal times, but we're used to
running in weather like this,'' anchor runner Sasha Spencer from
Salem, Ore., said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unfavorable weather, a crowd of 20,456 -- the largest
Thursday attendance in the meet's 106-year history -- showed up at
Franklin Field. The previous mark was 19,815 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Heath opened the relay with a solid 2:08.6 leg for 800 meters,,
putting Georgetown in second place, just behind Florida's Erin
Merten.
</P>
<P>
   Nickay Penado from Brooklyn, N.Y., followed with 2:09.2, but it
was good enough to give the Hoyas an 8-meter lead over the Gators.
Katrina de Boer from West Linn, Ore., turned in the fastest leg,
2:08.2, lengthening the lead to 35 meters, and Spencer finished
with 2:08.4.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same foursome that finished fourth last year in a
faster time, 8:31.68. The weather slowed the Hoyas this year, but
not their desire to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter how fast you run, it's how competitive you
are,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt we could break it open on any carry,'' coach Ron
Helmer said. ''Nickay broke it open a little, then Katrina really
pulled away.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Helmer also emphasized the importance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ''Georgetown has a huge tradition at the Penn Relays and it's
important to retain the legacy we have here,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said we need to win the first race, so we can have a good
time the rest of the week,'' Helmer said. ''To start with a win is
huge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know we can run. We may not win another race, but we are
capable. This is where we felt we had the best chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath and Penado also ran on Georgetown's team that won its heat
in the 1,600 relay and qualified for Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peta-Gay Gayle became the first woman from Alabama to
win an individual running event in the history of the Relays,
taking the 400 hurdles at 57.85.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle benefitted from the absence of the two favorites, Tanya
Jarrett and Angel Patterson, both from Texas. Jarrett won the race
last year, while Patterson beat her teammate at the recent Texas
Relays.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle, a transfer from Central Arizona Community College, was
the national junior college runner-up in the 400 hurdles and 400
sprint in 1998 and the Pan Am junior champion in the hurdles in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Patterson were late scratches because Texas coach
Bev Kearney did not want to risk running them in the cold
conditions too often.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Patterson did run on Texas' 1,600-meter relay team
that qualified for Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Longhorns, seeking their sixth consecutive title,
did not have an easy time. Their first runner, Natasha Neal, was
bumped around badly, getting pushed three times, and No. 2 runner
Jarrett had a foot stepped on and lost a shoe right at the start of
her leg. Still, the Longhorns won their heat at 3:40.50, with the
help of Patterson's anchor of 53.6.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh had the fastest heat time, 3:37.09.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had a more comfortable time in advancing to Friday's final
in the 400 relay. The Longhorns, seeking their second straight
title, led all qualifiers at 45.25.
</P>
<P>
   The long distance races provided some interesting developments.
</P>
<P>
   Marjo Venalainen, a 28-year-old from Finland competing as a
sophomore for Division II Kennesaw State, a school about a
half-hour north of Atlanta, won the women's 3,000 in 9:19.09,
upsetting defending champion Amy Yoder of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Competing against Yoder and other big-name runners from
high-profile schools didn't faze Venalainen, who attends school
with her husband of 5 1-2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been competing in Europe,'' she said. ''I didn't even
know about those people and those schools. I hadn't heard about the
Penn Relays until I came to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Steve Slattery, competing in his first 3,000-meter
steeplechase this year, came from behind on the final lap and won
in 8:35.15.
</P>
<P>
   ''I train with the best training partner in the U.S. -- Mark
Davis,'' Slattery said. ''If I can run with him for a workout, I am
confident I can run with any collegian.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners won the men's and women's college 5,000s.
</P>
<P>
   Silah Masoi, 25, from Kenya, took the men's race in a pedestrian
13:45.87, leading a 1-2 Life finish, and Virginia Commonwealth's
Maria Elena Calle, the runner-up in last year's 3,000, won the
women's event in 16:06.03.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Johnson of Georgia Tech rallied in the stretch to win the
women's 10,000 at 34:31.30, and Steve Bohan of West Virginia took
the men's 10,000 at 29:04.37, meeting the NCAA qualifying standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
