<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dole: No Glass Ceiling To Presidency  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE PFLEGER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole says her campaign for president
was about ''cutting-edge'' policies, inspiring voters, blue jeans
and motor cycles.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, it showed ''there is no glass ceiling at
1600 Pennsylvania Avenue,'' the former Republican candidate said of
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Dole on Thursday night recounted her stint on the campaign trail
for about 600 women and a few men attending a dinner at the
Republican Women Leaders Forum.
</P>
<P>
   She told the story of an 11-year-old girl at a town hall meeting
in Nevada, Iowa, who asked whether Dole's face would be carved into
Mount Rushmore if she was elected.
</P>
<P>
   She talked about her proposals to protect children from gun
violence and Internet pornography, to help farmers and boost
critical economic sectors, such as the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   And Dole described an unusual ride to a campaign event in New
Hampshire -- on the back of a motorcycle plastered with a ''Dole for
President'' bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Dole said, she had to stop at Wal-Mart for blue jeans. But
she startled GOP rival Steve Forbes when she ''roared'' up to the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that is one way for a candidate to connect with voters,''
Dole boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Dole did not address the possibility of running with George W.
Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee. But she
graciously accepted applause when Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.,
introduced her as a person on Bush's ''short list'' of potential
running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also addressed her viability against Democratic candidate
Al Gore, saying: ''It did me proud to see those polls where I was
beating Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the wife of Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential
candidate, dropped her bid to become the country's first female
president last October.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believed her campaign failed because she ''started
cold,'' without campaign funds or an organization after resigning
her post as president of the nonpartisan American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew the political odds were against me,'' Dole said. ''But
in the end ... it isn't how heavy the odds are, but how deeply you
believe in matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
