<DOCNO> APW20000427.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Reviews Vietnam Relations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Canada is reviewing its relations with Vietnam to
protest the execution this week of a Canadian woman convicted of
heroin smuggling, Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite requests by Canadian officials for Vietnam to wait for
police documents that indicated Nguyen Thi Hiep was an unwitting
courier rather than a heroin smuggler, the 43-year-old woman was
executed by firing squad Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This unwarranted action by the Vietnamese government does not,
and cannot, allow for the continuation of 'business as usual'
between our countries,'' Axworthy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said Canada's ambassador to Vietnam, Cecile Latour, who was
in Canada this week, would stay home until ''all aspects of
bilateral relations'' with Vietnam were reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy also withdrew Canadian officials from a training
program on the World Trade Organization for Vietnamese officials,
and said Canadian officials would be absent from events sponsored
by the Vietnamese government this weekend marking the 25th
anniversary of the end of the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen moved to Canada from Vietnam in 1982 and became a
Canadian citizen. She and her elderly mother were arrested in 1996
at the Hanoi airport after customs officials found 12 pounds of
heroin in small packets in their suitcase. Her mother, Tran Thi
Cam, 75, remains in a Vietnamese prison serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Canada believe Nguyen was asked to bring a package she
believed was artwork to Canada from Vietnam, The Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Vietnamese foreign minister, Axworthy asked
that Tran be released on humanitarian grounds and that Nguyen's
remains be turned over to her family, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Ruben ''Hurricane'' Carter -- a former pro boxer
who was wrongly incarcerated in the United States -- criticized
Vietnam for the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Carter told a news conference held by his Association in Defense
of the Wrongly Convicted that he had asked President Clinton last
year to help Canada pressure Vietnam to call off the execution of
Nguyen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000427.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crunch 27, Wave 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Hector Marinaro scored two 3-point goals during
a decisive third-quarter run Thursday night, leading the Cleveland
Crunch to a 27-15 victory over the Milwaukee Wave in Game 3 of the
NPSL finals.
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro, the six-time league MVP and seven-time scoring
champion, keyed a 10-0 spurt in the third quarter as Cleveland took
a 2-1 lead in the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's Steve Morris tied a playoff record with seven goals.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland can repeat as NPSL champions by winning Game 4
Saturday night at home. The Crunch have won four of the last six
league titles.
</P>
<P>
   Morris had four 2-point goals and three 1-point goals, tying the
NPSL playoff record for goals in one game accomplished twice by
Marinaro.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Tanner's two goals during a 9-0 run helped the Crunch take
a 14-9 lead at halftime. Tanner's second goal was a header of a
long pass by Zoran Karic that sailed over the right shoulder of
Milwaukee's Victor Nogueira, selected the league's top goalie for
the sixth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro's 2-point goal with 37 seconds remaining capped the
first-half scoring. The forward finished with nine points.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland goalie Otto Orf made 13 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Wave tied the series 1-1 on Tuesday night with an 18-12 win
in Milwaukee. The Crunch won the series opener in Milwaukee, 20-18.
</P>
</TEXT>
