<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressBice Clemow:
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP)-- Bice Clemow, who drafted and lobbied for
the legislation that became the state's Freedom of Information Act,
died Wednesday. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   During Clemow's nearly 50-year career as a journalist, he was
news editor of Editor &AMP; Publisher magazine, an Associated Press
photo editor and a Time magazine writer.
</P>
<P>
   Clemow is best remembered for his work to draft and get through
the General Assembly the state's freedom of information law in
1975. The Connecticut Council on Freedom of Information gives an
annual award, the Bice Clemow Award, in honor of his effort.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Clemow wrote that the law was needed ''to assure that
public business is done in public and that public records are open
to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemow came to Connecticut in 1939. He launched the Hartford
Newsdaily, a tabloid-style newspaper, the following year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, he started Connecticut Life, a monthly magazine, which
lasted 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1940 and 1947, the year he took over the Metropolitan
News, the predecessor of the West Hartford News, Clemow held
government jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Clemow stepped down as editor of the West Hartford News
but continued writing weekly columns as a contributing editor. He
wrote regularly until 1992.
Elmer Gertz:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Civil rights attorney Elmer Gertz, whose clients
included Jack Ruby, author Henry Miller and ''thrill killer''
Nathan Leopold, died Thursday. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz became a national figure in the late 1950s, when he won
parole for Leopold, a University of Chicago student convicted in
the 1924 slaying of 14-year-old Bobby Franks. In its time, the case
was called the ''trial of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   He made news again in the early 1960s for defending Miller
against obscenity charges tied to his novel, ''Tropic of Cancer.''
The U.S. Supreme Court ultimately lifted a ban on the book.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz also argued against the death penalty for Jack Ruby, who
was convicted of killing Lee Harvey Oswald, the accused assassin of
President Kennedy. Ruby's death sentence was overturned, but he
died in prison of natural causes in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz was chairman of the Bill of Rights Committee during the
Illinois Constitutional Convention of 1969-1970 and is credited
with including strong civil rights language that became a model for
other states.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz won a libel case in 1983 against the John Birch Society
magazine American Opinion for calling him a ''communist fronter.''
Alfred J. Scalpone:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Alfred J. Scalpone, a former advertising and
television network executive and writer credited with creating the
slogan ''The family that prays together stays together'' died April
21 of congestive heart failure. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Scalpone was a volunteer consultant for Family Theater
Productions, a nonprofit television and radio production company,
for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   He began an advertising career as an office boy with Young and
Rubicam and became a copywriter, script writer and vice president.
He handled such programs as ''The Burns and Allen Show'' and ''The
Fred Astaire Packard Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   He helped create the Armed Forces Radio Service during World War
II. He also was a vice president for radio and television
programming at McCann Erickson, a vice president of CBS Television
in Los Angeles, and vice president at W.R. Grace &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Scalpone is credited in the Oxford Dictionary of Famous
Quotations as the author of the phrases ''The family that prays
together stays together'' and ''A world at prayer is a world at
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Both phrases were written for the Rev. Patrick Peyton, a Roman
Catholic priest who was the producer of the Family Theater weekly
radio series.
Richard S. Shevell:
</P>
<P>
   ATHERTON, Calif. (AP) -- Richard S. Shevell, a retired Stanford
University professor who oversaw the design of the DC-10 aircraft,
died April 21 of lymphoma. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   As an engineer for Douglas Aircraft in the late 1960s, Shevell
oversaw the department that produced the designs for the DC-10,
conceived as a wide-bodied three-engine aircraft capable of making
routine coast-to-coast flights.
</P>
<P>
   Shevell took an academic post at Stanford in 1970, just as the
DC-10 was making its first commercial flights for American
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft became controversial in the 1970s after a series of
crashes and other problems involving a cargo door. Federal Aviation
Administration officials deemed it safe in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 446 DC-10s were built before the model was taken out of
production in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Shevell wrote the 1983 textbook ''Fundamentals of Flight,''
which is still used at Stanford and other universities.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Douglas Aircraft in 1942 and worked there for 28
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
