<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murdoch Confidante Ron Boland Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Newspaperman Ron Boland, who helped
Rupert Murdoch build one of the world's largest media empires, has
died. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Boland died Wednesday, the company said. He was hospitalized
after suffering a stroke a few days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ron lived and breathed newspapers,'' Murdoch said in a
statement. ''Not only was he a dear friend, but he played a
critical role in the formation and ultimate success of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Boland was editor of Adelaide's The Sunday Mail when Murdoch
inherited it and its sister publication, the daily tabloid the
News, in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   They were Murdoch's first papers, his training ground and the
starting point from which he built his global newspaper, satellite
television, film and book publishing company.
</P>
<P>
   Boland was managing editor at the News in 1960, when the
ambitious young Murdoch bought the Sydney Mirror, his first
acquisition and a tenacious bid to break into the highly
competitive Sydney market.
</P>
<P>
   It paid off, and boldness and high-risk ventures became
Murdoch's trademarks as he built his empire, which now includes the
Fox Entertainment group, the New York Post and the London Times.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
