<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pushes for Belfast Accord  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The British and Irish
governments on Thursday invited key Northern Ireland parties to
fresh negotiations that they hope will get the province's suspended
Catholic-Protestant government back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Britain announced plans for a London summit next Tuesday
involving both governments and the Ulster Unionists, the province's
major British Protestant party; the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, the major Catholic-supported party; and Sinn Fein, the party
linked to the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   All three parties briefly shared power in a Cabinet aimed at
serving as the bedrock for a lasting peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists agreed to take part only on condition that
the IRA began disarming in response and, when the outlawed group
refused, Britain suspended the Cabinet's powers and resumed direct
control in February.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the British and Irish governments have pressed both
Sinn Fein and the Ulster Unionists to reach a fresh understanding
that would allow the Cabinet to regain authority.
</P>
<P>
   But Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble has come under
increasing internal pressure not to resume any arrangements with
Sinn Fein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
