<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Cycling Sprint Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas (AP) -- Jennie Reed and Tanya Lindenmuth have
waited all year for a rematch. They can wait another night.
</P>
<P>
   Reed and Lindenmuth, who raced in the women's match sprint final
in last year's national championships, advanced again in the same
race Thursday night in the U.S. Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   However, their showdown was postponed when the temperature
dropped and dew formed on the track. The danger was apparent when a
rider slipped and crashed in a men's sprint qualifying heat. He
wasn't injured.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended events will be staged Friday, including the men's
points race final and the rematch of Lindenmuth's championship
sprint victory over Reed at last year's national meet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was warmed up and ready to go,'' said the 22-year-old Reed
of Kirkland, Wash., who lost her 1998 national title to Lindenmuth,
22, of Trexlertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The two are familiar foes, and it's likely they'll duel over the
next three months for a ticket to the Sydney Olympics. Under this
year's selection process, coaches will pick the team based on
training and racing performances.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too bad they can't race tonight,'' U.S. sprint coach Des
Dickey said. ''It would have been the first bullet fired.
Everything between them this summer, every competition, is going to
be a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindenmuth survived an exciting semifinal against Tammy Thomas
of Yazoo City, Miss. In match sprint, riders position themselves
for a final lap sprint while trying to disrupt the other cyclist's
positioning.
</P>
<P>
   Lindenmuth beat Thomas in the first race in the best-of-three
format. In the second, Thomas took an early lead and had Lindenmuth
boxed out as they turned for the homestretch, but Lindenmuth
charged hard and won at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was tough,'' Lindenmuth said. ''My coach was pleased with
the fact that I didn't panic. Usually when you're matched up well
with someone, the person who makes one move wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the morning preliminaries came from Jame Carney
of Flagstaff, Ariz., the four-time national champion in the points
race who dominated to win the first of two heats.
</P>
<P>
   In the points race, riders accumulate points during sprints on
designated laps. The winner is the cyclist who scores highest or,
as Carney did, laps the field and maintains the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Carney has excelled at the race during his career and probably
would have raced at the Atlanta Olympics if not for a fall during a
promotional photo shoot in 1995. He lost 30 percent of his upper
lip in the face-first crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pretty much looking like Freddie Krueger,'' Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   The dangers of bicycle racing were evident in a match sprint
race Thursday when Suzanne Marshall of Redwood City, Calif.,
clipped wheels with Shan Rayray of Federal Way, Wash., on the
Superdrome's 44-degree banked turn.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred more than one hour before dew condensed on
the track.
</P>
<P>
   Both riders tumbled about 10 feet in a near-vertical fall to the
concrete apron. After Rayray lay motionless for five minutes, she
was immobilized on a back board and carted away to a waiting
ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   A precautionary examination revealed no injuries and she was
expected to race again before the trials conclude Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Cycling team site: http://www.usacycling.org
</P>
<P>
   Superdrome track site: http://www.superdrome.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
