<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Release of Columbine Tapes Defended  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE VOGT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Widely criticized for releasing a graphic
videotape of the Columbine aftermath, the Jefferson County attorney
said Thursday officials did not want to make the tape public but
had no choice after a judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Attorney Frank Hutfless said the decision was
prompted by threats of legal action and reports that the tape had
been given to a television network.
</P>
<P>
   Hutfless also defended the musical soundtrack and the $25 cost
of the tape. He said the fee covers the county's costs and the
music had to be included because it was on the videotape viewed by
the judge.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Hutfless said he and Sheriff John Stone fought
the release because it ''was not in the best interest of the
victims or the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said officials were told the tape had already been given
to the media, and a judge had ruled there was ''no compelling
public interest'' to withhold it under the Colorado Open Records
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ''We simply had no choice but to release the videotapes. If we
did not release them, there would have been more lawsuits asking
for their release and we would have lost,'' Hutfless said.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly three-hour tape produced by the Littleton Fire
Department was given to victims' families Tuesday after they told a
judge they needed them for civil lawsuits against the sheriff's
office. They have sued over officers' handling of the April 20,
1999, attack on the school that left 15 dead, including two teen
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was released to the public Wednesday, eight days after
the first anniversary of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims' families were outraged by the music added to part
of the tape, which included songs by Sarah McLachlan and Cheryl
Wheeler. They said the music was inappropriate for a training
video.
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan and her record label, Arista Records, demanded that
the music be removed from the tape, calling it exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   Hutfless said authorities couldn't remove the music because they
were ordered to hand over the exact tape reviewed by Jefferson
County District Judge Brook Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had we edited out the music, we would have in effect tampered
with the videotape and violated the judge's order,'' Hutfless said.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County sold all 107 copies it had by noon Thursday,
spokeswoman Michelle Frongillo said. Nearly 400 more copies have
been ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Hutfless said the $25 fee covers only the county's cost of
getting the videotapes copied and distributing them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-27-00 2310 </TRAILER>
