<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACLU, Philadelphia Agree on Protests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The American Civil Liberties Union and the
city have reached an agreement to allow large demonstrations before
the Republican National Convention this summer, but the
convention's host committee must still approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''This city, thankfully, recognizes that dissent is an integral
part of our democracy,'' ACLU legal director Stephan Presser said
Thursday. ''This city recognizes that we, in fact, are the
birthplace of the American democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is contingent on the approval of Philadelphia
2000, host committee for the July 31-Aug. 3 convention. Co-chairman
David Cohen said he has asked the city to clarify some logistical
issues, and expects the agreement will be approved once those are
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Presser earlier threatened to sue if city officials did not
approve a demonstration permit by next month for the Pennsylvania
Consumer Action Network, which is leading the creation of an
anti-Republican coalition named ''R2K'' that hopes to coordinate a
mass rally.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the city will allow a rally July 29 on
Washington Square. The next day, a parade will be allowed from a
park near City Hall up the Benjamin Franklin Parkway, a major
thoroughfare downtown, for a crowd of up to 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The rally would be several miles from the First Union Center,
the convention's main site, but would be close to many secondary
events associated with the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
