<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP, Time Receive Press Club Honors  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Associated Press and Time magazine each won
two awards from the Overseas Press Club on Thursday, Time for its
coverage of Indonesia and East Timor and the AP for its Pulitzer
Prize-winning story on an alleged massacre by U.S. troops during
the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Louis D. Boccardi, AP's president and CEO, also received the
club's President's Award for lifetime achievement. The club cited
Boccardi's success in moving the news cooperative into television
and digital photography and his leadership on freedom of
information and First Amendment issues.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the award, Boccardi said it was ''a very special
honor. ... I accept it on behalf of legions of AP people who ...
have dedicated themselves to reporting the news, no matter what it
takes. Sometimes it takes all there is -- safety, health, even their
very lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi cited the courage of an AP photographer jailed in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obed Zilwa ... sits in a jail cell in Zimbabwe, accused of
planting a bomb that he merely photographed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four AP journalists -- Special Correspondent Charles J. Hanley,
reporters Martha Mendoza and Sang-hun Choe, and investigative
researcher Randy Herschaft -- won for breaking the story of the
alleged massacre at No Gun Ri. The press club honored the piece for
best reporting in any medium showing a concern for the human
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The story cited a dozen American veterans who confirmed the
charges some Koreans had been making for years that U.S. soldiers
machine-gunned hundreds of Korean refugees at the hamlet in July
1950, including many cowering under a railroad bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Photographer John Stanmeyer, working through Saba Press Photos
for Time magazine, was honored in the category of best photographic
reporting requiring exceptional courage for the images he captured
of Indonesian police killing an independence supporter in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   John Colmey, David Liebhold and Time's Asia staff won best
magazine business reporting for writing about the vast fortune of
deposed Indonesian President Suharto and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo coverage dominated the remaining Overseas Press Club
awards, presented by Mike Wallace of CBS' ''60 Minutes'' on
Thursday. Award winners included:
</P>
<P>
   --Gilles Peress of Magnum Photos for The New Yorker magazine,
best photographic reporting in magazines, Kosovo refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   --Yannis Behrakis of Reuters, best photographic reporting in
newspapers or wire services, images of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --National Public Radio, radio news or interpretation, Kosovo
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   --''NBC Nightly News'' journalists Ron Allen, Bob Faw, Martin
Fletcher, Dana Lewis and Kerry Sanders, best television spot news,
Kosovo bombing.
</P>
<P>
   --Rod Nordland of Newsweek, best magazine reporting, massacre of
an Albanian family in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --Charles Madigan and Colin McMahon of the Chicago Tribune, best
print reporting dealing with human rights, massacre of 64 ethnic
Albanian Kosovars by Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   --David Filipov of The Boston Globe, best newspaper or wire
service reporting, war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   --Mark Schoofs of The Village Voice, best newspaper or wire
service interpretation of foreign affairs, ''AIDS: The Agony of
Africa'' series, which also won a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   --Sherry Jones of Washington Media Associates and David Fanning
and Michael Sullivan of Frontline/WGBH Boston, best television
documentary or interpretation for a piece, Asian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   --Rob Rogers of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, cartoons on foreign
news, Russian attacks on Chechnya and mistaken U.S. bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   --Anita Raghavan and The Wall Street Journal staff, best business
reporting in newspapers or wire services, series on mergers and
acquisitions in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   --Jocelyn Ford and J.J. Yore of Marketplace Productions, best
business broadcast reporting, ''Reports from a Tokyo Barstool.''
</P>
<P>
   --New York Times columnist Thomas Friedman, best nonfiction book
on foreign affairs, ''The Lexus and the Olive Tree: Understanding
Globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   --Diane Sawyer and Catherine Harrington of ABC News ''20/20'',
best broadcast report dealing with human rights, neglect in Russian
orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   --David Talbot of the Boston Herald, best reporting on
environmental issues, pollution by oil development in Ecuador and
its impact on Secoya Indian culture.
</P>
<P>
   --Sebastian Rotella of the Los Angeles Times, best reporting on
Latin America, failure of Latin American judicial systems.
</P>
